abstract: Staten Island; Rev. R. A. Quinn Shot by Sailor
snippet: Staten Island; Rev. R. A. Quinn Shot by Sailor
lead_paragraph: At 9 o'clock yesterday morning a most atrocious homicide was committed at the Sailors' Snug Harbor, Staten Island, under the following circumstances: The chaplain of the Institution, Rev. ROBT. A. QUINN, had been holding religious services in the Sailors' Chapel, and was on his return home, when a sailor named HERMAN INGALLS, who was standing near the corner of the main building, confronted him saying: "You'll expose me, I know you will, if you live," and immediately drew from his breast-pocket a double-barreled pistol and fired at Mr. QUINN. The ball entered his left breast immediately under the heart, and after reeling for a few seconds, Mr. QUINN dropped dead, exclaiming. "I'm shot! I'm shot!"

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, the joint resolution tendering the thanks of Congress to Commander WORDEN, was passed. A joint resolution was also reported, tendering thanks to other naval officers, but with an amendment limiting such votes in the future to those who shall command expeditions, or be engaged on some special service. It was passed. The bill to increase the salary of the Chief Clerk of the Paymaster's Department to $2,500 per annum was lost.
lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the joint resolution tendering the thanks of Congress to Commander WORDEN, was passed. A joint resolution was also reported, tendering thanks to other naval officers, but with an amendment limiting such votes in the future to those who shall command expeditions, or be engaged on some special service. It was passed. The bill to increase the salary of the Chief Clerk of the Paymaster's Department to $2,500 per annum was lost. The resolution requesting the President to transmit to the Senate the orders, &c., regarding the exportation of articles contraband of war to Mexico, for the use of the French, was adopted. The Consular and Diplomatic Appropriation bill was passed. The Legislative, Executive and Judicial Appropriation bill was then considered until the adjournment.

abstract: Engineering, How to Improve our
snippet: Engineering, How to Improve our
lead_paragraph: If the public continued to admire our slow and rolling official "tubs" upon the advent of the Alabama, they will at least admit, in view of the Florida, that the engineering knowledge of the world is not centred in our official Bureaux. And where the Europeans, abandoning cast-iron ordnance, are firing 10 1/2 and 13-inch shot, with 50, 75 and 90 pounds of powder, out of steel and wrought-iron guns, while our own Government, neglecting better processes and materials for fabricating such guns than the Europeans possess, are to-day inviting proposals for more cast-iron 11-inch Dahlgrens, to stand a maximum charge of 25 pounds, and a fighting charge (the Monitor against the Merrimac) of 15 pounds, the public will be desirous of ascertaining some means by which outside knowledge and success can be made available. It will no longer answer to declare that a fast vessel is inadequate for successful cruising and fighting -- that "everything is sacrificed for speed." The Alabama and the Florida are triumphant evidences to the contrary. Nor will men any longer believe that heavy shot at low velocities will best destroy iron-clads, when the Government is already abandoning 15-inch guns and ordering 13-inch guns, for the purpose of firing lighter shot at a higher velocity -- and that, after their own carefully guarded but by no means concealed experiments on iron targets.

abstract: Report of Army of Virginia Campaign
snippet: Report of Army of Virginia Campaign
lead_paragraph: -- We publish this morning the full official report of Gen. POPE's campaign in Virginia in August last. The public interest in the facts of this campaign is still nearly as lively as ever, and we doubt not that this expose of its history by the General in command will be read universally. It was quite impossible either to get or give the facts about POPE's Virginia operations while in progress, as both the telegraph and the Press were then under the most rigid censorship, and almost everything that the War Department furnished for publication was unreliable, and had to be corrected in the light of subsequent revelations. Gen. POPE's report clears up many points that were then dark, and unravels many intricacies then beyond the skill of the sharpest. There are also in the report many facts which could not safely be published at the time, nor for some time after, such as the strength and location of various military columns, and the work assigned them to do.

abstract: Speech at New-Orleans on Slavery
snippet: Speech at New-Orleans on Slavery
lead_paragraph: -- "We cannot help sympathizing with Rip Van Winkle sometimes now-a-days. Every now and then we learn of occurrences, and hear them spoken of in the most indifferent way, which but a short time ago would have sent a thrill over the Continent. Changes take place so rapidly, and such great changes too, that we sometimes almost feel as if we too must have fallen into Rip Van Winkle's trance, and have newly awaked with the thunder still in our ears of those ninepin balls which echoed through the valleys of the Katskills as he sank to sleep. But it is only the thunder of the omnibuses on Broadway, as we find when we gather our thoughts about us, -- one of the old familiar sounds which show us that here at least some things remain as they were but a few years ago. How much stronger must this feeling be to those who live at the South. There changes have been so great and so swift that men might well find difficulty in recognizing themselves. What fancy was wild enough to imagine five years ago such things as now are there living facts.

abstract: Emperor, the, and his organ. La France
snippet: Emperor, the, and his organ. La France
lead_paragraph: "A little knowledge" has been pronounced "a dangerous thing," but a journalistic organ, whether for Emperor or President, seems to be still more so. The sternest Jehu cannot prevent these redactorial hacks from occasionally kicking over the traces, and involving their patrons in an awkward dilemma. Because of their position, every absurdity to which these semi-official journalists give utterance, is either ascribed to their masters, or assumed to have their sanction and approval. On account of being once in a while inspired, their readers imagine that they are invariably under the influence of the "divine afflatus." The erroneousness of this opinion, however, is exemplified by the recent indiscretion of NAPOLEON's new organ, La Nation.

abstract: The news from Fortress Monroe, this morning, is important. The rebels under Gen. PRYOR advanced across the Blackwater on Friday, and made a demonstration with artillery on Gen. PECK'S advanced Brigades. Our forces were immediately disposed to meet them, and advancing, drove PRYOR back again across the Blackwater, in the direction of Franklin. The fighting appears to have been quite brisk, and resulted in a loss to us of some 100 men killed and wounded.
lead_paragraph: The news from Fortress Monroe, this morning, is important. The rebels under Gen. PRYOR advanced across the Blackwater on Friday, and made a demonstration with artillery on Gen. PECK's advanced Brigades. Our forces were immediately disposed to meet them, and advancing, drove PRYOR back again across the Blackwater, in the direction of Franklin. The fighting appears to have been quite brisk, and resulted in a loss to us of some 100 men killed and wounded. The rebel loss is not known, but some prisoners were captured. A dispatch from Quartermaster KIRKER states that CORCORAN's Brigade was in the fight, and that the General and other officers came out safe.

lead_paragraph: The harbor at Galveston is so shallow that none of our steamers could fill their bunkers, hence frequent recourse to our coal ship for supplies was neccessary. The Westfield, on attempting to return during the night to the defence of the wharf where the Massachusetts troops had been landed, run aground. This was the prime cause of our misfortune. The Lane signaled at 3 o'clock A.M., "the enemy are afloat." The distance from us to her was about three miles. The Clifton went immediately to the assistance of the Westfield, and tried in vain, and too long, to get her off, while we steamed directly up toward the Lane. The rebels, as we afterward learned, had come down in force with about thirty guns from four to nine inches bore, and with 7,000 troops, and occupied the city. We engaged their guns, and soon silenced them. While coming down the Bay we saw three steamers steering for the Lane, who was holding our old position while we were gone for coal. One of the steamers endeavored to ram the Lane, but she yawed, and the steamer shot past her. Another steamer attempted the same play on the opposite side, and with the same result as before, only this time the Lane, on avoiding her enemy, got aground. They immediately closed in upon her, pouring a flood of musketry fire on her decks, and in a moment not a man was left to defence her -- all being either [???]e[???] or badly wounded. While this engagement was going on, we were steaming up the c[???]n[???] with the intention of ramming the steamers; but when within 200 feet, we ran aground, and they, turning their attention to us, swept the men from our [???]ns, and strewed our decks with the dead and dying.

abstract: It will doubtless be very interesting to the public to know something of the arrangements made in this City and in Brooklyn, for the care and medical treatment of our brave Union soldiers who have received their injuries on so many glorious battle-fields. We frequently hear of great battles, then of hundreds of sick and wounded brought to the different cities of the Union. Nothing is of more importance than that all of these should be well provided for, and the provisions necessary to afford comfort and accommodation to the vast numbers who sometimes need to be cared for are sometimes on a very vast scale. In the public and Governmental hospitals the attendant expenses are borne by the public Treasury, but in the case of private hospitals there is always room for the exercise of popular benevolence, which the citizens of the Republic are never backward in evincing to those who, like our wounded soldiers, so well deserve it.

abstract: By the arrival at this port of the steamship Australasian, we receive advices from Europe four days later. She left Liverpool on the 17th, and Queenstown on the 18th ultimo. The political news, generally, is not of much importance. Some idea of the intentions and expectations of the Emperor of the French in invading Mexico, may be gathered from a letter addressed by him to Gen. FOREY, commanding the French forces in Mexico, and just published among other diplomatic correspondence in the "Yellow Book." The purpose of establishing French influence in the heart of America is openly proclaimed. A letter is published from Archbishop WHATELEY, of Dublin, to Mrs. HARRIET BEECHER STOWE, in regard to the Slavery question and British sentiment in general upon America. Mr. LAING, former Chancellor of the Exchequer for India, in a letter to the Times, on the cotton supply, says: "Lancashire may be kept on half rations, and saved from absolute starvation during the next two years by Indian Cotton, but effectual and speedy relief can only come from America." The Liverpool Cotton market was comparatively quiet. Breadstuffs were steady, and Provisions dull. The death of HORACE VERNET, the French painter, is announced.

lead_paragraph: The object, for the accomplishing of which the Order of Sons of Temperance was organized, is too well known to the readers of the TIMES to require explanation now. The object in publishing this brief statement is simply to give information of the present condition and prospects of the Order, as may be of interest to all who are friendly to the cause of temperance and humanity, such information having been collated from reports of the Grand Divisions, made to be presented to the National Division. The Order, as is known, is a secret one, but such only to the extent which has been deemed necessary to protect the Divisions from impositions by such as have not entitled themselves to its privileges or its benefits. As at present organized, there are three grades, so to speak, to which members belong, to wit: Subordinate Divisions, which are organized in towns and villages, wherever there are enough total abstinence men to form them; Grand Divisions, composed of members of Subordinate Divisions who have been officers. These Divisions generally represent States. Territories or Provinces -- New-York being the only State in which there are two Grand Divisions, one representing Eastern and the other Western New-York; and a National Division, composed of representatives from the Grand Divisions, and the highest authority in the Order.

abstract: The recovery of Signor BRIGNOLI enables Mr. GRAU to commence a short season of Italian opera at the Academy of Music this evening, when FLOTOW's popular opera of "Martha" will be given. The cast in all respects is unexceptionable. In the part of Lady Henrietta, Miss KELLOGG has already won one of her best successes, and we may hope that Mlle. MORENSI will also deserve the approbation of the public as Lady Nancy, which part she will essay for the first time. Signors BRIGNOLI and SUSINI are excellent in their several roles, and the orchestra and chorus will, we are assured, be up to the best standard of the establishment. Mr. GRAU's season is limited by various circumstances, one of the most important being that he must appear with his troupe in Boston on Monday next. It follows, therefore, that the present week is the last we shall have of opera until Mr. MARETZEK's arrival. Mr. GRAU's announcements are always satisfactory, but we should like to know why he has omitted from these gala performances MEYERBEER's charming opera of "Dinorah" -- a work which was unwisely withdrawn just as its merits were beginning to be recognized. We trust that Mr. GRAU will see the advantage of playing this on Friday evening, instead of "Don Giovanni," which can hardly be prepared in so short a season.

abstract: The Northern auxiliaries of JEFF. DAVIS must soon give up their bush-fighting. It has served them a good turn. They owe to it all their success hitherto. But it could not last. No sort of bushwhacking ever does. People come to understand it, and when it is understood there is an end of it. Counterfeited flags, stolen uniforms, false alarms, decoys, traps, ambuscades, doublings on the track, and all the other means of deception, known to the political guerrilla quite as well as to any other, after a while -- especially in earnest times like these -- lose their effect. There is no alternative, then, but to take a little more courage, and change to regular warfare. This transition is now going on. These rebel allies are gathering fresh boldness every day, and are fast ranging themselves under their true colors in the open field. We may expect straightforward battle from them soon. It will be this political battle, quite as much as any other, that will decide the fate of the Union.
lead_paragraph: The Northern auxiliaries of JEFF. DAVIS must soon give up their bush-fighting. It has served them a good turn. They owe to it all their success hitherto. But it could not last. No sort of bushwhacking ever does. People come to understand it, and when it is understood there is an end of it. Counterfeited flags, stolen uniforms, false alarms, decoys, traps, ambuscades, doublings on the track, and all the other means of deception, known to the political guerrilla quite as well as to any other, after a while -- especially in earnest times like these -- lose their effect. There is no alternative, then, but to take a little more courage, and change to regular warfare. This transition is now going on. These rebel allies are gathering fresh boldness every day, and are fast ranging themselves under their true colors in the open field. We may expect straightforward battle from them soon. It will be this political battle, quite as much as any other, that will decide the fate of the Union.

snippet: Braddon, M. E.; Lady Audley's Secret
lead_paragraph: So many novels have been published of late, that they deserve a chapter for themselves, from which all mention of so[???]rer books shall be rigorously excluded. Hitherto the law of compensation has been faithfully observed by our publishers; one day a religious book would make its appearance and the next day a secular one; now a book of hymns and anon a choice selection from the melodies of the negro minstrels; so the balance was kept even. They have changed all that. Sober works are no longer in demand. It is a day of sensations. The popular taste clamors for a Wilkie Collins, a Sylvanus Cobb, or a Bishop Colenso. Anything will answer, so it lifts the mind out from the lurid and unpleasant light of surrounding realities into the golden mists of fiction, or deadens the senses, by the wild throbbings of the higher excitement it evokes, to the sad, stern voices that on every side call out from the Present. As soon as a novel appears on the other side of the water, if it only answers the exciting or soporific conditions demanded, it is reprinted on this, and in some cases fabulous sums are paid -- or said to be paid -- for the advance proof-sheets of the work.

The building was formerly used as a concert saloon and gymnasium. It has recently been rearranged and fitted up for the above Association, and is now one of the finest and most capacious halls in the city. Societies Nos. 1 and 2 of Brooklyn, and No. 2 of New-York, assembled about 2 o'clock P.M., and, preceded by two bands of music, marched through Fulton street. Court-street, Atlantic-street, Fulton-avenue, Bridge-street, Hudson-avenue, Little-street, John-street, York and Main streets, back to the Hall. The members all appeared in full regalia, and presented a very good appearance. The procession numbered about 300 men. After returning to the Hall the Societies were dismissed.

abstract: NEW TELEGRAPH ENTERPRISE. The Independent Telegraph Company having completed the extension of their line to Philadelphia, have laid across the North River a large and substantial cable probably the largest and best cable ever made in the United States. It is composed of four conductors of No. 14 copper wire, each one coated with gutta percha  three coatings 5-16 inches in diameter outside, and each strand wound with fine jute, well tarred.
lead_paragraph: NEW TELEGRAPH ENTERPRISE. -- The Independent Telegraph Company having completed the extension of their line to Philadelphia, have laid across the North River a large and substantial cable -- probably the largest and best cable ever made in the United States. It is composed of four conductors of No. 14 copper wire, each one coated with gutta percha -- three coatings 5-16 inches in diameter outside, and each strand wound with fine jute, well tarred. The four conductors thus prepared are then laid up like a rope, with lateral strands of hemp between each, and the whole wound with two-thread Manila yarn, and well tarred; over this is placed 26 No. 9 galvanized iron wires, and then bound around with No. 9 galvanized wire, thus forming a complete shield for the core. The weight is about seven tons per mile -- length one mile. This cable was manufactured by the Bishop Gutta Percha Company, of this City, and was laid by Col. SPEED, President of the Line, assisted by Mr. MARKS, the foreman of the Gutta Percha Works. The line will be in working condition to Philadelphia in a few days.

abstract: the new Bill
snippet: the new Bill
lead_paragraph: Postal laws should be changed or tinkered as little and as seldom as possible. If there is anything in which simplicity, uniformity and permanence are required, it is in those business matters in which the great mass of common people have daily transactions. Our postal system, though it is improved, or at least altered, in some of its details, at almost every session of Congress, is greatly deficient in these respects. The main reason of this undoubtedly is, that the matter has been in the hands of men who had no practical or extended acquaintance with the workings of the postage system. A bill, however, has just been introduced into the Senate which covers the whole ground, and which has recommendations far superior to any existing general law upon the subject. The bill was drawn up and introduced by Senator COLLAMER, who brought to the work his great experience acquired when Postmaster-General, and it is understood that he was aided by the present Postmaster-General and the other experienced functionaries of the Department.

abstract: Emperor, the, A???al of Purpose toward Mexico
snippet: Emperor, the, A???al of Purpose toward Mexico
lead_paragraph: It has pleased His Majesty the Emperor of the French to publish to the world a letter from his own pen to the commander of the French forces in Mexico, setting forth the reasons of his invasion of that country, and the advantages he expects to gain by it. The Imperial document is most certainly an astonishing one, and was not put forward at this moment without a design. The Emperor boldly avows his main objects in occupying the soil of Mexico with a military force to be to limit the territorial expansion of the United States, and to establish in Mexico either a monarchy, or, at all events, a Government which promises some stability.

abstract: Mexican affairs in Europe
snippet: Mexican affairs in Europe
lead_paragraph: The European invasion of Mexico may be said to have reached its second phase. In its first phase we saw the falling to pieces of the cumbersome, complicated tripartite coalition the moment its expeditionary forces touched the Mexican shores. Criminations and recriminations between the three invading Powers followed, and the Quixotic attempt of the French to stand in the breach and redress the grievances of all creation in Mexico -- as they pretended -- failed. With the defeat of the French before Puebla, in May last, every vestige of the tripartite coalition between England, France and Spain disappeared.

abstract: Virginia Extortion Prevention Bill
snippet: Virginia Extortion Prevention Bill
lead_paragraph: - There is a bill, designated the "Extortion Bill" now before the Virginia Legislature, in session in Richmond, the object of which is to limit and define the profits of merchants, traders and dealers generally. The fifth section provides that all articles must be sold at prices not exceeding 200 per cent. over the prices of May. 1861; and one of the speakers, in an elaborate argument upon the bill, submitted a schedule showing the benefit which would be derived from the establishment of this rate, and how vastly present prices would be lessened. The same number of the Richmond paper which contains this debate, has an advertisement in an adjoining column, headed, "No Extortion -- Superior black tea at $8 per pound." This would seem to indicate the truth of the speaker's remarks, just quoted, that the enforcement of the provisions of the Extortion bill would vastly reduce prices. If eight dollars a pound for tea is the "no extortion" prices, how much must the extortioners charge? Probably double that, or a dollar an ounce. If the Extortion bill becomes law, however, and the price of tea be reduced to say three dollars a pound, and other imported articles in proportion, we fear that the motive which induces our English relatives to make such desperate efforts to run the blockade with their cargoes, will be taken away.

lead_paragraph: WENDELL PHILLIPS ON THE "LOST ARTS." -- Whatever varieties of opinion may prevail regarding Mr. PHILLIPS' political views, there is certainly no diversity of sentiment in relation to his masterly skill as an orator. While this fact is admitted by even the most bitter of his political opponents, it is never more apparent than when he drops for the time the political excitements of the hour, and treats his audience to a feast of reason directed to a subject interesting and instructive to any intellectual assemblage -- such a subject as that of his already famous lecture on the Lost Arts. The Mercantile Library Association, therefore, in inviting him to repeat the lecture last evening, but recognized the public appreciation, and afforded to thousands the opportunity for a rare treat of classical eloquence.

abstract: The steamship Ocean Queen arrived at this port last night, from Aspinwall, which port she left on the 25th ult., under convoy of the gunboat Connecticut. She brought but about $306,000 in treasure. The news by this arrival is of no particular importance. Everything on the Isthmus is quiet; nothing later from the interior. An arrival from New-Zealand brings the most wonderful stories regarding the productiveness of the gold mines there. It is alleged that the mines agreed in extent and richness those of Australia and California together. Living and transportation, however, are very dear.

abstract: The Frequent Executions
snippet: The Frequent Executions
lead_paragraph: -- One would think, on looking over the newspapers from different sections of the Confederacy, that the rebel army would get considerably thinned out by the military executions that are continually taking place. Hardly a paper but contains in its local columns accounts of soldiers being shot to death -- generally for desertion. There seems to be no sensation over these executions, either among the people or in the newspapers. The facts are quietly chronicled in three or four lines of small type, as minor incidents of the day. The Richmond Dispatch of Saturday last, for example, says that, "Another military execution took place yesterday at Camp Lee, near Richmond, the party being JOHN MULLIGAN, Fifth Virginia Cavalry, convicted of deserting;" and it adds that "MICHAEL KIERNANS and JAMES BRODERICK, of the Letcher Artillery, will be shot to death with musketry" on Friday of this week for desertion, "The spectacle," coolly adds the Dispatch, "is for the sake of the example." It is a dangerous thing to desert from the rebel army, as military law is there relentlessly enforced.

abstract: A report having gained considerable currency, to the effect that Gen. WOOL had designed to suppress the World and Express, on account of the course they had taken in reference to the policy of the Administration, we are enabled to state, by authoritative assurance, that the intention intimated never proceeded from the headquarters of Gen. WOOL. Various rumors are constantly afloat as to the doings and contemplative acts of Gen. WOOL, but it rarely occurs they can ever be traced to a reliable source.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, a communication was received from the President of the Smithsonian Institute, stating that GEORGE E. BADGER, a Member of the Board of Regents, is in the rebel army, and ought no longer to remain a member. A petition from MADISON Y. JOHNSON was presented by Mr. RICHARDSON, of Illinois, who stated that the petitioner had been arrested, imprisoned and released, without explanation or cause. In the course of discussion. Mr. RICHARDSON admitted that JOHNSON had refused to take the oath of allegiance -- whereupon the petition was laid on the table, 22 to 16. The bill to aid he State of Missouri in emancipation was reported back from the Judiciary Committee. A resolution was adopted inquiring of the Paymaster-General what payments were made up the 31st of August, 1862. The Executive, Legislative and Judicial Appropriation bill was passed, with an amendment appropriating $20,000 for experiments in preparing hemp and flax as substitutes for cotton. An appropriation of $80,000 was made for the Agricultural Department. The Senate then adjourned.

abstract: BROOKLYN ACADEMY OF MUSIC. The brevity of Mr. GRAU'S New-York season, occasioned by the necessity of transferring his company to Boston in time for Monday next, enables the enterprising manager to give but a single supplemental performance in Brooklyn. This will take place to-night, when an unusually attractive programme will be interpreted by the full force of the company. The performances commence with the whole of VERDI'S "Ernani" ...
lead_paragraph: BROOKLYN ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The brevity of Mr. GRAU's New-York season, occasioned by the necessity of transferring his company to Boston in time for Monday next, enables the enterprising manager to give but a single supplemental performance in Brooklyn. This will take place to-night, when an unusually attractive programme will be interpreted by the full force of the company. The performances commence with the whole of VERDI's "Ernani" -- Mme. LORINI sustaining the role of the heroine. After this, an act of "La Traviata," with Mlle. CORDIER, whose remarkable performance of Violetta was one of the memorable pleasures of last season. This is surely a sufficient provision for a night's musical entertainment.

abstract: Last evening the Tweny-fifth Annual Ball of the Brooklyn Fire Department was given in the Academy of Music, as usual in aid of the Widows' and Orphans' Fund of the Fire Department. These annuals of the Department are always looked forward to with yearnings for the arrival of the evening announced as that on which the occasion will take place, and when the time arrives the occasion is enjoyed to the fullest by every fireman who can be there, and by all his family. It differs from the great majority of balls in its genuine sociality. Every one seems to attend with a determination to spend an agreeable evening; and as the proceeds from the sale of tickets ($5 each) all goes to the support of the poor and needy, benevolence, which beams out from the jolly faces of the exempts and past officials, and fills with a charming light the eyes of the ladies and children, wells up the heart of the mere spectator with joy and gladness. Prior to last evening, the trustees and managers had some unpleasant forebodings that the Annual this year would, as compared with others, be less successful. These fears were based on the fact that there is not in the City an organized body of men from which so many soldiers have volunteered for the war as the Fire Department. But their fears, though apparently well founded, were not realized -in fact, the attendance last evening was the largest and best that has ever been seen at an Animal. At 10 o'clock there was not less than two thousand present. The arrangements were perfect; the decoration calculated to attract and please both eyes and ears. At the rear of the stage Engine No. 22 and Hose No. 8 were placed -both splendid specimens of fire apparatus. Over them, and somewhat nearer the front, was, in letters of light, "Voluntary Aid." The front of the stage was ornamented by the appropriate coat of arms, hung from the drop roll, and descending about midway to the stage. The side of the stage and the front of the several circles were hung with American flags, and from every gas pendant there hung a tiny cage, containing a singing canary bird. The dancing music was furnished by the Brooklyn Band, and the promenade music by DODWOTH's, and both were excellent. The floor was covered with gay dancers, and every available seat in the building was filled with those, who though friendly to the object of the occasion, preferred being spectators to taking part in the more active festivities. Altogether it was a grand success, one which will add fully $2,000 to the Widows' and Orphans' Fund. Judging from the number of dancing and promenade pieces on the programme, the happy assemblage will still be dancing when this brief notice shall have gone to press. Among the notables present were the Mayor, Heads of Departments, Aldermen and City Officials generally, Chief Engineer Cunningham, Hon. Jehn C. Roach, Hon. Robert Story, Ex-Chief Velsor, Ex-Chief Fury, and others. The Floor Committee, of twelve prominent firemen, and the Police Committee, of twelve ditto, deserve the highest commendation for the manner in which they performed their several duties.

abstract: The Richmond Dispatch of the 29th ult. announces that on the 27th the Ericsson Monitor Montauk attacked Fort McAllister, at the mouth of the Ogeechee River, but was compelled to haul off, owing to some injury to her turret, though the solid shot fired by the rebels were broken to pieces against her armor.
lead_paragraph: The Richmond Dispatch of the 29th ult. announces that on the 27th the Ericsson Monitor Montauk attacked Fort McAllister, at the mouth of the Ogeechee River, but was compelled to haul off, owing to some injury to her turret, though the solid shot fired by the rebels were broken to pieces against her armor. It is possible that a temporary disarrangment of her turret machinery has caused the Montauk to haul off, though we consider it prudent to wait for our own reports of her operations before placing reliance upon the rebel report.

abstract: The Presentation of Christ in the Temple, commonly called "The Purification of St. Mary the Virgin." was celebrated yesterday in all Episcopal and Catholic Churches throughout the world. According to the law of Moses, (Levit. xii,) twenty-three days were to elapse after the circumcision of a male child, before the mother could enter the sanctuary or touch any hallowed thing. These, together with the seven days from the birth to the circumcision, were called the "Days of Purification." Besides this there was a law that the first born, (male,) both of man and beast, should be offered to the Lord, and in the former case the child was to be redeemed with a lamb, of the first year, and if the parents were too poor to bring a lamb, then they brought "a pair of turtle doves or two young pigeons," one for a burnt-offering, and the other for a sin-offering, and the priest then made an atonement for the mother, and she was pronounced clean. In the case of a "maid child," the "Days of Purification" were doubted. The reputed father, and the mother of our Lord were too poor, it appears, to give the lamb, and accordingly we find them approaching with the more humble offering. But if poor, it was shown at this purification that he who was brought to be presented was the promised Messiah. Simeon, who was not to see death, before he had seen Christ, burst out with that beautiful hymn, since used in the Christian Church, "Lord, now lettest thou thy servant depart in peace according to thy word; for mine eyes have seen thy salvation, which thou [???]ast prepared before the face of all people; a light to lighten the Gentiles, and the glory of thy people, Israel." Yesterday solemn services were performed in all the Catholic Churches in this City, and also in the Protestant Episcopal Churches. In the former the ceremony of blessing candles, before early mass occurred. Pieces of these candles are considered of great efficacy in sickness, or otherwise. When a person is dying, a piece is put in his hand lighted, and thus he passes away in the belief that it may light him to Paradise. On account of these "blessed candles." the day is also called "Candlemas Day." In Ireland the day is particularly observed. The days are now visibly longer, and there is an old distich which runs thus:

abstract: Texas WIGFALL de  livered a speech in the rebel Congress last Wednesday, upon a bill organizing a Supreme Court for the Confederacy. Of course, WIGFALL was slightly excited, rather angry, somewhat personal and defiant in his remarks.
lead_paragraph: -- Texas WIGFALL delivered a speech in the rebel Congress last Wednesday, upon a bill organizing a Supreme Court for the Confederacy. Of course, WIGFALL was slightly excited, rather angry, somewhat personal and defiant in his remarks. He "did not choose to be put in a false position; he intended that he should be understood by the Senator from Georgia; he was bound by oath not to stultify himself; and he was opposed to the provisions of the measure." One of his objections to the bill, however, was rather curious. abstract: their Futility; the Illinois Legislature; North as well as South
snippet: their Futility; the Illinois Legislature; North as well as South
lead_paragraph: Foiled in New-Jersey, they are doing their best to get the Illinois Legislature to lead off with the armistice resolutions. With prospect of good success, it is said. We doubt it. Undeniably, there is no creeping thing of a more creeping nature than an Egyptian Copperhead; still it has something of what BURKE calls "a reptile prudence." It has but recently sloughed off its old Democratic skin, and is tender yet. For a while longer it will simply lie quiet, and spit venom. In due time, perhaps before the snow melts, it will boldly show itself in broad daylight on he high road to Dixie -- secesh not only in hidden sting and fang, but secesh so that the way faring man, though a fool, can see it in every scale. There is no reptile work it will not then be ready for.

lead_paragraph: NEW-JERSEY LEGISLATURE. -- Yesterday, in the Assembly, Thomas DUNN ENGLISH, of Bergen, introduced resolutions, protesting against the appropriation by Congress of $10,000,000 to emancipate slaves in Missouri, and declaring that the people of New-Jersey will never submit to taxation for such purpose. The resolutions were referred to the inevitable Committee on National Relations, who will have a pretty mess to report upon by and bye. A bill will be presented to the Legislature for the incorporation of a company at Newark to be called the Rankin Mills, for the manufacture of cotton, wool, silk, and other fibrous materials, with a capital of $225,000. Prominent capitalists of Newark are connected with the enterprise.

lead_paragraph: Brooklyn, take it all in all, is one of the finest cities in the world. Its hundreds of beautiful streets and avenues, lined on both sides with elegant houses, filled and decorated with every luxury that science can invent or art produce; its public buildings, libraries, opera and churches -- are the pride of its own citizens and the wonder of traveled Manhattanese. Its people, on the average, probably, enjoy a larger share of the good things of this life than falls to the lot of the denizens of any other city on the globe. They are noted for their refinement, for their culture, for their high morality. They are blessed with golden-mouthed preachers, who, in turn, are favored with vaster and sleeker flocks than any other shepherds of this heritage. Their temples so abound that the city has acquired the designation of the "City of Churches." Their charity is wide as the world. Whoever seeks aid for the people of any continent or clime, turns his footsteps first to Brooklyn, assured that the appeal has but to be made, to be generously responded to.

abstract: Ex-Gov. MORGAN was yesterday elected Senator in the Congress of the United States, in place of PRESTON KING, whose term expires with the present session.
lead_paragraph: Ex-Gov. MORGAN was yesterday elected Senator in the Congress of the United States, in place of PRESTON KING, whose term expires with the present session. This result puts a very effective quietus on the predictions of leading Democratic journals just after the last election, that they would either elect a Democrat or throw the election over to another year. Gov. MORGAN is a Republican, and if we may judge the future by the past, will continue to act as the representative of that party. At the same time he is a gentleman of enlarged and liberal views, and has seen enough of public life to appreciate the fact that public service is a practical matter, and as such is inconsistent with an obstinate adherence to favorite theories, regardless of circumstances and under all contingencies.

abstract: We trust that in  the discussions on the Franco-Mexican question, which were opened in the Senate yesterday, and which that body seems disposed to entertain, there will be no unnecessary heat ...
lead_paragraph: -- We trust that in the discussions on the Franco-Mexican question, which were opened in the Senate yesterday, and which that body seems disposed to entertain, there will be no unnecessary heat displayed, and no false charges made against either of the belligerents. The speech of Senator MCDOUGALL, of California, on his Mexican resolutions, was highly unjustifiable. He accused France not only of a design of taking possession of the Mexican States, but of an intention of pushing her conquests further -- of going through Lower California and seizing California, and then of seizing Texas and the more Southern States, and gaining control of the Mississippi River. It is, perhaps, no more improper in Mr. MCDOUGALL to make such charges against France than it was for the French Emperor to make the charge against our Government of a desire to seize Mexico, and dominate the Antilles and South America. But both the charge and the counter-charge are improper, insolent and offensive. The French charge was the most offensive, in that it was official; but Senators also must remember the importance that is put in Europe upon their declarations.

abstract: Speech at Brooklyn on Our Future
snippet: Speech at Brooklyn on Our Future
lead_paragraph: A full house and WENDELL PHILLIPS have been seen and heard together for so many years, that a moderate assemblage at any place where he had been announced to speak, would be matter of surprise, and would warrant a lengthy notice. But the audience last evening at Plymouth Church was not a moderate one in any sense. The church was literally crammed, at 7 o'clock, although it had been advertised that the proceedings would not be commenced until 8 o'clock, and all seemed to know that fact, for it was not until the hour hand upon the dial had reached the then most interesting figure upon the dial's face, that the slightest impatience was shown, and that was answered immediately by a voluntary on the organ, followed by the singing of a hymn to liberty, written by Mr. THEODORE TILTON, and which was earnestly and heartily approved. The singing of the hymn concluded, Mr. PHILLIPS appeared upon the platform, accompanied by Mr. TILTON. As soon as the presence of Mr. PHILLIPS was known to the assemblage, he was long and rapturously applauded. When the general enthusiastic demonstrations had partially subsided, Mr. TILTON came forward and spoke substantially as follow:

abstract: -- Under this appropriate title we have a memorial by Rev. HUGH S. CARPENTER, of EMMA WHITING, who died in Brooklyn in June, 1861. It is not a commonplace memoir, but a memorial of rare interest. The person and character sketched by the author, and shadowed forth by judicious selections from her own writings, will touch many of the tenderest sympathetic chords in the heart of the reader. She was at once a child of earth and a child of the skies, and the attractions of the latter proving strongest, she passed away from earth to heaven at the early age of twenty years. The closing chapter, "Life Resumed," is one of great beauty and suggestiveness in regard to another life. The volume is published by CARLETON. -- Independent.

abstract: Mr. McDougall's Senate resolution
snippet: Mr. McDougall's Senate resolution
lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, after the presentation of numerous petitions, and the transaction of some business of minor importance, the Post-office Appropriation bill was reported back from the Finance Committee, and passed. The bill to provide a National currency, secured by United States stocks, was postponed for a week. A bill was passed providing for an Assistant Register of the Treasury Department, and a Solicitor for the War Department. A bill to provide for stopping the pay of unemployed military officers was referred to the Military Committee. Mr. MCDOUGALL's resolutions regarding the operations of the French in Mexico were taken up, after some opposition from Mr. SUMNER, and Mr. MCDOUGALL proceeded to give his views relative to the matter at length. When he had concluded, Mr. SUMNER made a motion to lay the resolutions on the table, pending which the Senate went into Executive session, and subsequently adjourned.

abstract: The Reduction of, Nee ed
snippet: The Reduction of, Nee ed
lead_paragraph: The Secretery of the Treasury has expressed the opinion, in a communication to the Senate, that the reduction of the present duty on imported paper will increase the revenue to the Government. Of this, we presume, no one can entertain any doubt. The revenue from all kinds of imported paper has never exceeded $200,000 a year: -- and not a dollar of this came from the duties on the common qualities of printing paper. Writing paper, wall paper, and some of the most expensive kinds of book paper have sometimes been imported. But we presume that for the last ten years not a dollar has been derived by the Government from duties on paper used for newspapers, simply because, under these duties, no such paper has been imported.

abstract: McDougal, Sen., and his resolution against France
snippet: McDougal, Sen., and his resolution against France
lead_paragraph: The denunciatory resolutions directed against France, which Mr. MCDOUGALL, has been pressing on the attention of the Senate, were tabled yesterday by a vote of four to one. There never was anything to be gained, since our troubles began, by official railing or menace against foreign Powers; and there is now less than ever. If LOUIS NAPOLEON sees that we are weak, or divided, or faltering, nothing that we say will cause him to alter one tittle of his plans. If he sees that we are united and determined and strong, in the enterprise we have now on hand, neither speeches nor resolutions will be necessary to induce him to let us alone.

abstract: A flaming rebel account comes to us from Charleston, of an attach by two gunboats the Chicora and Palmetto State accompanied by three small steamers, upon our blockading fleet outside, in which if we may believe the story as told by the rebels two National gunboats were sunk, another crippled, and the whole blockading fleet dispersed. All this occurred on the 31st...
lead_paragraph: A flaming rebel account comes to us from Charleston, of an attach by two gunboats -- the Chicora and Palmetto State -- accompanied by three small steamers, upon our blockading fleet outside, in which -- if we may believe the story as told by the rebels -- two National gunboats were sunk, another crippled, and the whole blockading fleet dispersed. All this occurred on the 31st ult., about 4 o'clock in the morning. The rebel fleet was commanded by Commodore INGRAHAM, who was on board the Palmetto Slate. He attacked the Mercedita and sunk her, and all on board are supposed to have perished, with the exception of Capt. STELLWAGEN and a boat's crew. There is a vague report of another gunboat having been sunk, and a number set on fire; but it appears to have very little foundation. All this accomplished the rebel fleet returned to Charleston, and reported the entire blockading fleet destroyed or driven off, and a joint proclamation was issued by BEAUREGARD and INGRAHAM, as commanders respectively of the land and naval forces, declaring the blockade raised. It appears, however, hat on the same evening some of our blockading vessels were again discovered outside, and the text morning some twenty vessels were off the bar -- so the raising of the blockade was only for a very brief period. Indeed, the whole rebel story bears evidence of the most gross exaggeration. In connection with this subject it may not be inappropriate to state, that the Navy Department yesterday ordered the iron-clads Keokuk Catskill, Nantucket and Sangamon to be got ready for sea at once, and to proceed South.

abstract: TO BE PAID IN GOLD OR ITS EQUIVALENT. -- The Canard, the Liverpool, New-York and Philadelphia, the Hamburg Packet Company, and the Bremen lines have decided to make the passage money payable in gold or its equivalent in currency. The buyer of a passage ticket, on the Edinburgh, for instance, which sails on Saturday for Liverpool, will have to pay $80 in gold -- the equivalent of which in currency depreciated fifty per cent., as is now the case, is $120 -- and should gold ever rise to one hundred per cent, premium, the buyer of a passage ticket will have to pay one hundred and sixty paper dollars -- just double the nominal price of passage. Foreign travel, however, is now very restricted, the ruinous rates of Exchange preventing many from going abroad who would otherwise do so.

abstract: An older, issued a few weeks since by Gen. WOOL, calling upon citizens to aid the military authorities in apprehending deserters from the army, has not, it appears, been fully appreciated by the parties whose interest it was intended to enlist. Instead of exhibiting their loyalty by showing a disposition to bring deserters to the notice of the proper authorities, some persons are constantly exerting themselves to the utmost to screen the base cowards, who have pocketed their bounty money, thrown away their arms, and ignominiously sought a clandestine retreat. The purport of the order is obvious, and does not require any explanation additional to that which has already been given. It is a matter of surprise that parties, ostensibly heart and band with Gen. WOOL in the rigid enforcement of his order pertaining to the apprehension of deserters, should seek to throw any obstacle in the course indicated for a speedy and effective accomplishment of that object. It is known that numerous deserters are quietly and unmolestedly availing themselves of the hospitality of their friends in this City, to say nothing of the deserters who have sought and obtained refuge in the New-England States.

abstract: Maj.-Gen. Ambrose E. Burnside, and wife, accompanied by his Staff, arrived in this City from Providence, R.I., via New-York and New-Haven line of steamboats, about 8 o'clock yesterday morning, and proceeded directly to the Fifth-avenue Hotel, where apartments were in readiness for their reception. The General left this City again last evening by the 11.30 P.M. train for Washington, at which place he is summoned to appear as a witness in Gen. Franklin's trial, which is now in progress in that city. Mrs. Burnside did not accompany her husband to Washington, but will remain in this City until his return. Gen. Burnside and wife, during yesterday, attended the wending ceremonies consequent upon the marriage of Major Ed. M. Neill, (one of the members of the General's Staff, to a Miss Stuyvesant, of this City.

abstract: To skate or not to skate, that is the question. Whether 'tis better to endure the dilatory action of the Central Park Commissioners and the Fifth-avenue Pond proprietors, who persistently refused yesterday to let the people skate, or to take skates and overcoats and adjourn to Beekman's Pond or to the frozen regions of Brooklyn and Jersey. That is the question. Who would endure these ills when he himself and his lady-love might their releasement make by means of comfortable ferryboats?

abstract: -- It is gratifying, on many accounts, to find the people of Boston extending so hearty a welcome to Gen. MCCLELLAN. It shows a desire on their part to reward patriotic services by applause, even if they have not been of the most distinguished or decisive character. We are glad, also, to learn, from Gen. MCCLELLAN's own declaration, that he is devoting himself mainly to the preparation of a history of the Peninsular War, while he was in command of the Army of the Potomac. It will doubtless be a valuable work, and will throw light upon an important portion of this great contest with rebellion.

abstract: The extensive cracker bakery of GOODWIN & CO., at the corner of Cherry and Pike streets, was totally destroyed on Tuesday by fire, involving a loss on building, machinery, stock and fixtures, of at least $60,000. The fire broke out about 7 1/2 in the evening, and burned until 10 o'clock. It originated on the third floor, and, from the dry condition of the timber, burned very rapidly. The ovens had been running night and day, and a constant heat was kept up in the building, which rendered the woodwork highly combustible. This is the fifth cracker bakery burned in this City within two months. A vessel lying at foot of Pike-street took fire, but the flames were extinguished but with little damage. HECKER's Mills were also in great danger, but by the exertions of the firemen were saved from burning. The property of Messrs. GOODWIN & CO. is said to be fully insured. About 11 o'clock, one of the walls fell and buried three firemen. JOHN SLOWEY, of Engine Company No. 19 was killed, and GEO. W. BADGER, foreman of the same Company, and THOMAS SWEENY, of Engine Company No. 6, were severely injured.

lead_paragraph: INQUEST UPON THE FIREMAN KILLED AT THE FIRE IN CHERRY-STREET. -- Coroner WILDEY held an inquest upon the body of JOHN SLOWEY, the fireman who was killed by the falling of a chimney at the burning of the cracker bakery corner of Pike-slip and Cherry-street, on Tuesday night. The deceased was a member of Lafayette Engine Company No. 19, and a brother of Detective SLOWEY, of Police Headquarters. At the time of the accident, he was standing on the corner of Pike-slip and South-street, with Mr. CHAMBERS, foreman of Hose Company No. 22. The latter observed that the chimney -- which was a very high one -- was trembling and tottering for a fall, and at once started across the street, at the same time shouting to the deceased to look out for himself, as there was imminent danger from the falling mass of bricks. The latter started after him, but whereabout half-way across the street, he was buried beneath the brick and mortar which composed the chimney, and almost instantly killed. Mr. CHAMBERS reached the opposite side of the street, just at the moment his friend was buried under the ruins. The jury -- which was composed mostly of firemen -- rendered a verdict of "accidental death." The deceased was a native of this State, about 35 years of age, and resided at No. 75 Rivington-street. He held the position of Superintendent of Lands and Places, to which office, he was appointed soon after the death of his predecessor in office, THOMAS BYRNES, who, it will be remembered, came to an untimely death in the First Ward a few weeks since. The deceased kept a public house in Centre-street and was well known among the politicians of this City. The Board of Engineers and Foremen will meet this evening at 8 o'clock, at Fireman's Hall, to take suitable steps regarding the death of Mr. SLOWEY.

abstract: Sturgis vs. Bark Edward; Salvage Agreement
snippet: Sturgis vs. Bark Edward; Salvage Agreement
lead_paragraph: Russell Sturgis vs. The Bark Edward, her Tackle, &c. -- SHIPMAN, J. -- On the morning of the 4th of November, 1861, the bark Edward was lying at anchor off the Highlands below Sandy Hook. She had been on a foreign voyage, and was bound into the port of New-York. In coming into the neighborhood of the Highlands, the wind blowing fresh to the eastward, she crossed a shoal, touched bottom, and carried away her rudder, breaking or pulling out the hanging gear attached to the stern-post. She had ho means of steering, and it does not appear that those on board could repair or supply the loss. The wind had shifted to the westward, and was blowing off shore. She lay at anchor in three or four fathoms of water, in this helpless condition, but in no imminent danger. She had sent a small boat, with the mate, to Sandy Hook for aid, which was met by the libelant's tug, the Achilles.

lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the bill to prevent correspondence with the rebels was reported back from the Judiciary Committee. The joint resolution to revive the act to secure to the officers and men employed in the Department of the West their pay, bounty and pensions, was reported back from the Military Committee. A bill concerning pardons, remission of penalties and forfeitures in criminal cases, was passed. A bill for the sale of certain Indian reservations in California, and for the establishment of new reservations, was referred to the Military Committee. Mr. MCDOUGALL's resolutions, relative to French intervention in Mexico, were laid on the table, 34 to 9. The League Island matter was again referred to the Naval Committee. Mr. WILSON's bill for the encouragement of reenlistments, and for enrolling and drafting the militia, was then considered until the adjournment.

lead_paragraph: THE BROOKLYN POLYTECHNIC. -- The pupils of the Brooklyn Collegiate and Polytechnic Institute propose, on Thursday night, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, to offer to their friends another entertainment, similar to those which, on former occasions, have elicited such enconraging expressions of public approval. The programme will present the accustomed variety of eloquence, wit and pathos, both original and selected, comprising serious and humorous recitations, declamations and colloquies, and enlivened by calisthenic exercises and tableaux, and by choice selections of sacred, national and comic music, including specimens of choral, carol, hymn and song. The concluding piece will be an entirely new comic colloquy, entitled "Fish out of Water." In fixing a price of admission, no mercenary object is sought. This entertainment in no way interferes with the free exhibition of the Institute at the close of the academic year. The time and labor of preparation is contributed gratuitously and cheerfully, and the entire proceeds, after payment of expenses, are applied to the enlargement of the library and the apparatus of the Institute, thus adding to the permanent attractions and advantages of an important public Institution.

abstract: New-York and Washington Railway Connections at; New-York and Washington--Connections at Philadelphia
snippet: New-York and Washington Railway Connections at; New-York and Washington--Connections at Philadelphia
lead_paragraph: The accompanying map of the railways entering Philadelphia will show at a glance how the present annoyance and delay of twice changing cars there, in passing between New-York and Washington, is about to be prevented, without Government aid or interference. During the last Summer, the trains from New-York arriving at Camden were, ferried bodily across the Delaware to the terminus of the Baltimore Railroad. There was, indeed, no changing cars, but great delay, and the boat is not adapted to Winter navigation. At present, the New-York trains, crossing the Delaware at Trenton, do not arrive at Philadelphia at all, but at the ultimate suburb of Kensington, whence the passengers, "breaking bulk." puddle into horse-cars, and by a circuitous route, not laid down on the map. reach the Baltimore Station, and there make another change of conveyance. If there is, indeed, one individual in the North who has not experienced the various sensations incident to this transit of Philadelphia, in the middle of a Winter's night, for instance, we assure him, without fear of contradiction, that they are not seductive.

abstract: Neither the Common Council or the Board of Supervisors have as yet made their appropriations for City and County purposes, respectively, consequently none of the employees in the public offices have received their salaries for the month of January. The Board of Supervisors evince a disposition to pass the appropriations for County purposes at an early day, the Committee on Annual Taxes having already reported an ordinance for that purpose. The Comptroller's estimates for City expenses, which were referred to the Finance Committee of the Board of Aldermen, have not yet been reported upon by them, but probably will be soon. Meanwhile the City officials and their creditors must continue to await, as patiently as they possibly can, the "good time coming," when the City Treasury will be open to them. It should be added, however, that the Supervisors have considerately provided for the Police by passing that portion of the annual appropriation bill for the County which provides for the support of the Police within this County. The ordinance for this purpose was approved by the Mayor yesterday, and Comptroller BRENNAN immediately drew his warrant for $165,000 -- the amount of the requisition of the Police Commissioners for the month of January. The taxes for 1863 will not be collected before next October, but the money required to be paid under appropriations is raised on revenue bonds, which are authorized by law to be issued both by the Corporation and the County, in anticipation of the collection of the annual taxes.

abstract: Gen. Grant Before; Battle for the Mississippi
snippet: Gen. Grant Before; Battle for the Mississippi
lead_paragraph: Gen. GRANT, with nearly the entire Army of the Mississippi, is now opposite Vicksburgh, on the Louisiana shore. It is a vastly greater army than was engaged in the last attack on Vicksburgh. It comprises all the latter force, together with the much larger force that GRANT, in the closing days of the year, was marching down the Mississippi Central Railroad to attack Vicksburgh in the rear -- which movement, it is now known, was baulked by the cowardly surrender of Col. MURPHY at Holly Springs and the imbecility of Gen. DAVIES at Island No. Ten. The Richmond Whig puts the strength of GRANT's army at 80,000 men, accompanied by fourteen gunboats and over two hundred steamers and transports. It is quite likely that this estimate is not far from the truth. So far as appears from facts which have been telegraphed from Cairo, Gen. GRANT's plan of operations is to consist of a simultaneous land attack on the rebel works from above and below, while the gunboats may be able to render important aid both on the Mississippi and the Yazoo. The famous "cut-off" canal seems to be still progressing, and the water is reported running through it at a depth of from two to four feet. Even if the channel is not widened so as to turn the course of the Mississippi River, the canal may subserve the vital purpose of permitting our gunboats and transports to pass through, after the fashion in which Gen. POPE's canal higher up the same river enabled him to circumvent the rebels at Island No. Ten. The rebels have planted a battery on the left bank of the river which commands the lower end of the canal; but, on the other hand, a considerable Union force -- undoubtedly accompanied with artillery -- has crossed the bend, and is stationed about a dozen miles below Vicksburgh, on the opposite side of the river. We suppose, also, that our gunboats could run the gauntlet of this rebel battery -- a sort of action which has been frequently accomplished on the Western rivers.

lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- Mr. GRAU's short season at the academy of Music comes to an end this evening, when MOZART's opera of "Don Giovanni" will be given. This work, introducing three prime donne, and the usual force of male singers, is seldom played except on the last night of the season, the impression prevailing that its attractions are too strong for any other time; that the public will not care to listen to one prima donna after having heard three. In accordance with custom, therefore, Mr. GRAU plays his trump card, and we may rest assured the house will be crowded, The two performances already given attracted the largest and most fashionable audiences ever seen here, and have, we are glad to hear, been a source of considerable profit to the impresario. The house, we are told, will be made sufficiently warm; on Wednesday it was miserably heated.

abstract: The Richmond corres  pondent of the Charleston Mercury says that French bankers have tendered the Confederacy a loan of seventy-five millions of francs, but that the terms of the loan are not yet divulged.
lead_paragraph: The Richmond correspondent of the Charleston Mercury says that French bankers have tendered the Confederacy a loan of seventy-five millions of francs, but that the terms of the loan are not yet divulged. We have heard frequently before of foreign loans to the Confederacy, including the ventures in that line of Mr. SMITH and Mr. BROWN, mentioned in the recently intercepted rebel dispatches; but we have not put much value either on the assertions or on the loans. It is quite possible, however, that the rebels are carrying on negotiations to procure foreign credit on the strength of the cotton crop, the whole of which the rebel Government now proposes to seize.

abstract: 'A bill to amend an act entitled an act to organize and supply negro labor for coast defence, in compliance with requisitions of the Government of the Confederate States, and to authorize and direct the Governor to proceed to furnish negro labor under said act," is before the South Carolina Legislature, now in session at Columbia. In precisely what way the "negro labor for coast defence" is to be "organized" does not appear. We suppose the negroes are to be employed on fortifications, &c., along the coast. At all events, South Carolina is to be defended by the aid of negroes. And if BEAUREGARD may employ negroes in raising rebel works to defend the State, why should not Gen. HUNTER employ negroes to scale those defences? If black hands may work BEAUREGARD's artillery, why should they not work HUNTER's cannon?

abstract: The peace movement at the North is fairly begun at last. The voice of a populace longing to close a hopeless and ruinous war of aggression can no longer be stifled. The mighty rabble of New-York and Philadelphia have caught up the cry raised by the Hoosiers of the Northwest, and day by day the peace element in party politics grows stronger and more distinct. The utterances which reach us show that there has been no lack of venal presses and unscrupulous politicians, shaping their course so as to share the rising fortunes of the anti-war movement. Everywhere throughout the North we find supple demagogues echoing the popular sentiment with a vigor and boldness which, a year ago, would have consigned them to a dungeon; and even the fearless and consistent VALLANDIGHAM takes a step farther than he ever dared before, and unfurls the white flag in the very halls of the Yankee Congress.
lead_paragraph: The peace movement at the North is fairly begun at last. The voice of a populace longing to close a hopeless and ruinous war of aggression can no longer be stifled. The mighty rabble of New-York and Philadelphia have caught up the cry raised by the Hoosiers of the Northwest, and day by day the peace element in party politics grows stronger and more distinct. The utterances which reach us show that there has been no lack of venal presses and unscrupulous politicians, shaping their course so as to share the rising fortunes of the anti-war movement. Everywhere throughout the North we find supple demagogues echoing the popular sentiment with a vigor and boldness which, a year ago, would have consigned them to a dungeon; and even the fearless and consistent VALLANDIGHAM takes a step farther than he ever dared before, and unfurls the white flag in the very halls of the Yankee Congress.

lead_paragraph: General orders from Yankee headquarters announce that Gens. BURNSIDE and SUMNER have been relieved at their own request, and that Gen. FRANKLIN has been relieved -- the General says in a farewell address to his troops -- against his consent. We are not given to understand the grounds of the resignation of the first, or of the removal of the last. A resolution in the Senate, by a Rhode Island Senator, implies that BURNSIDE has been embarrassed and thwarted by orders from Washington. Other accounts represent that he was conscious of his inability to effect anything. This has been his position from the beginning. He did not seek the command when MCCLELLAN was removed, but rather shrank from it, as being beyond his capacity. He has several times since indicated a wish to retire, for the same reason. After the battle of Fredericksburgh, he repeated his request to retire, confessing that the failure was owing to him; for which, says Northern scandal, he received $50,000 from STANTON and HALLECK. In chroncling his failures, it is due to him to remember this persistent modesty of his. It proves him to be a great man on the Socratian principle -- he knows his own folly.

lead_paragraph: Both branches of the Pennsylvania Legislature have passed resolutions urging Congress to repeal or reduce the duty on imported printing paper. The New-York Assembly has done the same thing, and so have the Legislatures of Massachusetts and of New-Jersey. Other States, without doubt, will rapidly follow the example. We have not heard of any State passing resolutions in favor of keeping the duty at its present enormous rate, as the Paper-maker's Association desires. Indeed, Massachusetts and Pennsylvania, the strongest protectionist States in the Union, have resolved exactly the other way.

lead_paragraph: "Now, I would accept anything on an Anti-Slavery basis. I would accept separation. I would accept compromise. I would accept Union. I would accept peace, and pay the whole Confederate debt at par on an Anti-Slavery basis. On that basis I have touched the hard-pan of National existence. I have reached the granite strata, and may begin to build again in peace. And until I reach that, no chicanery of parties, no ingenuity of compromise, no manner of separation can make any difference. We are in for the war."

lead_paragraph: The skating carnival, which has been so long postponed on account of the weather, fairly commenced yesterday, and all New-York rejoiced, for all New-York is interested, either by actual participation in the ice sports, or in the ruddy cheeks and joyful hearts of friends who do participate, and bring home the glad tidings of the day's sport. It needed not the multiplied flags and manifold balls to tell the people that the ice was in good order, for everybody expected it would be -- and what everybody expects very often happens. In cars, in carriages and on foot then, the devotees of the gyrating art effected their hegira to the upper part of the City, where broad expanses of frozen ponds absorbed, them all, and left room for even more than the fifty thousand who went.

abstract: The fight at Blackwater between the Federals, numbering, it is stated, from ten to fifteen thousand, and the Confederates, under Gen. PRYOR, commenced Saturday morning, about dawn our pickets being suddenly driven in, and the enemy shelling our camp by the light of its fires. Capt. CORT'S (South Carolina) Battery and a section of Capt. WRIGHT'S Battery replied to the fire.
lead_paragraph: The fight at Blackwater between the Federals, numbering, it is stated, from ten to fifteen thousand, and the Confederates, under Gen. PRYOR, commenced Saturday morning, about dawn -- our pickets being suddenly driven in, and the enemy shelling our camp by the light of its fires. Capt. CORT's (South Carolina) Battery and a section of Capt. WRIGHT's Battery replied to the fire. After the artillery duel was over, the fight was maintained about one hour with musketry, when the enemy ceased firing and retired. Gen. PEYOR fell back eight miles to Carrsville. Our loss was not over fifty killed and wounded. Among the killed was Col. POAGE, of Pulaski County, commanding the Fifty-fourth Virginia, and Capt. DOBBINS, of the Twenty-seventh Virginia. Col. POAGE was struck in the thigh by a fragment of shell, and bled to death in a few minutes. In WRIGHT's Battery, Capt. WRIGHT, Lieut. WATKINS, and GEO. R. WATTS, of Halifax, were slightly wounded.

abstract: We publish else  where a very eloquent and timely sermon by Rev. Dr. BELLOWS, on the duty of sustaining the Government in this terrible crisis of the nation's fate. It deserves general and attentive perusal.
lead_paragraph: -- We publish elsewhere a very eloquent and timely sermon by Rev. Dr. BELLOWS, on the duty of sustaining the Government in this terrible crisis of the nation's fate. It deserves general and attentive perusal. It states in just and strong terms the disastrous effects of the disposition to criticise and condemn the action of our rulers, which has to so large an extent obtained possession of the public mind. It denounces, with deserved severity, the sweeping censures and the wholesale slanders on the private characters of public men, in which a portion of the Press is so prone to indulge. And it sets forth, in very clear and impressive language, the absolute necessity, if we would rescue the Union and Constitution from the destruction which threatens them, of giving to the Government, and to the men who wield its powers, a larger degree of public confidence, and a more generous support than they now receive.

abstract: FIRE IN BROADWAY. About 3 o'clock yesterday morning fire was discovered breaking from the third story of promises No. 160 Broadway, occupied by Messrs. RINALDO  LASKY, cap manufacturers. lead_paragraph: FIRE IN BROADWAY. -- About 3 o'clock yesterday morning fire was discovered breaking from the third story of promises No. 160 Broadway, occupied by Messrs. RINALDO & LASKY, cap manufacturers. Notwithstanding the efforts of the firemen, who were promptly on hand, the entire building was seen in flames. RINALDO & LASKY occupied the third and fourth floors and garret. They estimate their loss at about $1,000. They are insured for $6,500, as follows: Kings County Insurance Company, $2,500; Hanover, $2,600; Lafarge, $2,000. The second story was occupied by Messrs. MA[???]KOLD & WERKLESS, dealers in furs. Their damage is about $5,000, insured for about $12,000, as follows: Mechanics' & Traders', $2,000; East River, $2,000; Montauk, $2,000; Pacific, $2,000; Citizen's, $2,000; and another Company, the name of which is not known, $2,000. The first floor was occupied by Messrs. VANZANDT & LIDGERWOOD, wine and liquor dealers. They are damaged to the amount of $1,000, mostly by water. They have an insurance upon their stock of $12,000 in the following companies: East River $4,000; Kings County $3,000; Relief $3,000; Standard $2,000. The basement was occupied by Messrs. PERKINS, STEIN & CO., importers of California wines. Their loss will probably amount to $1,000; insured for $15,000 in the Fulton and Security Insurance Companies. The building, which is owned by Mr. MARQUAND, is damaged to the amount of about $5,000; fully insured in the Etna and Manhattan Insurance Companies, Building No. 162 was considerably damaged, mainly by water. The origin of the fire is at present unknown. The Fire Marshal has the matter under investigation.

abstract: We have received very full files of Richmond and other Southern papers, to the 3d inst., from which we make important extracts, this morning. We get no additional details of the affair off Charleston harbor; but we get the fact that the ...
lead_paragraph: We have received very full files of Richmond and other Southern papers, to the 3d inst., from which we make important extracts, this morning. We get no additional details of the affair off Charleston harbor; but we get the fact that the rebels are industriously engaged in trying to convince everybody, and especially the foreign Consuls, that the blockade has been "raised." The French and English Consuls at Richmond have been officially notified that such is the case, and it is asserted, also, that, during the absence of the National vessels, on the 31st inst., a steamer left the port for Nassau, to notify our neutral English friends that the coast is clear, and that, for the present, at least, they can run in cargoes of "contraband" with impunity. Whether any such enterprise will be successful, however, remains to be seen. The new National frigate Ironsides is stated to be new lying off Charleston bar, outside a numerous fleet of other vessels.

abstract: We are in favor of giv  ing our gallant soldiers as many of the good things of this life as possible good rations,  good clothes, prompt pay, good muskets and plenty of work. But we hope that the statement we get from Washington is not true, that ...
lead_paragraph: -- We are in favor of giving our gallant soldiers as many of the good things of this life as possible -- good rations, good clothes, prompt pay, good muskets and plenty of work. But we hope that the statement we get from Washington is not true, that the War Department has decided to add tobacco to the army ration, and that a resolution to that effect will soon be introduced into Congress. The effect of it will simply be to make a bad habit universal in the army. We have not heard that the soldiers asked or desired any such favor from the War Department. Doubtless some of them smoke, others chew, and not a few like snuff. A few cents a week will procure supplies for such, if they purchase themselves; but if the Government undertake the business if will cost at least a quarter of a dollar a week for each man; and this, with our present force in the field, will add nearly a million dollars a month to the already enormous expenses of our military establishment. We would not begrudge this or ten times as much, if it would benefit our army, or add to its efficiency, health or morale in any way. But it will not. It will be a foolish waste, without equivalent, and will tend only to the benefit of speculators. We suspect that the whole thing has been gotten up by some tobacco speculators, who see in it a hopeful means of filling their pockets and increasing the value of their stock. The thing our army wants is to be paid its legitimate dues regularly and promptly, and out of these, those who use the weed will procure what of it they need. The ration of grog, which many thought really needful, has been abolished in the navy; let us not introduce a worse one into the army.

lead_paragraph: Walter T. Klots, et al. vs. The Steamboat Red Jacket. -- This case was a libel filed by the owners of the schooner Henry Ransom, to recover the damages occasioned to her by a colision with the steamer on June 2, 1860. The libelant alleged that the schooner was bond from Elizabethport, New-Jersey to Pawtucket, Rhode Island, with a cargo of coal. That while in the channel leading from Elizabethport to the Kills, the wind being fresh from the north and the schooner closehauled on her larboard tack, with a double reefed mainsail, she saw the steamer which had left Staten Island bound for Elizabethport, and was heading north of the schooner. That the channel was three hundred feet wide and there was room enough for the steamer to have passed on that side, but the steamer sheered to the south and crowded on the schooner, which at the last moment ported her helm to avoid the collision but too late.
