abstract: Secresy (in War Matters) at the Wrong Time
snippet: Secresy (in War Matters) at the Wrong Time
lead_paragraph: It is said that Gen. BANKS is unable to commence operations against Port Hudson, owing, partly, to the insufficiency of his force, but mainly to the fact that the Medical Department, not knowing where the expedition was going, but suspecting that it was to act against Richmond, sent all the medical stores to the James River. If this be true, it proves that there is such a thing as keeping a secret too well; and that, from letting everything be known to the wrong people, the authorities have rushed into the opposite extreme, of letting nothing be known to the right people. It is, we admit, better, as a general rule, to err on the side of too great secrecy, than on that of too great publicity; for while the former may sometimes cause suffering or delay, the latter is pretty sure to cause total failure.

lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the credentials of ALEX. S. RAMSEY, elected Senator from Minnesota, were presented. A bill to aid in the construction of railroads and telegraphs in Kansas was introduced. The President was called upon for information relative to the death of Gen. WARD, an American, killed in the service of the Chinese Government. A resolution introduced by Mr. WALL, of New-Jersey, making inquiries relative to the imprisonment of Capt. JOHN WEATHERS, formerly of the Fourth New-Jersey Regiment, in Fort Delaware, was laid over. The bill in relation to juries in the Courts of the United States was passed. A bill to incorporate the National Association for the Relief of Colored Women and Children, was referred to the Committee on the District of Columbia. The bill to temporarily supply vacancies in the Executive Departments was passed. Mr. WILSON's bill to encourage reenlistments, and for the enrollment and drafting of the militia, was then considered at some length, and was finally recommitted to the Military Committee. A resolution was adopted calling upon the President to communicate the number of volunteers and drafted men actually raised and mustered into the service. The Senate soon afterward adjourned.

abstract: The Ball instituted by the Ladies Aid Society camp off last night at Irving Hall, and was one of the happy events of the season. That a society of Germans should meet together for convivial enjoyment and fail in their intentions and purposes would be a circumstances not easily reconciled with their established reputation for determining, when they once ...
lead_paragraph: The Ball instituted by the Ladies Aid Society camp off last night at Irving Hall, and was one of the happy events of the season. That a society of Germans should meet together for convivial enjoyment and fail in their intentions and purposes would be a circumstances not easily reconciled with their established reputation for determining, when they once decide to give a social entertainment, to carry it through in spite of all obstacles. It may be inferred from this that there was no interference with the enjoyment of last evening, and perhaps every one was convinced that the unpropitious state of the weather would prevent a large assemblage of the fair. It must be admitted, however, that, notwithstanding the flood of rain, the ball was well attended, the elements having apparently little or no influence in depriving the lovers of mirth from indulging in their favorite pastime. To witness the eminent satisfaction which characterized the gathering of last night, would delight the most stoic spectator. There is an air of carelessness about a German dancer that adds much to the grace and beauty of a ball-room. The frigidity and stiffness which is too often noticeable among Americans, is, to a great extent, unobservable in a party of Germans assembled for a ball. While perfect decorum is exacted, they do not mistake etiquette by declining to contribute to each others' enjoyment. The ball of last evening was not different in its features from others held by the same class of citizens. The main object was to promote pleasure, and that was successfully accomplished.

The wamsutta is one of the 27 gunboats built by contract for the regular navy in 1861. She has recently undergone a thorough overhauling here, and is now in excellent condition. abstract: Some of our neighbors are expending a great deal of industry and some little learning in discussing the question whether the rebel ram Palmetto State has actually broken the Charleston blockade or not. The enormous exaggerations of the rebel newspapers, in ...
lead_paragraph: -- Some of our neighbors are expending a great deal of industry and some little learning in discussing the question whether the rebel ram Palmetto State has actually broken the Charleston blockade or not. The enormous exaggerations of the rebel newspapers, in stating the tacts of the case, leave very little solid ground for argument upon the subject; and the official dispatches, though couched in the most extravagant language, throw an air of ridicule over the pretensions which they themselves have put forward in connection with it.

abstract: To Washington; The
snippet: To Washington; The
lead_paragraph: We have published several communications against the passage of the bill now before Congress, authorizing and aiding the construction of an air-line railroad between Washington and New-York. The main argument they urge against it is, that the Directors of the existing roads propose to remedy all the defects in the present lines, and that the proposed "air line" road cannot be built. The configuration of the country and other material obstacles forbid it.

abstract: Since Gen. WOOL came to this Department there has been a great change in military matters. Previously the streets were crowded with soldiers and officers absent from their regiments wither without proper authority. The crowds of these dressed as soldiers and officers attracted attention on all sides. They were on the streets, in the dram-shops, and in the theatres and brothels throughout the City. There was a change needed, and fortunately enough the change has taken place under the supervision of the old hero of many battles, who now commands the Department of the East. Gen. WOOL has instructed Major CONWAY to carry out implicitly the orders of Gen. DRAPER, Provost-Marshal-General, and in order to do this a sufficient guard is allowed, thoroughly armed and prepared for the work. With this guard the City is patroled every night. Major CONWAY finds some facts which the people will be curious to know, and we give room for some of them.

abstract: Some correspondence that lately took place between the rebel Col. IMBODEN and Gen. MILROY was received yesterday at the Executive Department. IMBODEN says that Sheriff TRAYHORN, of Barbour County, was arrested by his order. He understands that two rebels named HENRY WILSON and HENRY BOWMAN were recently murdered in Barbour County.
lead_paragraph: Some correspondence that lately took place between the rebel Col. IMBODEN and Gen. MILROY was received yesterday at the Executive Department. IMBODEN says that Sheriff TRAYHORN, of Barbour County, was arrested by his order. He understands that two rebels named HENRY WILSON and HENRY BOWMAN were recently murdered in Barbour County. IMBODEN further understands that fifteen citizens of Barbour County have been arrested and confined in this city, and are to be executed in fifteen days, if TRAYHORN is not released within that time. IMBODEN informs Gen. MILROY that he will not release TRAYHORN, and if the fifteen citizens are executed, IMBODEN will execute thirty Union citizens and officers now in his possession. IMBODEN says he is "resolved that within the limits of the pretended State of West Virginia, he will at all times arrest as dangerous enemies to his State, every man he can lay his hands upon who holds any office under the usurped State Government at Wheeling." He says, further, that when he ascertains for certain that WILSON and BOWMAN have been murdered he will cause to be executed Lieut. DAWSON, of the First Virginia Cavalry, and Sergt. ATKINSON, of the same regiment, now in his possession.

abstract: EXCITEMENT IN HUDSON CITY.--A considerable excitement was occasioned in Hudson City yesterday and the afternoon previous, in consequence of the summary arrest of two citizens by the provost-guard, as alleged deserters. It appears that on Wednesday afternoon, a Sergeant and four privates ...
lead_paragraph: EXCITEMENT IN HUDSON CITY. -- A considerable excitement was occasioned in Hudson City yesterday and the afternoon previous, in consequence of the summary arrest of two citizens by the provost-guard, as alleged deserters. It appears that on Wednesday afternoon, a Sergeant and four privates belonging to the provost-guard and quartered at West Hoboken, proceeded to Hudson City where they took into custody a young man named WM. KETCHUM, on a charge of being a deserter from the United States service. The accused protested against the arrest on the ground that he was not a deserter, did not belong to the service and never had with the exception of serving with the first three months volunteers, at the close of which he received an honorable discharge. The provost-guard paid no attention to KETCHUM's protestations but compelled him to accompany them to the camp. A friend of the prisoner, named PATRICK COLEMAN, went along with them, and upon arriving at the camp was questioned by Col. LEICHLERKOST, who caused him also to be detained on suspicion of being a deserter. The circumstances of the affair becoming known caused considerable excitement in Hudson City, and about twenty citizens started for the camp for the purpose of procuring, if possible, the release of the prisoners. Meantime Squire MARTIN being applied to, issued a warrant which was placed in the hands of Constable HANLEY. The latter accompanied by two citizens proceeded to the camp and arrested the Sergeant and one private, who were taken to the jail and locked up to await further action. Col. LEICHLERKOST at once released KETCHUM and COLEMAN, and it is said immediately took his departure, apparently fearing that he too might receive a summons from the Squire and a night's quarters at the county lock-up.

abstract: Whatever may  be the effect of the war upon the prosperity of the country at large, we are very glad to know that it has improved the condition of the poorer classes, especially in this City. There is much less suffering among them than usual.
lead_paragraph: Whatever may be the effect of the war upon the prosperity of the country at large, we are very glad to know that it has improved the condition of the poorer classes, especially in this City. There is much less suffering among them than usual. The mild weather, which we have had thus far, has something to do with it, but other causes contribute to it also. A very large number of men now in the army from this City were persons who, when at home, earned very little or gave very little of what they did earn, toward the support of their families. But they now receive very good pay, have no chance to spend it for liquor, and as a matter of necessity send a large part of it to their families at home. Very many have thus fallen into good habits, and dropped bad ones, through their service. Others who were always industrious and thrifty continue to be so, and remit nearly all their earnings to their homes. And where these aids fail to avert suffering, families are relieved from the Volunteer Fund, which has contributed immensely to the comfort of this class of our poor. There are cases, of course, where great distress has been caused by loss of husbands and fathers in the war, but these are less numerous in this City than is generally supposed. On the whole, the burdens of the war fall very lightly on the poorer classes of our people.

abstract: Mexican advices, by way of Havana, are to the 24th ult., on which date a French vessel left Vera Cruz. Very little news had come down from the interior, communication being very precarious, owing to the operations of the guerrillas between Vera Cruz and Orizaba. It was reported ...
lead_paragraph: Mexican advices, by way of Havana, are to the 24th ult., on which date a French vessel left Vera Cruz. Very little news had come down from the interior, communication being very precarious, owing to the operations of the guerrillas between Vera Cruz and Orizaba. It was reported that DOBLADO, Government General, had been surprised and defeated by MEJIA, in the interest of the French, with the loss of $400,000 and a large number of muskets. There is no confirmation of the report of the defeat of the French by the Puebla garrison, but as the French had possession of all the avenues of information, they were very careful to allow no news to reach Vera Cruz which was unfavorable to them. Strict martial law was being enforced, and the fear of transportation to Martinique presented outspoken demonstrations on the part of the Mexicans. Two executions had taken place in the Castle of San Juan de Ulloa, of Mexicans accused of poisoning French soldiers.

abstract: Hon. ELI THAYER lectures this evening at the Cooper Institute in support of his project of conquering the rebellion by colonizing the rebel States. He proposes to crowd out the rebel population by planting upon their soil a new class of loyal citizens. The superior attractions of climate and soil he relies upon as inducements to settlement, and he is firm in the faith that in this way the tone and temper of the Southern people can be more rapidly changed than any other.

abstract: On Ending the War
snippet: On Ending the War
lead_paragraph: The Tribune of yesterday attempts an explanation of its recent mysterious movements in favor of foreign mediation and of making peace, if the campaign now opening against the rebels should fail to conquer them. Its explanation is less lucid than could be desired; but as near as we can understand it, Mr. GREELEY's movement is intended as an experiment on the Democratic party. He says:

abstract: The Collector of Customs has been instructed to issue no permits for shipment of goods Westward, unless satisfactory proof is given by the shippers that said goods are not ultimately destined for rebel consumption. The railroad companies have been notified not to carry such goods without the special sanction of the authorities. The cause of this restriction is the discovery lately made that large quantities of goods were forwarded to the rebels, via St. Louis, rough the activity of prominent Secessionists in that city. The action of the authorities will, without doubt, put a stop to this contraband traffic.

abstract: -- There was a year, less ten days, between the first and second battles of Fort Donelson -- if the affair of last Tuesday may be called a battle. Last year we attacked the rebels and took the fort -- this year the rebels attacked the fort but did not take it. The investing force last February was twenty thousand, and the defensive force nearly as great. The assaulting force, on the 3d inst., was four or five thousand of the style of troops which the rebels call "horse marines;" and we believe our garrison consisted of two or three infantry regiments. Our losses in killed and wounded at the first battle of Fort Donelson were about four thousand; the rebel loss was about the same, beside twelve thousand prisoners. The respective losses at Tuesday's battle we do not yet know; for we can hardly credit the astonishing dispatch sent to the New-York Press, yesterday, from Cairo, that the rebel killed were two hundred and our killed but two -- that the rebel wounded were five hundred and our wounded less than forty. Our main object in attacking Fort Donelson last year was to open the Cumberland River and then advance upon Nashville; the rebel purpose in attacking it this year was to block up the Cumberland River and cut off the supplies to ROSECRANS and Nashville. The battle of last year was our first grand effort to enter and obtain possession of the rebel State of Tennessee; the fight this year was the expiring effort of the rebels to maintain a foothold in that State. Both the battles, though of widely different magnitude and results, were decisive victories to the Union arms.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The best performance of Mr. GRAU's short season, was undoubtedly the "Don Giovanni" of last night. The principal characters were intrusted to most competent hands, and the orchestra and chorus were more than ordinarily perfect. Miss KELLOGG's Zerlina has already been recognized as one of her best roles, a little too refined, perhaps, for the innocent village maiden, but none the less delightful for that reason. Mme. LORINI was excellent in the dramatic music of the first act, and generally satisfactory elsewhere. Mme. STRAKOSCH, who made her first appearance this season as Elvira, was, as usual, thoroughly perfect in the part. Of the male characters, it is only necessary to say that Signor AMODIO essayed the part of Don Giovanni for the first time, and, as we understand, without even the advantage of having heard it performed elsewhere. It was a very acceptable substitute for Signor GASSIER, who was certainly the most gallant Don we have ever had in this country. Signor BRIGNOLI was the Octavio, and Signor SUSINI the Leporello, characters in which they are already known. The performance was, in almost every respect, a good one.

abstract: BUSINESS IN THE COURT OF SESSIONS. In the Kings County Court of Sessions, yesterday, WILLIAM H. PATTON was arraigned on an indictment for forgery in passing a counterfeit $10 bill on the Citizens' Bank of Worcester, Mass., at the store of GEORGE BELL, in ...
lead_paragraph: BUSINESS IN THE COURT OF SESSIONS. -- In the Kings County Court of Sessions, yesterday, WILLIAM H. PATTON was arraigned on an indictment for forgery in passing a counterfeit $10 bill on the Citizens' Bank of Worcester, Mass., at the store of GEORGE BELL, in the Eastern District, on the 7th of January last. The accused pleaded guilty. He is represented as being an old offender, having three years since been tried for some offence, and paid his counsel, D. PARMENTER, Esq., (how a non-commissioned officer in the One Hundred and Fifty-ninth Regiment, N.Y.V.,) in counterfeit bills. Sentence was reserved. MICHAEL FERNANDEZ, heretofore convicted of grand larceny, and SAMUEL CORDOZA, found guilty of burglary in the fourth degree, were, sentenced -- the former to, State Prison for two years and three months, and the latter for two years and two months. JOHN BURNS, indicted for manslaughter in the third degree, in causing the death of his wife, pleaded guilty to the offence in the fourth degree, and was remanded for sentence, WILLIAM DEMING, indicted on the charge of committing a rape upon the person of a little girl, eight years of age, named MARY MCGARRY, was convicted by the jury. Sentence was reserved. The Court adjourned until next Tuesday.

abstract: DOMESTIC TROUBLES A YOUNG WIDOW POISONS HERSELY. Yesterday afternoon, Mrs. MARY FRANCES CLARK, a widow, only 17 years of age, living at No. 141 Worth-street, having become tired of life, owing to a multiplicity of domestic and other troubles, proceeded to the drug-store of Dr. WELCH, No. 86 Centre-street, and stated that a Mrs. WILLIAMS, well known to the Doctor, had sent her for half an ounce ...
lead_paragraph: DOMESTIC TROUBLES -- A YOUNG WIDOW POISONS HERSELF. -- Yesterday afternoon, Mrs. MARY FRANCES CLARK, a widow, only 17 years of age, living at No. 141 Worth-street, having become tired of life, owing to a multiplicity of domestic and other troubles, proceeded to the drug-store of Dr. WELCH, No. 86 Centre-street, and stated that a Mrs. WILLIAMS, well known to the Doctor, had sent her for half an ounce of laudanum. Believing the girl's statement, Dr. WELCH gave her the laudanum, which she took home and drank in the presence of several persons. The doctor who sold the narcotic was at once called, and administered antidotes which eventually had the desired effect. After being sufficiently recovered, she was taken before Justice DOWLING, and by him transferred to the care of the Commissioners of Charities and Correction. This would-be suicide was married when only 14 years of age, but the match was an ill-timed one, and she separated from her husband three weeks afterward. After the war broke out, he entered the service of his country and was subsequently killed in battle. The news of his death had a depressing effect upon the young widow, and she formed dissolute habits. She became attached to a worthless fellow, who often beat and abused her. About eight months since Capt. JOURDAN found this young woman on the Points, and learning that she then lived at No. 29 Carroll-street, Brooklyn, he sent her home. She seems to regret that she failed to take her life, and expresses the determination to renew the attempt when an opportunity presents itself.

abstract: Payne, Dr. Martin; Institutes of Medicine
snippet: Payne, Dr. Martin; Institutes of Medicine
lead_paragraph: A medical work which holds its ground with the profession for sixteen years, which in that time runs through seven editions, which has been used as a text-book by half a dozen generations of medical students -- a work which embraces in its comprehensive grasp the three prime domains of a physician's study: physiology, pathology and therapeutics, or the laws of life, the laws of disease, and the laws of cure -- a work which is the accumulated experience of fifty years' professional and professorial life -- must have some extraordinary merit that it thus endures the test of time, withstands the assaults of criticism, and maintains its popularity with the most progressive of professions. A book upon geometry or any of what are termed the fixed sciences, is true forever; a play of SHAKESPEARE never grows old, and his delineations of character will be as apt for the last generation of men as they would have been for the first, had the plays then existed; the epics of the Homeridae and the philosophies of new and old schools have an abiding value, as food to the imaginative and speculative intellect; even old sermons, if they are good ones, have an eternal freshness, and, if orthodox, might be preached to a hundred generations of men and carry them all to Paradise. But with doctor's books it is different. For the reason that there are very few articles in the creed or philosophy of doctors that endure through a single generation, much less through successive centuries. The popular physiology of the ancients and of the mediaeval ages, when dissections were forbidden, is now ridiculous; pathology, up to the days of JOHN HUNTER, had no scientific existence at all; while our present therapeutics and chemistry are both products of the most modern research. And we need not go back centuries or generations to find the most fundamental changes in every department of practical and scientific medicine, and their collateral branches. The pathology of 1863 is not that of 1853; nay, in many important points, it is not that of 1860. What in physiology has not been elucidated within the last twenty years, or since the practice of vivisection, the use of the modern microscope, and the discovery of anaesthesia? As to therapeutics and the use of drugs, every decade produces such radical changes that a Dispensatory a few years old, or a doctor who does not perpetually increase his knowledge from current medical literature, is worthless.

abstract: Goods from China
snippet: Goods from China
lead_paragraph: -- A telegraphic dispatch from San Francisco last night brought us a noteworthy item. Among the arrivals of ships at that port, was one on day before yesterday from Shanghai, with late dates, and bringing as cargo seven hundred bales of cotton goods (drills and sheetings) from China. She also brings advices that hereafter the California market will be liberally supplied with cotton goods from that quarter. Considering the present enormous prices of cotton goods in this country, this is not at all wonderful. Cotton can be raised in China cheaper than in any other part of the world, except the Southern States, owing to the great abundance and low price of labor; and from the same cause it can be manufactured cheaper there than anywhere else, except in Europe and this country, where there is labor-saving machinery.

snippet: Richter, Jean Paul; Titan; Gautier, Theophile; Romance of the Mummy; Wood, Mrs. Henry; Verner's Pride
lead_paragraph: -- We would like to know Mrs. HENRY WOOD. Any woman capable of writing books brimming with emotion, and mystery, and murder, and all that, faster than any two men can read them, must be a woman worth knowing. If she records the titles and dates of her books as matrons in the ordinary walks of life do the births and names of their children, her family Bible must consist chiefly of a family record, and from it even the names of the prophets must necessarily be excluded. Phenomically prolific as Mrs. WOOD is, she is correspondingly popular. To be popular is to be rich. Her pen, like the fingers of Midas, transmutes everything it touches into gold. Even our wizard Secretary of the Treasury cannot work half the wonders with paper that she does. Each slip of her manuscript has a money value which passeth that of greenbacks.

abstract: RAILROAD MOVEMENTS IN NEW-JERSEY. On Friday, a supplement to the charter of the Newark and Orange Horse-car Railroad was introduced in the Legislature of New-Jersey. This supplement contemplates the important step of consolidating all the horse railroads running in and from Newark into one corporation, a measure which, it is claimed, would be attended with more ample facilities and accommodations ...
lead_paragraph: RAILROAD MOVEMENTS IN NEW-JERSEY. -- On Friday, a supplement to the charter of the Newark and Orange Horse-car Railroad was introduced in the Legislature of New-Jersey. This supplement contemplates the important step of consolidating all the horse railroads running in and from Newark into one corporation, a measure which, it is claimed, would be attended with more ample facilities and accommodations to the public than can be secured under a diversity of controlling interests. Objections are urged against the proposed plan upon the ground that the public would be, in case of its adoption, at the mercy of a powerful monopoly, which would have none of the checks upon extortion which competition secures. In reply to this, it is averred that the exclusive control which the municipality of Newark reserves over all horse railroads, would be an ample guarantee against any abuse of power.

abstract: recaptured by the rebels
snippet: recaptured by the rebels
lead_paragraph: We have another bad item of news, this morning, from Texas. The Sabine Pass, on the extreme southeastern point of the Texas border, which our troops took possession of some months ago, has been recaptured by the rebels, and its garrison, guns and supplies captured, together with a United States gunboat and an unknown schooner. We suppose MAGRUDER will now proclaim the blockade at that point broken, and Sabine City open to the commerce of the world. The occupation of Sabine Pass was important as obstructing the trade which is carried on from Texas to Louisiana, and to the Cotton States this side of the Mississippi, and also that from Eastern Texas to and through Mexico.

snippet: United States vs. Sunbeam, steamship; Prize; Alleged Distress
lead_paragraph: The United States vs. The Steamer Sunbeam and her Cargo. -- This vessel was captured Sept. 28, 1862, off the port of Wilmington, N.C., by the United States man-of-war State of Georgia. She was brought here and libeled as prize. The process was returned Nov. 4, 1862, when the British Consul intervened, claiming the vessel and cargo as owned by British subjects. On Dec. 27, Henry Lafour, a British subject, intervened, claiming to be sole owner of the vessel and the whole of her cargo. The test oath was made by his attorney in fact. On Dec. 30 a claim was filed by Joseph Greenwood, of England, also through an attorney in fact, claiming to be the owner of 18 bales of worsted goods, which he alleged were shipped from Liverpool for Matamoras, and were not subject to the control of the master of the ship, but were in the sole charge of his own agent.

abstract: -- The Joint Committee of the Common Council who recently visited Suffolk, Va., to present a sword, sash and belt to Gen. CORCORAN, and of which WILLIAM WALSH, the President of the Board of Aldermen, was the Chairman, gave a dinner last night, at the "Maison Doree," to Rev. JAMES M. DILLON, the Chaplain of CORCORAN's Brigade, who was unremitting in attentions to the comfort of the Committee, while they were at Suffolk, and who is now in the City on a brief business visit connected with the "Irish Legion." The dinner was of the most recherche character. In addition to Rev. Mr. DILLON and Alderman WALSH, there were present Aldermen Mitchell. Henry, Reed, Hardy and Ottiwell, Ex-Aldermen Smith and Brady, Councilman Healy, Judge Charles K. Smith, Surrogate Gideon J. Tucker, Simon Meyer, Secretary to the Committee, and the TIMES' Reporter. The affair passed off very happily. Brief addresses were made by Rev. Mr. Dillon, Aldermen Walsh, Reed, Ottiwell and Hardy, Councilmen Healy, and Judge Smith and Mr. Tucker. At 11 o'clock A.M., to-morrow, at the City Hall, the Committee will present to Mr. DILLON, as their personal offerings of friendship to that gentleman, an elegant saddle, a pair of spurs of superior description, and a pair of gauntlets.

abstract: In the Senate yesterday, the House bill to promote the efficiency of the Commissary Department, was passed. A memorial was presented from merchants of New-York, praying that legal tender notes may be used for the payment of customs duties. A resolution directing the Committee on the Conduct of the War to inquire into the condition of the Army of the Potomac, was introduced by Mr. SUMNER, of Massachusetts, and laid over. The Missouri Emancipation bill was taken up, and debated until the adjournment, which did not take place until midnight.

lead_paragraph: Lieut Commander EDWARD LEA was born in the City of Baltimore, on the 30th day of January, 1838. His father, Gen. ALBERT M. LEA, graduated in the Topographical Engineers at West Point, and his mother was a grand-daughter of SAMUEL SHOEMAKER, Esq., Mayor of Philadelphia before the formation of the Government. Having conceived a fondness for the Navy, EDWARD LEA entered the Academy at Annapolis in 1851, and graduated therefrom June 9, 1855.

abstract: The Lynchburgh Republican learns from the Mail Agent on the Virginia and Tennessee Railroad, who came east Wednesday evening, Jan. 28, that it was reported the Yankees were advancing upon the salt works in Washington County, and were stated to have been within four miles of them Tuesday night. abstract: Slavery in; New-Jersey resolutions on
snippet: Slavery in; New-Jersey resolutions on
lead_paragraph: We notice that resolutions have been introduced into the Legislature of New-Jersey in reference to the proposed assistance of the General Government to Missouri in securing the emancipation of her slaves. The resolutions set forth that New-Jersey is not willing to cause her citizens to be taxed for the special benefit of other States, or to permit the money of the people to be expended for objects not contemplated by the Constitution, and that she gives notice that any debt contracted for this purpose is not binding in law or equity upon the State or its citizens, and will not be regarded by either in the light of an obligation.

abstract: The Lavacca correspondent of the Houston (Texas) Telegraph gives an interesting description of a peculir shell which the "Abolitionists" have been throwing into the town of Lavacca. "The shell is filled with explosive bullets, resembling the Minie ball in shape, filled with powder, with a piece of punk used to stop the hole. The effect of this sort of thing is, when the bullet is fired the punk takes fire, and about the time the bullet is supposed to bury itself in a rebel it explodes, making a terrible and incurable wound. With such savage appliances does our enemy seek to destroy us."

abstract: The Lynchburgh Republican learns from its correspondent in Charlottesville, that Capt. MALLORY, Captain of the post, seized on Wednesday, about $20,000 worth of goods, boots and shoes, dry goods, hats, 400 pounds of bi-carbonate soda. These goods were in three wagons, unloading at the store of a merchant in the place, when they were seized. The owner of the goods and wagons had the permit of Col. EPPA HUNTON, GARNETT and Gen. STUART, "to bring shoes, hats and other things out of Loudon County, for the soldiers." Capt. MALLORY being satisfied that these goods came from Baltimore through Loudon County, and that they were brought to Charlottesville for speculation and not for the use of soldiers, seized and holds them to the order of the Secretary of War.

abstract: The coquetry of the South with the Northwest is inexplicable on the theory that the rebels believe their ordinary assertions. They loathe and detest the North because it would not allow them to secede, and has made war upon them to prevent it.
lead_paragraph: The coquetry of the South with the Northwest is inexplicable on the theory that the rebels believe their ordinary assertions. They loathe and detest the North because it would not allow them to secede, and has made war upon them to prevent it. But have the Northwestern States been any less determined than the Eastern States in upholding the unity of the Government, and have its volunteer soldiers made war upon the Southern Secessionists with any less vigor and vim than the soldiers of the East? Was the call of the President for troops responded to with any less alacrity in Indiana and Illinois than in Massachusetts and New-Hampshire? Did the battles of Pea Ridge and Fort Donelson suit the rebels any better than those of Manassas and the Peninsula? Do they love their foes of Murfreesboro better than their foes of Antietam? Do they find any higher satisfaction in the Democratic vote of Indiana than in that of New-York?

lead_paragraph: FUNERAL OF A GALLANT JERSEYMAN. -- The funeral of Lieut. FRANKLIN EMERY, of Company G, Seventh Michigan Infantry, will take place to-morrow, at 3 P.M., from the residence of his uncle, S.R. HAINES, Esq., No. 32 Franklin-street, Newark. Lieut. EMERY was one of the heroic Michigan boys who manned the boats which crossed the Rappahannock, at Fredericksburgh, in the face of a storm of rebel bullets, to drive the sharpshooters of the enemy from their position. Lieut. E. was in the second boat that landed, reaching the shore uninjured. Later in the day, however, in a gallant charge upon the enemy, he was struck by a Minie bullet in the forehead and killed instantly. His last words were, "The Government expects every man to do his duty." Lieut. E. was formerly a resident of Newark, having removed West some years ago. He served with the Seventh Michigan from the opening of the war.

abstract: Paris Nation on Cotton and the Blockade
snippet: Paris Nation on Cotton and the Blockade
lead_paragraph: The Nation, of Paris, tells its readers that the end which it is the duty of France to pursue, at any price, is to "reestablish the relations of Europe and the United States on the former basis." It thinks that France is urged to this duty by the condition of her cotton industry -- not that there is not cotton enough, for it declares that the cotton stock is not ten per cent. below that of last year at this time, but that the manufactured articles are so high that the manufacturers dare not carry on operations to any extent for fear of a fall in prices, which would inevitably result from the announcement of peace in the United States, or any decided movement in that direction.

abstract: the Pope and his Patrons
snippet: the Pope and his Patrons
lead_paragraph: Wonders never cease; and not the least astounding one of this thaumaturgic age is, that England has recently offered to take the Pope under her protection in event of his being obliged to leave Rome. The offer was made through Mr. ODO RUSSELL, British Charge at the Vatican, and, considering England's anti-papal prejudices, must be regarded as an extraordinary instance of liberality and condescension on her part. Whenever His Holiness is compelled or disposed to exchange his position as a sovereign prince for that of an exiled sovereign, England will be ready to accommodate him with a palace in the island of Malta, and to treat him with all due respect -- nay, she will even go so far as to place her Mediterranean fleet at his service to convey him thither. The Pope, it seems, has not the slightest intention of availing himself of England's generosity; but, nevertheless, as soon as M. DROUYN DE L'HUYS became aware of such a proposition having been made to PIO NONO by Mr. RUSSELL, he grew quite alarmed. This was evidently an attempt of perfide Albion to get inside of France with the Pontiff, and to put the "Eldest Son of the Church" at a discount with the heretic; and, accordingly, the French Minister, as in duty bound, set about countermining the British functionary, by informing the Papal Nuncio accredited to the Tuileries that France expected, should His Holiness be unfortunately impelled to quit Italy, that he would prefer her protection to that of England.

abstract: This morning a [???] of citizens gathered near an object of strange interest, as if throwing the last fond gaze on an object soon to disappear from mortal sight. That object proved to be the last of the famous Manassas wooden guns, about which so much has been written and said. The history of this formidable object, as near as we could learn, is, that it was boxed, and sent from New-York, per express, several weeks since, the charges to be paid here. On its arrival no claimant appeared, and the box and contents were sold at auction, by Messrs. WALL & Co., to pay the freight. The precious contents were sold "unseen" and the competition for the mysterious box was very great. The "goods" were "knocked down" at sixteen dollars. The lucky purchaser "forked over" the cash, and hastily proceeded to examine his prize. His horror may be imagined, when he beheld nothing but an enormous black log! Seeing his disappointment, a benevolent colored individual offered to take the burden off the purchaser's hands. Only too glad to "git shet" of the hated object, the log was presented to the contraband, and to-day he is converting it into stuff to "make Dinah's kettle boil." Farewell to the "wooden guns!" -- Washington Republican Feb. 4.

abstract: Engineering, Documents Wanted
snippet: Engineering, Documents Wanted
lead_paragraph: The fact that much of the machinery of war, especially the marine-engines designed by Government bureaus, have failed, and that much successful practice and promising invention from without have been ignored, is already patent to the public; and no honest attempt will probably be made to deny it. Indeed, Government Boards have been recently directed to inquire into the defects of our new sloops-of-war. The leading official mistakes charged upon the Department are briefly these: The construction, not of one ship, but of an entire navy, in accordance with the ridiculous hypothesis, contrary to the whole successful practice of a century, that the expansion of steam in the usual way, is not economical; so arranging the valves of the naval engines against the specific protest of builders, that they cut their seats to a degree that will allow long runs and tolerable speed only by reconstruction; proportioning the reciprocating parts of the engines -- parts which for high speed and durability require extreme lightness -- about 250 per cent. heavier than those of successful outside examples, and the other parts, 75 to 100 per cent. heavier; depriving the ships of power adequate to catch any tolerable sailer, and by the means just named, hampering what power they have, introducing the most expensive and complex, but not the most effective details and accessories -- condensers, for instance -- especially where the patents are held inside the "ring;" failing to calculate within two hundred tons, the displacement of twenty-three gunboats, thus making them slow and of deep draft; unnecessarily placing the boilers and engines of these boats above the water-line and in short range; attempting to saddle upon the people the excessive cost of several iron-clads -- two-and-a-quarter millions apiece -- with a kind of armor which the best experimental and service ordnance smashes through with ease; delaying provision for predicted exigencies, until great damage was done and prestige gained by the enemy -- for instance, the construction of iron-clads and fast vessels; adhering to patented cast-iron shell guns competent only to low charges and velocities, for a kind of warfare which foreigners and rebels have prepared to engage in, only by the use of wrought-iron and steel guns, and high charges; and persistently refusing to adopt many of the promising improvements offered and urged by outside inventors and practitioners.

abstract: EXTORTIONATE CHARGES FOR STORING PRIZE PROPERTY. Messrs. WARD  GOVE, keepers of the Union Stores, Brooklyn, have lately presented a bill of $11,191 for storage, cooperage, labor,  c., on nine cargoes of resin. United States Marshal MURRAY refused to pay the bill, and yesterday they applied to Judge BETTS to sanction the bill as rendered, but the Judge very properly refused the application.
lead_paragraph: EXTORTIONATE CHARGES FOR STORING PRIZE PROPERTY. -- Messrs. WARD & GOVE, keepers of the Union Stores, Brooklyn, have lately presented a bill of $11,191 for storage, cooperage, labor, &c., on nine cargoes of resin. United States Marshal MURRAY refused to pay the bill, and yesterday they applied to Judge BETTS to sanction the bill as rendered, but the Judge very properly refused the application. As a sample of the extortion practiced by this firm, the case of the schooner Alfred H. Partridge may be cited, when the bill presented to the Marshal for cooperage amounted to $307, while the amount paid the cooper for doing the work was $39 55. Marshal MURRAY has consulted some of the prominent merchants of the City with regard to the charges customary and proper in such cases, and he refuses to pay on behalf of the Government more than is usually paid by individuals. He has offered to Messrs. WARD & GOVE on their bill of $11,191 one-fifth of the amount claimed. It has long been a subject of complaint among captors of prizes that the expenses attending the storage and sale of prize property sent to this port are so exorbitant that nothing is left to be divided among the prize men. So notorious is this fact that Commanders of our blockading vessels refuse to send prizes to New-York if they can possibly avoid it, but prefer sending them to Boston or Philadelphia. There is no good reason why the expenses should be greater here than in other cities, and it is to be hoped that hereafter all extortions like the above will be exposed.

abstract: Baltimore American on
snippet: Baltimore American on
lead_paragraph: It is quite common for over-zealous partisans of the Administration, in Congress and in the Press, to sneer at "Border State loyalty" as something quite unworthy to be mentioned in any connection, however remote, with their devotion to the Union. We have more than once protested against this injustice. In our judgment, if the Union is saved, it will be due quite as much to the efforts of loyal men in Missouri, Kentucky, Tennessee and Maryland, as to the more fervid, but not more serviceable, zeal of Massachusetts and New-York.

abstract: Speech before Uni ed States Christian Commission, New-York; Meeting at N. Y. Academy of Music
snippet: Speech before Uni ed States Christian Commission, New-York; Meeting at N. Y. Academy of Music
lead_paragraph: The Academy of Music was filled to overflowing last evening on the occasion of the meeting in aid of the United States Christian Commission. The announcement that Gens. SCOTT and BURNSIDE would be present, attracted thousands who were unable to gain admittance to the building. Just before the commencement of the exercises, the Chairman of the New-York Committee, Mr. WM. E. DODGE, suggested to those present that it would much comport with the character of the occasion if the venerable Gen. SCOTT, who was about to take the Chair, should be received by the audience rising in silence, rather than by any other demonstration. Almost instantly Gen. SCOTT appeared, and the audience unanimously complied with the request. It was one of the most remarkable spectacles of a docile audience ever witnessed, for the desire to cheer the old hero was next to irrepressible. The few who attempted to depart from the desire of Mr. DODGE were promptly hushed, and Gen. SCOTT bowed his acknowledgments amid the most impressive stillness.

lead_paragraph: The matinee on Saturday brought Mr. GRAU's reason to a very successful termination. It was crowded to the greatest capacity of the house, and with the three previous performances must have netted a very handsome profit to the impresario. Mr. GRAU's plan of operations, if it leads to no result in an art point of view, possesses, at least, the merit of being thoroughly safe to himself. Two or three nights of opera in a city so fond of the entertainment must be successful, although it does not at all follow that artistically the performances will be good. It would be difficult, except on the ground of necessity, to account for the success of the last week. With the exception of Friday night, when "Don Giovanni" was given, the performances outside of the more or less successful efforts of the vocal quartette were extremely mediocre. It could hardly be otherwise, for a long and steady season can alone support a respectable orchestra and chorus, and completeness rests on these auxiliaries. It is but just to Mr. GRAU to say that his intentions were somewhat more ambitious than heretofore, but they were frustrated by the accident of Signor BRIGNOLI's indisposition. With a vocal company of unusual strength, he had, but for this contretemps, the opportunity of making his management memorable. Reduced to the briefest proportions, the most that can be said of the season is that it was successful in a pecuniary point of view, and that the prime donne under his direction, distinguished themselves in their few interpretations -- especially Miss KELLOGG, who, as Lady Henriette in "Martha," and Zerlina in "Don Giovanni," gave evidence of improved style and lightsome appreciation of seriocomic character. In parting with Miss KELLOGG the public loses the best native prima donna the country has yet produced. Mr. GRAU's company appears to-night at the Boston theatre.

lead_paragraph: FATAL RESULT OF AN AFFRAY. Coroner NORRIS held an inquest, on Saturday, upon the body of THOMAS MILLER, who died the night previous, from the effect of injuries sustained in an affray in BURDON'S iron foundry, Front-street, about two months since. It appears that JAMES McLAUGHLIN and JAMES LYNCH got into a quarrel, and commenced fighting. The deceased interfered, when JAMES MARTIN also took part, and was knocked down by MCLAUGHLIN. He jumped up, and seizing a bar of iron, made a pass at MCLAUGHLIN, but missing him, struck MILLER on the head, fracturing his skull. The injury was not supposed to be of a fatal character at the time, and MARTIN, who was arrested, was released from custody. Lately, MILLER began to fail, and finally died. MARTIN has left the city. The jury rendered a verdict that THOMAS MILLER came to his death from a blow from a bar of iron in the hands of JAMES MARTIN.

abstract: We have the American edition of Braithwaite's Retrospect of Practical Medicine and Surgery for the first half of the current year. It contains a large number of very valuable papers and digests of papers by the most distinguished British practitioners, treating of almost every ...
lead_paragraph: -- We have the American edition of Braithwaite's Retrospect of Practical Medicine and Surgery for the first half of the current year. It contains a large number of very valuable papers and digests of papers by the most distinguished British practitioners, treating of almost every branch of medical practice, and furnishing a full exhibit of the progress of medical discovery and improvement in England during the latter half of last year. It is invaluable to those who do not see the weekly and monthly periodical medical literature of Great Britain, or who wish to obtain better m[???] better tested and more concise views than many of those hastily given in the weekly journals. It is not merely British medical literature and medical discovery the[???] are epitomized, but the present number contains articles by French, German, Italian and American, as well as English doctors. We always like to take up a book that is well indexed, and has a good table of contents, as is the case with the Retrospect; but the Messrs. BRAITHWAITE furnish a distinct feature to this magazine which is equally valuable with either of these. We refer to the "Synopsis," which, as is put forth in the headline, "contains a short abstract of the most practical articles in the preceding page, showing at a glance the most important indications of treatment published within the half year." Thus the body of the present issue consists of nearly 300 pages, while in the 20 pages of "Synopsis" at the close, the reader is furnished with the seed-kernel of each article in a few lines For example, to give the reader at once an instance of neat abbreviation and a valuable medical fact, we find on page 126 a short article on the treatment of earache, which in the synopsis is epitomized thus:

abstract: After five days' impatient waiting, we have the truth concerning the naval affair in Charleston harbor, which so excited the town last Wednesday. The news comes to us by way of Philadelphia, to which port it was brought by the iron steam propeller Princess Royal ...
lead_paragraph: After five days' impatient waiting, we have the truth concerning the naval affair in Charleston harbor, which so excited the town last Wednesday. The news comes to us by way of Philadelphia, to which port it was brought by the iron steam propeller Princess Royal, which was captured by our Charleston blockading fleet, on the 29th ult. The affair, it seems, was mainly about the possession of this valuable vessel, which, when captured, was laden with a heavy cargo of military supplies for the rebels, such as Whitworth guns, gunpowder, steam-engines, sheet-iron, and a lot of English "mudsills," not to speak of coffee, boots, and other luxuries and necessaries. She was taken on the evening of the 29th, quite close in to the shore; and as she was permitted to remain there the next day, the rebels got ready as quick as possible and started out on the night of that day to see if they could not recapture her by a grand coup. In this primary object they completely failed, as the fact of the arrival of the Princess Royal at Philadelphia proves; and being foiled in this, and circumstances favoring, BEAUREGARD bethought him of the magnificent programme of "formally declaring the blockade of Charleston raised by a superior force of the Confederate States."

lead_paragraph: GREAT WRESTLING MARCH FOR $1,400. -- A wrestling match took place at the Hudson House, Jersey City, on Saturday afternoon, between F.D. BUNNELL, of Chenango County, N.Y., and Lieut. AINESWORTH, of Hartford, Conn., for $700 a side. The terms of the match were a collar and elbow hold, best in three, time to be called every fifteen minutes, allowing five minutes for rest, and one hour intervene between each fall. BUNNELL won the first fall, (upon which it is said that he had $800 bet,) after six minutes' contest. On the second trial, after time had been called, and the contestants had taken hold, BUNNELL let go with one hand, and was it the act of handing his cap to a man near by, when AINESWORTH improved the opportunity and threw him. "Foul" was claimed by some of the spectators, of whom there were about 200 present. Considerable discussion followed, when it was finally settled by BUNNELL giving in that it was a fair fall. Previous to this, it is said, the judges declared off all outside bets, and, upon the settlement of the second fall, declared them on again, which, it is claimed in sporting circles, they had no right to do. The third fall resulted in favor of AINESWORTH, who, of course, won the main bet.

lead_paragraph: The steamship Hansa, from Southampton on the 21st inst., arrived at this port, about 1 1/2 o'clock yesterday morning. Her news is three days later than previously received. The resolution was opposed by Mr. SPENCE, who constituted himself the champion of the South, but to no effect. We give among our extracts a full copy of the letter of the French Emperor to Gen. abstract: What it Means

lead_paragraph: The agents of secession who are now laboring at the North for compromise and peace, profess to be working in the interest of the Union, and with what FERNANDO WOOD would call "a single eye" to its restoration. But we vould once more warn those whom they are bout to supply with their "political information," that compromise or peace upon any other erms than the naked, unconditional submission of the South, would be just as fatal to the Union as if we acknowledged the independence of the Confederacy to-morrow. This is a fact which some simple people, bewildered by he bombastic effusions of "the Conservatives" about liberty and the Constitution, are beginning to forget, but if we all forget it, we [???]o so at the risk of destruction as utter and complete as ever overtook any nation.

abstract: Bibliotheca Sacra for January
snippet: Bibliotheca Sacra for January
lead_paragraph: This scholarly quarterly, edited by Prof. E.A. PARK and Dr. S.H. TAYLOR, of Andover, comes to us in the midst of war with the same demure and thoughtful air, the same unworldly and impassionate tone which it has carried in the meditative times of peace. We like it the more for this, as an assurance that the foundations of society are not yet upturned; that churches, schools, colleges are fixtures; that men of learning and piety expect to have readers for their profoundest speculations, because they have faith in the future of their country -- just as our fathers cared for the future of learning and religion in the midst of the Revolution.

abstract: The obscurity which ...
lead_paragraph: -- The obscurity which has surrounded the right of property in umbrellas, from the days of the daring JONAS HANWAY to days present, is at last cleared away by Yankee ingenuity. A Mr. FOOTE has not only established the doctrine that there is such a thing as ownership of the article, but has showed how to maintain it. His "lock umbrella stand," in itself an ornamental piece of furniture, has the advantage of giving the proprietor the same certainty of possession as if the handle were within his grasp. The moment the umbrella drops to its place in the rack, the handle is by a single movement grasped and held firmly in the clutch of a lock which nothing but the key specially manufactured for the particular depositary can loose. The key, which is practically a pawn-ticket for the article, is of less weight and no greater size than a nickle cent, and adds no perceptible weight to the vest pocket. The invention is at once ingenious and useful. Its introduction into counting-rooms, hotels, offices and halls, and other places of public and private resort, must become general.

abstract: Journal of Commerce repudiating allegiance
snippet: Journal of Commerce repudiating allegiance
lead_paragraph: The "Peace Democrats" are rapidly taking position. The Journal of Commerce, in the leading article of its Saturday's issue, came squarely up to the no-allegiance doctrine, so boldly set forth by MASON, of Virginia, during his best days in the Senate. Said MASON, "I owe no allegiance to this Government -- none whatever; although Virginia is a constituent of this Government, and I am one of her representatives. I owe allegiance to Virginia, and to no one else. The old feudal idea of allegiance was the relation between the subject and sovereign -- between vassal and lord. I know of no sovereign except the State. I take it for granted that Connecticut is the Senator's sovereign, and that if he yields allegiance to this Government he is faithless." The Journal now takes exactly the same ground -- the occasion being a staunch, high-toned, thoroughly patriotic article in the last Princeton Review, on "The War," which was well calculated to disturb the nerves of the Peace Reactionists. We quote from our cotemporary:

abstract: This Bureau, which ...
lead_paragraph: This Bureau, which is a reorganization of a Department of the old Bureau of Ordnance and Hydrography, (the latter erewhile under the direction of that arch-quack and traitor, MAURY,) has been placed under the charge of Admiral C.H. DAVIS, who is now taking steps to render it useful in the general navigation of the country. The Bureau has placed moorings in our Lower Bay for the purpose of testing the accuracy, and discovering the errors of compasses on board of vessels, caused by the local attraction of the iron. A plan of the work is now before us, showing the bearings of all the prominent points in the Lower Bay of New-York. The necessity and utility of this have been long evident to the British Government, and they have acted upon it.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, the resolutions of the New-York Assembly in favor of a reduction of the duty on printing paper, were presented. A memorial from bankers and merchants of New-York  City, asking that the notes of the Government be received for Custom-house dues.
lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the resolutions of the New-York Assembly in favor of a reduction of the duty on printing paper, were presented. A memorial from bankers and merchants of New-York City, asking that the notes of the Government be received for Custom-house dues. A bill to organize a Signal Corps during the rebellion was reported from the Military Committee. A bill for enrolling and calling out the National forces was reported from the same Committee. The Secretary of the Treasury was requested to communicate to the Senate the amount of Government cotton sold in New-York since the establishment of the blockade, &c. A bill to raise additional soldiers for the service of the United States was introduced by Mr. SUMNER, of Massachusetts. A resolution was adopted calling upon the President for information regarding the mission of M. MERCIER, the French Minister to Richmond. The bills relating to the District of Columbia were passed. The Currency bill was taken up and read as the special order. An amendment was adopted increasing the amount of circulating currency from $200,000,000 to $300,000,000. The Senate held an Executive Session and then adjourned.

abstract: We have news from Europe this morning, derived both from French and English sources, that the persevering and suggestive mind of the Emperor has conjured up another expedient for bringing the American difficulty to a ...
lead_paragraph: We have news from Europe this morning, derived both from French and English sources, that the persevering and suggestive mind of the Emperor has conjured up another expedient for bringing the American difficulty to a solution. It is a better, more practicable and more just device than his last. It is simply, as stated by one correspondent, "that Commissioners be delegated by the Federal Government and by the Southern States to meet on neutral ground and confer together, without hostilities being suspended, so that they may advise mutual concessions, and effect a reconciliation so desirable for the interests of the world." There are many difficulties about this plan, and particularly in a democratic form of government, such as both North and South possess; but the difficulties are fewer than appertain to any other plan that has yet been suggested, either here or abroad.

abstract: Good Conduct in Battle
snippet: Good Conduct in Battle
lead_paragraph: -- Col. HIGGINSON, of the First South Carolina Volunteers, furnishes an entertaining official report of the exploits of his black regiment in Florida. He seems to think it necessary to put his case strongly, and in rather exalted language, as well as in such a way as to convince the public that negroes will fight. On the expedition, his battalion was repeatedly under fire -- had rebel cavalry, infantry, and, says he, "even artillery," arranged against them; yet in every instance came off with unblemished honor and undisputed triumph. His men made the most urgent appeals to him to be allowed to press the flying enemy. They exhibited the most fiery energy, beyond anything of which Col. HIGGINSON ever read, unless it was in the case of the French Zouaves. He even says that "it would have been madness, to attempt with the bravest white troops what he successfully accomplished with black ones." No wanton destruction was permitted, no personal outrage desired, during the expedition. The regiment, beside the victories which it achieved, and the large amount of valuable property which it secured, obtained a cannon and a flag, which the Colonel very properly asks permission, for the regiment to retain. The officers and men desire to remain permanently in Florida, and obtain supplies of lumber, iron, &c, for the Government. The Colonel puts forth a very good suggestion, to the effect that "a chain of such posts would completely alter the whole aspect of the war in the seaboard Slave States, and would accomplish what no accumulation of Northern regiments can so easily effect." This is the very use for negro soldiers suggested in the Proclamation of the President. We have no doubt that the whole State of Florida might easily be held for the Government in this way, by a dozen negro regiments.

abstract: It will be
lead_paragraph: -- It will be seen by an order of Gen. HOOKER, that the division of the Army of the Potomac into "Grand Divisions" has been discontinued, and the system of organization by Corps adopted in its stead. The Grand Division plan was the invention of Gen. BURNSIDE, and, perhaps, in itself, was not a bad system. But it was never properly and fully perfected; and, as it was, was found to work very badly. Among the many things which contributed to our failure at Fredericksburgh, this, undoubtedly, though indirectly, was not the least.

abstract: The Board of Aldermen met at 1 o'clock P.M. yesterday. Resolutions were adopted inquiring of the Street Commissioner by what authority earth is removed from Hamilton-square; direct- ...
lead_paragraph: The Board of Aldermen met at 1 o'clock P.M. yesterday. Resolutions were adopted inquiring of the Street Commissioner by what authority earth is removed from Hamilton-square; directing the Special Committee on City Property to ascertain whether the title to certain specified plots of ground (heretofore known as lanes and roads) in Yorkville and Harlem is yet vested in the City; inquiring of the Comptroller the particulars concerning GEORGE LAW's illegal use of a wharf at the Battery for his north shore Staten Island Ferry; and directing the Committee on Wharves and Piers to inquire into and report as to the expediency of constructing stone piers. A resolution directing the Comptroller to stop the unauthorized ferry to Guttenberg from the foot of Spring-street, and to advertise to sell a ferry franchise from that point or its vicinity to the New-Jersey shore, upon the usual conditions, was laid over. A new ordinance to reimburse the relief fund, which will soon be exhausted, was presented by Mr. FARLEY, and laid over under the rule. It provides for an appropriation of $500,000. The Comptroller's weekly financial statement showed the balance in the City Treasury on last Saturday to have been $1,080,297 40. The Comptroller also reported that, for the fortnight ending Jan. 24, $65,532 50 was disbursed from the Relief Fund to 15,916 families, comprising 15,813 adults and 21,420 children. The Board adjourned till 1 o'clock P.M. Thursday.

abstract: By the arrival at Halifax of the steamship Europa, we have advices from Europe three days later than were received by the Hansa. We learn by this arrival further important rumors regarding the intentions of the French Emperor ...
lead_paragraph: By the arrival at Halifax of the steamship Europa, we have advices from Europe three days later than were received by the Hansa. We learn by this arrival further important rumors regarding the intentions of the French Emperor touching the American question. The Paris correspondent of the London Times states that official instructions have been sent to the French Minister at Washington, suggesting that Commissioners be delegated by the North and the South, to meet on neutral ground, and to confer without hostilities being suspended. The Paris Pays publishes a somewhat similar report; also Le Nord. The London correspondent of the Manchester Guardian gives currency to a statement that the rebel Government has been doing a considerable business in England through the medium of cotton warrants -- these warrants being undertakings to deliver so much cotton at a fixed price, so many days after sight, at any Confederate port, after the recognition of the Confederacy. It is said also that the rebels have even addressed proposals to the British Government for some such provisionary transactions. From France, we learn that it has been found necessary to order 6,000 additional reinforcements to Mexico. It is announced that the Duke of Coburg has accepted the Throne of Greece on condition that the House of Bavaria renounces its rights. Other Continental news is not important. There had been a decline in the Liverpool Cotton Market. Breadstuffs were tending downward, and Provisions strong. Consols were quoted at 92 1/2 for money. _____.

abstract: The Respective Forces at
snippet: The Respective Forces at
lead_paragraph: What is probably the real strength of the military and naval forces which the rebels have at Charleston to resist the attack of our army and navy, which is believed to be imminent? We have had statements of all sorts, both from "intelligent negroes" and white blockheads, which make the military forces there anywhere from five to fifty thousand, and the naval force anywhere from one old scow to a whole squadron of iron-clads. The truth, doubtless, lies somewhere betwixt these extremes; but exactly where, we shall probably not know until the day of actual conflict.

abstract: The Tribune makes another attempt to enlighten us as to the meaning and drift of its recent support of Foreign Mediation, and of peace at the end of this campaign.
lead_paragraph: The Tribune makes another attempt to enlighten us as to the meaning and drift of its recent support of Foreign Mediation, and of peace at the end of this campaign. We are sorry to be troublesome, but the subject is one of such importance and the influence of the Tribune is so great, that we hope we shall be excused for what may seem to be unreasonable pertinacity in trying to make its position clear. We assure our neighbor that we can be "induced to meet the issue as he presents it" -- if he will only present it in such a shape that it can be met at all. We assume that he does not mean to shift it from day to day. Let us then go back a little and see if we can fix it with any degree of precision.

abstract: We publish this morning the official reports of the recent affair off Charleston, from Rear Admiral DUPONT, Capt. STELLWAGEN, who commanded the Mercedita, and Lieutenant Commander ABBOTT, Executive Officer of that vessel, who visited ...
lead_paragraph: We publish this morning the official reports of the recent affair off Charleston, from Rear Admiral DUPONT, Capt. STELLWAGEN, who commanded the Mercedita, and Lieutenant Commander ABBOTT, Executive Officer of that vessel, who visited the rebel ram Palmetto State, and held communication with her commander. The main facts, as stated in these official reports, have already been given. It appears, however, that the entire officers and crew of the Mercedita surrendered to and were paroled by the rebels, under circumstances where such a course could not be avoided. We also have details of the affair given by our special correspondent, including a list of casualties on board the two disabled steamers.

abstract: The NEW-YORK TIMES is very gravely mistaken in saving that we ever proposed to make peace in case the rebellion is not subdued in three months. What we did propose was a very different sort of warfare from any we have yet had, with a vast augmentation of our forces by closing West Point, stopping the Coast Survey, and calling out the militia, so as to test the strength of the nation as compared with that of the rebels. We believe the back of the rebellion might thus be broken within three months; but, as the war is now carried on, it may run three years for aught we know, yet prove nothing as to the main point. That the Richmond Dispatch should pervert what we said, gives the TIMES no warrant for doing likewise. Nor has has the TIMES any right to say that we have made personal efforts with M. Mercier or any one else in favor of mediation. The TIMES is already aware of this.

She brings as passenger Col. HENRY C. DEMING, late Acting Mayor of NewOrleans, and Commander of the Twelfth Connecticut Volunteers, who has resigned both positions. A steamer rigged as a bark, supposed to be the pirate Alabama, made her appearance off Southwest Pass on the 23d ult. She was apparently watching for signals. A number of the Pass pilots have been placed under arrest for communicating with her. The rebels at Sabine Pass destroyed the ship Morning Light, a short time after capturing her, on the approach of some of our gunboats from Galveston. The schooner captured by them was the transport Velocity.

abstract: Ella Warley; Steamer, Sunk by Collission off Sandy Hook
snippet: Ella Warley; Steamer, Sunk by Collission off Sandy Hook
lead_paragraph: The steamship North Star, (United States transport,) Capt. LEFEVRE, from New-Orleans Jan. 30, via Key West on the 4th inst., with passenger, to United States Quartermaster, arrived at 8 o'clock yesterday morning. She reports that last night, when off the Woodlands, (near Sandy Hook,) she came in collision with the steamship Ella Warley, hence for New-Orleans, striking her forward of the wheel on the starboard side, crushing in the boilers, and sinking her in twenty minutes. Her first Assistant Engineer, two firemen, two coal-passers and a boy, were lost, who, it is supposed, were scalded to death. The passengers and crew were rescued by the boats, and brought back to this City.

abstract: -- We have news, this morning, of a brisk skirmish in Upper Georgia, between a body of citizens of the State and the rebel troops sent to put down the disaffection in that region. It is likely enough to be true. There were several such skirmishes in East Tennessee a year ago. But they were all suppressed, and the men engaged in them have nearly all been drafted into the rebel army. We presume these outbreaks in Georgia will have the same result. There are strong elements of disaffection, rebellion and revolution against the Confederacy all over the South among the poor whites, but they cannot be availed of as Union elements until the rebel Government is overthrown.
lead_paragraph: -- We have news, this morning, of a brisk skirmish in Upper Georgia, between a body of citizens of the State and the rebel troops sent to put down the disaffection in that region. It is likely enough to be true. There were several such skirmishes in East Tennessee a year ago. But they were all suppressed, and the men engaged in them have nearly all been drafted into the rebel army. We presume these outbreaks in Georgia will have the same result. There are strong elements of disaffection, rebellion and revolution against the Confederacy all over the South among the poor whites, but they cannot be availed of as Union elements until the rebel Government is overthrown.

It provides for building an island on Oak Orchard Shoals, and erecting suitable buildings thereon -- the present Board of Commissioners to be continued three years. A resolution to adjourn over from the 19th to the 25th inst., was adopted. The general bill legalizing the State bounties to volunteers was made the special order for Thursday, at noon. The Committee on Banks made an unfavorable report on the proposition of the Commissioners of the Canal Fund, that the principal and interest of the State debt should be paid in coin.

lead_paragraph: Mr. ISAAC COOK, of Chicago, Ill., has commenced a suit in the United States Court against The Tribune Association to answer for an alleged libel against him. The capias laying the damages at $50,000 was issued on Monday, and was placed in the hands of U.S. Deputy Marshal PEALE, who went to the Tribune office in search of Mr. GREELEY soon afterward to serve it. He did not find him there, and at a later hour he went over again, but Mr. GREELEY had not then arrived.

abstract: New-York; Byrnes, Thos; Trial of Dennis P. Sullivan
snippet: New-York; Byrnes, Thos; Trial of Dennis P. Sullivan
lead_paragraph: The trial of DENNIS P. SULLIVAN for the murder of THOMAS BYRNES, late Superintendent of Lands and Places, commenced in this Court before Judge LEONARD on Monday. It will be recollected that the homicide of Mr. BYRNES occurred in Greenwich-street, between Liberty and Cedar streets, early on the morning of the 29th of November last, a few days before the Charter election. The prisoner, it appears, was engaged in posting handbills for the opposition candidate to the Democracy, and, as is alleged, was attacked by BYRNES and his party, who attempted to interfere with his work. An altercation ensued, during which SULLIVAN discharged a pistol, the ball taking effect in the abdomen of BYRNES, who died from the wound at 5 P.M. the same day. The homicide gave rise to a good deal of excitement among the politicians of the First Ward at the time, and had an important bearing on the Aldermanic canvass then pending. The present trial seems to be attended with equal feeling, and the Court-room was crowded with First Ward politicians, and friends of the deceased and of the prisoner.

abstract: New-Orleans, the Distress in
snippet: New-Orleans, the Distress in
lead_paragraph: One of our New-Orleans correspondents writes us concerning the terrible condition of the poor in that city. The destruction of its trade and commerce, by the blocking of the Mississippi River, has long kept them out of work; and more than thirty thousand men, women and children, of all nations, (but mostly natives of the British isles,) have, since our occupation of the city, been supported by charity. Thousands of men who had joined the Confederate army left their wives and families behind them to starve; and though "registered enemies" of both sexes have been permitted to go within the rebel lines, very few of the residents have chosen to avail themselves of the opportunity. Gen. BUTLER mitigated the distress by putting the idle men to work on city improvements, at the city's expense; and also by levying contributions on the rich rebels, who were responsible for the unfortunate state of things. Gen. BANKS, by a recent order, announced his purpose to continue the policy of levying on property, but he has not yet carried the plan fully into effect, and has thought it prudent to stop entirely the public works. As a consequence, the distress is now nearly as great as ever, and thousands of miserable, helpless and unemployed creatures are wandering round the city, and besieging the offices of the Union authorities for aid.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, the bill to reorganize the Post-office Department was passed. A bill to authorize an increase of Major and Brigadier Generals was reported from the Military Committee. The President was called upon for any correspondence with the French Government on the subject of mediation, arbitration, or other means looking to a termination of the war. The National Currency bill was then taken up, and Mr. SHERMAN, of Ohio, proceeded to explain its provisions. Various amendments were proposed and rejected, and the Senate adjourned without coming to any conclusion on the bill.

In one case the struggle is about to be renewed on the same ground; in the other apparently but a few miles further South.

abstract: Speech before Democrat Union Association
snippet: Speech before Democrat Union Association
lead_paragraph: The Headquarters of the Democratic Union Association, corner of Broadway and Twenty-second-street, were crowded last evening, to listen to an address from Mr. JOHN VAN BUREN. Although the house was full at 7 1/2 o'clock, neither officers nor speaker appeared until 8 1/2 o'clock, at which time the audience, becoming impatient, called for a few brief remarks from Commodore NUTT, Gen. Thumb, "or any other man." While these calls were loudest, Mr. VAN BUREN appeared, and was greeted with enthusiastic cheering. He was accompanied to and on the platform by Mr. LUKE COZZENS, President, Mr. JAS. B. MURRAY, H.S. CLINTON, Esq., Prof. MASON and Judge PARKER, of Albany, all of whom were seated beside the speaker.

abstract: The iron-clad Sangamon, which our Washington correspondent mentioned as being ordered South in 96 hours, has been completed. She was put formally in commission at Chester, Penn., on Monday, her ship's company having been all on board. She left yesterday for Port Royal, via Fortress Monroe. Her crew, consisting of 19 seamen, 10 ordinary seamen, 18 landsmen, 2 boys, 3 first-class firemen and 7 coal-heavers, making a total of 69, were taken from the Navy-yard to Chester in a tugboat. Capt. GUEST, the commander of the Sangamon, the Commandant at the Navy-yard, and several other naval officers, were on board the tug. On reaching Chester the iron-clad moved out into the stream and anchored. Capt. GUEST then took charge of the Monitor, and, after the men had been called together, addressed them in a brief and patriotic speech. The wharves in front of the yard where the iron-clad was built were crowded with citizens of Chester, who were anxious to see the Sangamon leave for her destination.
