abstract: His Reply to the Senate on Alleged Communication with Rebel Authorities
snippet: His Reply to the Senate on Alleged Communication with Rebel Authorities
lead_paragraph: -- It will be seen that Secretary SEWARD has furnished to the President, who has transmitted to the Senate, a very explicit, specific, and decisive answer to the resolution of that body, alleging that he had held, through M. MERCIER, communication with the rebel authorities in Richmond. The Senatorial allegation against Mr. SEWARD was based upon a very unjust misconstruction of a passage in a dispatch of M. MERCIER to the French Government, which we published on the 6th inst. Why the Senate should have taken up the matter, and given it the shape of a direct charge, it is difficult, or perhaps not so difficult, to tell. But we should think the Secretary's reply would prevent a repetition of such shameful assaults in the future. Speaking evil falsely against authorities has attained such a fearful extent as nearly to break down the confidence of the country in every one of its rulers. Senators have been convicted of it twice, and each time in reference to the same functionary, within a few weeks. Let them avoid it altogether in the future, if they would retain the respect of the country themselves.

abstract: In the Senate yesterday the bill to amend the  charter of Brooklyn was reported favorably; also, the bills to extend the Chenango Canal. Among the bills introduced was one relative to the acknowledgment of legal instruments by persons in foreign countries.
lead_paragraph: In the Senate yesterday the bill to amend the charter of Brooklyn was reported favorably; also, the bills to extend the Chenango Canal. Among the bills introduced was one relative to the acknowledgment of legal instruments by persons in foreign countries. Consideration of the Albany and Susquehannah Railroad bill, as the special order, was resumed in Committee of the Whole, and after debate it was ordered to a third reading. The bill confirming the acts of Gov. MORGAN relative to the payment of bounties was also ordered to a third reading. A bill to protect the harbor of New-York against invasion was introduced by Mr. MURPHY. It appropriates $500,000, to be reimbursed by the General Government.

abstract: At an early hour on the morning of Jan. 16, 1859, there were committed, in the Sixth Ward of this City, two of those deliberate and unprovoked murders for which that portion of our city has for very many years been notorious. On the morning cited, a man named DECKER was shot twice in his own house in Elm street by ruffians outside; and almost ...
lead_paragraph: At an early hour on the morning of Jan. 16, 1859, there were committed, in the Sixth Ward of this City, two of those deliberate and unprovoked murders for which that portion of our city has for very many years been notorious. On the morning cited, a man named DECKER was shot twice in his own house in Elm street by ruffians outside; and almost at the same time a respectable citizen of Brooklyn, while passing homeward, on the other side of the street, was shot through the heart and lungs, and died immediately. The occurrence created considerable excitement at the time; and unusual efforts were made to bring to light all the circumstances connected with the murders. Full reports were published in the TIMES, of the proceedings from the morning of the murders until the perpetrators were sent to the State Prison. At the time it was considered a clearer case against the accused, than the vast majority of similar cases brought before the Court; and as there is now a strong effort making to influence Gov. SEYMOUR to pardon the convicted men and thereby set them loose again upon society, it may not be amiss to refresh our memories in relation to the case and the characters of those convicted of the offences as they were developed during the trial. Both murders were committed soon after midnight of the 15th of January. At that time JOHN GLASS, an exconstable of the Sixth Ward, and several others, rang the door-bell of No. 21 Elm-street, a reputed house of ill-fame, kept by WILHELM DECKER, a German, who refused them admittance. They then forced their way in, rushed up stairs, and commenced smashing mirrors, chairs, and whatever else in the way of furniture they could lay their hands on. Mr. DECKER hurried after them to protect his property. Seeing him, one of the party of invaders immediately extinguished the light in the hall, and all rushed into the street, leaving the hall-door open. DECKER proceeded to close it, when two shots were fired in quick succession. Both balls passed through the door, and struck DECKER -- one taking effect just behind his left ear, penetrating the skull, and lodging there. The other was imbedded in the muscles of the chest, having first entered the back on the left side, and described an erratic course in a forward and upward direction. DECKER fell helpless, and a few days afterward died of the wounds thus received. When the two pistol shots were fired, Mr. RICHARD OWENS, a master rigger and stevedore, then doing an extensive business in New-York, and residing in Brooklyn, to which latter place he was proceeding, was passing on the other side of the street at the time. Hearing the cries of DECKER, he halted to learn what was the matter, and was almost immediately shot through the heart and lungs, falling dead upon the street. JOHN GLASS and a man named JAMES HIGGINS were arrested very soon afterwards and locked up in the Sixth Ward Station-house. WILLIAM MYERS, a step-son of DECKER, positively identified JOHN GLASS as the person who fired the two shots at the door from the street. He was standing on the opposite side of the street at the time, and knew GLASS from having seen him often before at his father's house. At the same time he saw a man cross the street, (Mr. OWENS,) and fearing that there would be more shooting he ran up the street, but had hardly turned around when a third shot was fired, though he did not see who fired it -- the shot which killed Mr. OWENS. DECKER subsequently identified the prisoners as of the party who broke into his house. Additional testimony implicating JAMES GLASS, a brother of JOHN, and JAMES LOFTUS, then a constable. LOFEUS was arrested as soon as implicated, but JAMES GLASS escaped the police for awhile, but was finally captured. It was given in evidence that soon after the murders, JAMES GLASS handed a pistol quietly to JOHN QUINLAN, who put it in his pocket, and kept it until Capt. DOWLING, of the Police, obtained it from him. It was a six-barreled revolver, with three of the chambers loaded and three empty. After a full hearing the Coroner's jury, investigating the causes of the death of RICHARD OWENS, rendered a verdict to the effect that he came to his death by pistol-shot wound at the hands of JOHN GLASS; and that GLASS was aided and abetted by JAMES HIGGINS, JAMES LOFTUS, JAMES GLASS and JOHN QUINLAN. The cases were tried in the Court of Oyer and Terminer, and during the trials the Court-room was densely packed with the friends of the accused and members of rival associations in the same Ward. The influence of the accused, political and otherwise, secured them excellent counsel, and everything was done to insure an acquittal which legal skill could devise. But with all, JOHN GLASS and JAMES HIGGINS were convicted, and on the 7th of May, 1859, were sentenced to the State Prison, each for the term of twenty years, and on the 16th of June following JAMES GLASS was sentenced by the same Court to the State Prison for life. JOHN GLASS was one of the constables of the Sixth Ward, as we have stated, for the year ending December, 1858, and for a long time had the reputation of being a hardened and desperate character. Previous to the killing of DECKER and OWENS, GLASS had been arrested often for assaults. He was a member of Engine Co. No. 21, but had been expelled by the Company some months before the time of the murders. JAMES GLASS, his brother, kept a drinking saloon at No. 19 Elm-street. JAMES HIGGINS had also established a reputation for recklessness and disregard of human life. He had not followed any legitimate calling for several years prior to his conviction. These are the men the new Governor is now asked to pardon, and it is thought by their friends that, with the influence they can bring to bear upon him, they have some chance of success for their petition, which is said to have been signed by several yards of names. Nearly every working Democrat is aware there is, and has been for years, rival factions in the Sixth Ward, the more prominent being known as the "Dead Rabbits," and the other as the friends and adherents of Mr. BRENNAN. It is the "Dead Rabbits," as alleged, who are now exerting themselves to secure the release of the three caged members of their gang; and it is said that they have secured the names of quite a number of persons to their petition -- names which will be read with interest, in such a connection, by the people, if they can be obtained from the original document. It has been suggested that before granting the prayer of the petition, it might be well for the Governor to consult with Mr. WATERBURY, now his Advocate-General, then prosecuting Attorney, and Justice DOWLING, then Captain of Police -- both of whom are familiar with the case and the character of the men convicted.

abstract: Restoration to Rank
snippet: Restoration to Rank
lead_paragraph: -- We learn from Washington that the President has restored to the rank of Brigadier-General of Volunteers, Major H.W. BENHAM, of the Engineer Corps of the army, and has assigned him to a command in Gen. HOOKER's army. Gen. BENHAM is an officer of excellent judgment and high efficiency. His deprival of rank was in consequence of his having, as was alleged, fought the battle on James Island, near Charleston, in June last, contrary to orders, and at the great disadvantage of assailing the enemy in an impregnable position. Against these representations, Gen. BENHAM has strenuously remonstrated, declaring that the movement was within the line of his orders, and was undertaken upon the fullest information that the enemy's position was entirely assailable; and these assertions have been sustained by his colleagues and by the Colonels of the regiments under his command.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, an adverse report was made from the Military Committee on the bill to construct a marine cable. The same Committee was discharged from the further consideration of the bill for the construction of a military and postal road from Washington to New-York.
lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, an adverse report was made from the Military Committee on the bill to construct a marine cable. The same Committee was discharged from the further consideration of the bill for the construction of a military and postal road from Washington to New-York. The bill to amend the Fugitive Slave act was reported adversely upon by the Judiciary Committee. The bill to allow the United States to prosecute appeals and writs of error without giving security was passed. The bill for the removal of the Winnebago Indians from Minnesota was passed. The bill to increase the number of Generals was debated but not acted upon. The bill to aid Missouri in, emancipating her slaves came up as the special order, but was postponed to give place to the Finance bill, which was debated until the adjournment. It was agreed that a vote should be taken at 1 o'clock to-day.

abstract: The late collision of the steamer North Star with the Ella Warley, as fully described in the TIMES of yesterday, is still a topic of general conversation "down town." Owing to the many rumors afloat to the effect that the Ella Warley was lost in consequence ...
lead_paragraph: The late collision of the steamer North Star with the Ella Warley, as fully described in the TIMES of yesterday, is still a topic of general conversation "down town." Owing to the many rumors afloat to the effect that the Ella Warley was lost in consequence of the culpable negligence of the officers of that vessel, and that the said officers were in an unfit condition to navigate her at the time of the collision, the officers of the Warley have united in a protest against credence being given to reports reflecting on their capacity or condition at the time of the disaster, which protest, verified by affidavits, will be given to the various marine insurance companies affected by the loss of their steamer. We give the main points of it below:

abstract: Movements; Independent State Action by the Copperheads
snippet: Movements; Independent State Action by the Copperheads
lead_paragraph: The Copperheads are fast getting into line. They of Indiana briskly follow those of New-Jersey and Illinois. In fact, they take the track with a little more fierceness. The others have as yet only asked for an armistice; these demand one, and threaten independent State action unless the Government complies. If the present Congress will not authorize a Convention of all the States, they present as an alternative that Indiana, by her delegates, will meet as many of the States, both Confederate and National, as will send delegates to Nashville, and proceed to make peace on their own responsibility.

abstract: Emperor, the, new proffered Mediation in United States
snippet: Emperor, the, new proffered Mediation in United States
lead_paragraph: It is extraordinary that a man of the practical sagacity of the French Emperor, and with a personal knowledge like his of the character of the American people, derived from a prolonged sojourn in our midst, should cling to the idea that he can be of some service in promoting peace between our Government and those in rebellion against it. There never was a completer hallucination. If one-third of France were in revolt against the government of NAPOLEON III., or one-third of England against the government of Queen VICTORIA, most assuredly neither of them would listen for an instant to any proffer by the Government of the United States of friendly offices, calculated to bring about an arrangement between the "belligerent" parties. Either of them would repel it, if not as an indignity, at least as an impertinence. But our case is immeasurably stronger than that. The question with us is not simply a question as to the national head, but as to the national existence. It is not simply whether this Republic shall be presided over by ABRAHAM LINCOLN, whose authority, to say the least, is quite as rightful as that of NAPOLEON the Emperor or VICTORIA the Queen, but far beyond that -- it is whether the Republic itself shall exist. It is the same question as would arise in France or in England, were it attempted to detach a third part of their territory, and form it into an independent nation. Their present rulers might be deposed by revolution, as some of their past ones have been, without in anywise affecting the national life. This sort of revolutionary work is not to be compared in audacity or fatality with that other which would cut the nation in two. But if the European sovereigns would not at all abide our coming between them and revolutionists of the first kind, how can they imagine that we will abide their coming between us and revolutionists of the second? If they would never permit their dynastic lives to be put into negotiation, what sort of human beings must they take us to be in fancying that we can be made willing to let our very national life itself be put into negotiation?

abstract: Legislature's Mission to Richmond
snippet: Legislature's Mission to Richmond
lead_paragraph: -- It seems that the rebels not only have preliminary knowledge of all military movements in the North, but of all political schemes. A fortnight ago there was quite a little flurry in Richmond and in the Confederate Congress over the intelligence that Commissioners from several Northern Legislatures had arrived there to treat with the rebels. No proposition of this kind had yet been made in any Northern Legislature, and the Northern public had no knowledge that any such plan had been projected. Yet it seems the rebel news was only a short time in advance of the fact, or at least the suggestion of it. Since then, resolutions to send Commissioners to Richmond have been introduced in one State Legislature, and the same thing has been strongly urged in two others. We presume that the rebels must have had knowledge that the plan would positively be adopted, for the foreshadowings of Northern devices in Richmond usually turn out accurate. The question is, whether Mr. JAMES SMITH, of Newark, who introduced the resolutions into the New-Jersey Legislature, and the copperheads who have broached the subject in the Legislatures of Indiana, and Illinois, have been in secret correspondence with the rebel authorities upon the subject.

abstract: We publish this morning the diplomatic correspondence sent to the Senate yesterday by the President, in response to the resolution adopted a day or two ago, calling for any correspondence between our Government and that of France on the subject of mediation.
lead_paragraph: We publish this morning the diplomatic correspondence sent to the Senate yesterday by the President, in response to the resolution adopted a day or two ago, calling for any correspondence between our Government and that of France on the subject of mediation. It embraces sundry letters that passed between Mr. DAYTON, M. DROUYN DE LHUYS and Mr. SEWARD during the lost four months. All the documents are of great interest, and some of them of the highest importance. In all his suggestions or offers of mediation, the French Minister expresses the greatest regard for the honor and independence of the American Government; and in the various replies to these suggestions and offers, Mr. SEWARD is firm and decided in expressing the refusal of this Government to entertain any proposition in regard to the conduct of our domestic affairs from any foreign quarter whatsoever.

snippet: Mediation; Diplomatic Correspondence; Diplomatic Correspondence; Paris Letter, Jan. 23
lead_paragraph: The attention of the French people is today almost exclusively directed to the suffering from the cotton crisis. The Emperor has given another hundred thousand francs from his private purse, and he has decreed a gift from the State Treasury of five millions of francs, one-half i to be distributed as charity by the Minister of the Interior, and the other half by the Minister of Agriculture and Commerce as salary on public works to be created expressly for the employment of men out of work. The contributions from public charity are immense in number but small in the total amount, owing to the fact that in France more than elsewhere, there are an immense number of persons capable of giving small sums Thus, in all the shops, in all the corporations, as such, even in the different corps of the militia and the army, five and ten sous subscriptions are proposed, and generally acquiesced in by the whole body. But as said before, the total of these is but a small sum, and the number of large subscriptions is limited -- the fact is, that of the Emperor is about the only one, for between his subscription of forty thousand dollars, and that of the Prince NAPOLEON of six hundred dollars, there is not one.

Also, all official orders, reports and documents, and the latest and fullest Washington news, European news, with graphic letters from our correspondents in London and Paris, giving the tone of public feeling abroad, is  made a special and permanent feature. abstract: The ship Hope, Capt. HANCOCK, arrived here yesterday from New-York, with provisions, &c., for the relief of the distressed operatives in Lancashire. She took up her anchorage in the Mersey, opposite the Birkenhead Docks. The Hope is a fine new ship. She sailed from New-York on the 22d December. Her cargo consists of 1,010 barrels of flour and 987 tons of guano, both of which, we understand, will be sold at this port, and the proceeds forwarded to the Central Relief Committee at Manchester. The Hope was towed into the river free of charge, and she will be exempted from pilotage, light, port, dock, and all other dues to which other ships are subjected. The ship is consigned to Messrs. BABCOCK & Co. of this town, who have undertaken the part of consignees free of all expense.

abstract: THE EASTERN DISTRICT PIERS. -- Some time since the Brooklyn Common Council passed resolutions appropriating certain sums for the erection of piers at the foot of South Seventh, South Fourth and North Sixth streets, Eastern District, the object being to afford accommodation for the shipping interest. lead_paragraph: AMERICAN INSTITUTE -- ANNUAL ELECTION OF OFFICERS. -- The annual election of officers and Committees of the American Institute was held yesterday at the rooms of the Institute, Cooper Union Building, the polls being open from 3 to 7 o'clock P.M. The following gentlemen were elected without opposition: President, WM. HALL; Vice-Presidents, Dudley S. Gregory, Edward Walker, Sylvester Comstock; According Secretary, Thomas McElrath; Corresponding Secretary, John Torrey; Treasurer, Benedict Lewis, Jr.; Finance Committee, Thomas M. Adriance, John M. Reed, Wm.S. Slocum, Thomas Williams, Jr., George Peyton. Besides the above there were twenty-four managers of the Fair elected, and Committees on Library, Agriculture, Manufactures, Science and Art, Commerce, Admission of Members, Correspondence and Repository -- five members each.

She was an iron screw steamer, with three masts, fore-and-aft-rigged on the lower masts, and three yards across aloft, on fore and mainmast, and has one pipe. Upon approaching she showed a white color, but subsequently she hoisted the American ensign. It was probably the Alabama, as it answers her description.

abstract: The Promenade Concert given to aid the Woman's Relief Association, at the Academy of Music, last evening, was a remarkable success, and must have furnished a most gratifying increase to the means of the Association, which was organized for and has long been engaged in preparing comfortable clothing and other necessaries for the sick and wounded soldiers of the Union army.
lead_paragraph: The Promenade Concert given to aid the Woman's Relief Association, at the Academy of Music, last evening, was a remarkable success, and must have furnished a most gratifying increase to the means of the Association, which was organized for and has long been engaged in preparing comfortable clothing and other necessaries for the sick and wounded soldiers of the Union army. Notwithstanding the storm, the Academy was crowded by a delightful and delighted audience; the music furnished by the Seventh Regiment Band, under the lead of Mr. E. GRAFULLA, was excellent, and the old and new flags of the famous Brooklyn Fourteenth, added, in no small degree, to the interest of the occasion. When the music in par first, had been played, S.B. CHITTENDEN, Esq., ascended the platform upon the stage, and briefly and appropriately introduced to the audience Rev. Dr. BELLOWS.

abstract: Copperhead Peace-Plotters in Western Legislatures
snippet: Copperhead Peace-Plotters in Western Legislatures
lead_paragraph: The loyal members of the Illinois Legislature have threatened to withdraw, and leave the two Houses without the constitutional two-thirds quorum, in order to prevent the passage of the Armistice and Convention res olutions of the Copperhead majority. This expedient has been, in time past, more than once resorted to by the Democratic party of Indiana, in order to prevent the election of a political opponent to the United States Senate. But these are wretched precedents, established by reckless men; and we are happy to learn that, though sorely tried, the loyal men of the Western Legislatures have concluded to take advantage of no such example, and stand to their positions. Let the event be what it may, it is of the first importance that the regular constitutional Government should be, in all respects, strictly maintained by every friend of the war, for that alone is the principle on which the war rightly rests.

abstract: This  vessel, which arrived here on Sunday from off Charleston, S.C., is a beautiful propeller of 470 tons. She has an iron hull, new and splendid machinery, and is said to be able to make from fourteen to sixteen miles an hour. In appearance, she is very much like the prize steamer Lodona, which was captured off Charleston last summer and brought to this port.
lead_paragraph: This vessel, which arrived here on Sunday from off Charleston, S.C., is a beautiful propeller of 470 tons. She has an iron hull, new and splendid machinery, and is said to be able to make from fourteen to sixteen miles an hour. In appearance, she is very much like the prize steamer Lodona, which was captured off Charleston last summer and brought to this port. To aid the Princess Royal in running the blockade, her hull was painted the color of our naval vessels, and she might have been readily mistaken for one of them. The papers of the prize steamer were placed in the hands of Commissioner FLANDERS yesterday, and thesteamer will be handed over to the United States Marshal to-day or to-morrow. Meanwhile the powder (100 kegs) will be removed from her hold and placed in the magazine. -- Philadelphia Ledger, Feb. 10.

abstract: The prolongation of the war, though it has been productive of much suffering and of much loss, is nevertheless proving instrumental in furnishing us abundantly with the thing, of all others, which, as a nation, we most needed experience.
lead_paragraph: The prolongation of the war, though it has been productive of much suffering and of much loss, is nevertheless proving instrumental in furnishing us abundantly with the thing, of all others, which, as a nation, we most needed -- experience. There is one point in particular, and the most important, perhaps, of all those which now interest us, upon which the events of each day are casting a flood of light. We are having, in short, what nothing short of a struggle of great violence and intensity could possibly have afforded us -- a practical exemplification of the nature and tendencies of the theory that the United States form simply a confederacy, as opposed to the theory that they form a nation. The secession of the Southern States is, of course, an illustration on a gigantic scale of the legitimate results of the doctrine that each State has the right to quit the Union at pleasure.

abstract: Never since the war begun has matters been so dull at the Navy-yard as at present. Although there are over 4,500 men on the payroll, whose monthly wages must reach $220,000, there are only four or five vessels in hand, and none of them requiring night work. Loads of immense shot and shell are being conveyed from the wharves to the pyramids. The new addition to the Ordnance Department is nearly finished. There is no Court-martial in the Lyceum, which is a very rare occurrence. There are a couple of hundred blue jackets on board the North Carolina, but nearly all of them assigned to ships in, or about to go into, commission. The 15-inch guns for the Roanoke are almost ready to be sent aboard. The new vessels on the stocks, the Maumee, Mackinaw, Shamrock and Miaminmoah, are progressing gradually, but will not be ready for sea service for many months. The following statement will explain with sufficient distinctness the condition of the fleet at anchor:

abstract: At the opening of the Court, yesterday morning, Ex-Recorder JAMES M. SMITH, commenced the summing up for the defence. It being nearly 3 o'clock when he closed his argument, Judge LEONARD adjourned the Court to 10 o'clock this morning, when the District-Attorney will sum up for the people and the case will be given to the jury under the charge of the Court.

abstract: On the 1st of January the American Minister at Copenhagen, Mr. WOOD, presented to the King of Denmark a pair of Colt's revolvers, the gift of the President of the United States to his Majesty. On delivering the pistols, after the usual felicitations, ...
lead_paragraph: On the 1st of January the American Minister at Copenhagen, Mr. WOOD, presented to the King of Denmark a pair of Colt's revolvers, the gift of the President of the United States to his Majesty. On delivering the pistols, after the usual felicitations, Mr. WOOD is reported to have said that the revolvers were an American invention, of American material and manufacture, and that it his Majesty should ever have occasion to use them in defence of his kingdom and the rights and privileges of his people, (now among the freest in Europe,) he would find them us true as the material of which they were made, and as unerring as justice and right.

abstract: McDowell, Maj.-Gen., the personal defence of
snippet: McDowell, Maj.-Gen., the personal defence of
lead_paragraph: We publish this morning the personal defence of Gen. MCDOWELL, presented to the Court of Inquiry on Tuesday last. Those who have not had time or disposition to bring together all the loose ends of the evidence given in the case, which we have published from day to day during the months in which the trial has been going on, will find in this document a capital resume of the facts, -- put, of course, in a light favorable to the speaker, but at the same time apparently calm, just and truthful. It is not for the public or the Press, of course, to prejudge the decision of the Court of Inquiry. It may be favorable, it may be adverse, but certainly Gen. MCDOWELL seems to have very effectually disposed of the main part of the charges that have been made against him.

abstract: Russell, William Howard; My Diary North and South
snippet: Russell, William Howard; My Diary North and South
lead_paragraph: America to the Englishman is as inexhaustible a subject as Africa. Nothing would seem easier than to travel through either country, and not write a book about it, but nothing to the thoroughbred Englishman is more impossible. Under both the American and African suns everything is new to him -- prairies and deserts, hippopotami, prairie chickens, hyenas, possums, rhinoceroses and red squirrels -- he finds none of these in his country preserves, nor yet in those remote parts of the United Kingdom whither he annually resorts to chase the grouse to its nest, and track the rampant hare to its inscrutable den. As with animals, so with the people. Whiskers and waistcoats are of a different cut from those that have met his vision in "Lunnun." If he attempt a neat little excursion through the interior of Africa, natives rush around him, rub their noses against his in an affectionate manner -- generally contriving to rub his up the wrong way -- ask him into their huts, and perhaps offer him a small baked alligator, or a bit of boiled negro for supper. Sometimes they skin him, which may please him better, for we are not entirely sure that in the majority of cases the representative Englishman would not prefer being skinned to being treated in a hospitable manner. For it is an indisputable fact, that he always finds fault with his entertainers, and that the more he is feted and caressed, the more he grumbles.

abstract: Without a single flourish, this document yet stirs the blood like the blast of a trumpet. abstract: NEW-YORK JUVENILE ASYLUM. -- The New-York Juvenile Asylum, which adopts, in behalf of the State, the orphan and the outcast, and opens even to them the way to a happy life, is in a flourishing condition, as appears from the annual report for the past year. At the commencement of the past year there were 516 children in the institution, and during the year 957 children were committed. Of this number 442 were again discharged by magistrates and 262 by committee; 223 were indentured, 5 escaped and 5 died, leaving 473 remaining at the commencement of the present year. The average number for the year was 548. and the average time of each child in the asylum is six months. The asylum buildings, situated near the High Bridge, are now in a state of completeness, by which a higher condition of health and comfort is attained. The excellent system of juvenile emigration to the West, which was inaugurated by the directors of the institution, is working most beneficially. During that time over 1,000 children have been indentured in Illinois, and those of the earlier companies are now arriving at manhood and womanhood, and are entering upon their various careers in life. Sixty-four boys have joined the army, and are now in the field. Eleven are members of a company recruited by their pastor, Rev. Mr. TODD, of Washington County, Ill., mostly from his own church. This company, known in the regiment as the "Psalm Singing Company," went into one of the recent battles in Missouri chanting the beautiful words of the Twenty-third Psalm.

abstract: An evening paper is elated with the idea that our Government has now muskets enough to arm the loyalists of East Tennessee and other parts of the South, and argues that "there is no way of carrying on the war so cheap as to arm our friends who dwell in the interior of rebeldom." We are glad to learn the fact first mentioned, and we perfectly agree with the statement following it. It is pleasing also to learn that 20,000 stand of arms are turned out monthly at the Springfield armory, and that we are offered muskets and rifles from Austria at prices scarcely higher than are paid for children's guns at a toy shop.

abstract: THE BOUNTY FRAUD CASES. -- The trial of Capt. CARTWRIGHT and Lieut. LAMBERT, indicted for conspiracy on the charge of attempting to defraud the Volunteer Bounty Committee of Kings County, out of bounty moneys, by presenting recruits who falsely swore that they were residents of Kings County, was concluded in the Court of Sessions yesterday. A great portion of the alleged fraudulent operations, it appears, transpired in New-York, and therefore was beyond the jurisdiction of this Court. The Judge, however, charged that if the parties were believed to have confederated themselves together in this County for the purpose of defrauding the Bounty Committee appointed by the Supervisors, by inducing parties to represent themselves as residents when they were not, and to enlist when under the required age, with the understanding that they were not to be troubled thereafter, the jury would bring the prisoners in guilty as charged in the indictment. The jury retired at 11 o'clock A.M., and came into Court at 5 o'clock, unable to agree upon a verdict. They were thereupon discharged and the prisoners were remanded for further action. The jury is understood to have been eleven for conviction and one for acquittal. It being intimated that one of the jurymen had been tampered with, the matter will probably undergo further investigation.

abstract: The news from the Southwest this morning is of an important character. The rebels are said to be again advancing up the Mobile and Ohio Railroad, having already reached Okoloma, where they are trying to repair that portion of the road destroyed by Gen. GRANT. They are also hurrying troops to Vicksburgh, in anticipation of the attack there. It is asserted that a large part of the Army of Virginia is already there, and that Mobile has been left with only four thousand men, the rest having been sent to swell the Vicksburgh host. The railroad from Selma, Ala., to Meridian, Miss., has been completed, and the concentration of the rebel forces is thus rendered an easy matter. A barge, loaded with coal for the Queen of the West, ran the Vicksburgh blockade on Sunday last.

abstract: Conscription Insurrection Round Warsaw
snippet: Conscription Insurrection Round Warsaw
lead_paragraph: A threatening insurrection had broken out in the provinces around Warsaw, in consequence, as was supposed, of the Conscription which had recently taken place there. Two thousand of the Conscripts enrolled at Warsaw had deserted, but hostages were seized in their places. Three bands of insurgents had assembled, one in the direction of Minsk, 8 versts from Warsaw, the second at Blonie near Surock, and the third at Outtusk. A Warsaw telegram of the 24th ult. says: "On the night of the 22d, attacks were everywhere made upon the detachment of troops separately cantoned. The insurgents killed all the soldiers they found in the houses where they were billeted.

abstract: The Dublin Freeman says: "On Friday last, about 2 o'clock, a smart looking screw-steamer, named the Georgiana, arrived at Holyhead from Liverpool for a supply of coals. The craft is a tender to the well-known Alabama, and laden with arms and ammunition. She has a crew of sixty men, all picked, consisting of English, Irish, Scotch and Welsh. They are bearded, and most ferocious-looking sea dogs. She has a large quantity of tea and other necessaries on board for the Alabama, and carries twenty-eight guns. It is stated that she steams sixteen miles an hour, and is bound for Nassau -- her crew having signed articles for that port -- and will probably run the blockade to Charleston. She left Holyhead on Saturday."

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, Mr. SUMNER's bill to raise additional soldiers (colored) for the service of the United States, was reported back from the Military Committee, with a recommendation that it do not pass, as authority is sufficiently granted in the act of July 17, 1862. The bill to withhold the pay of officers absent from duty was also reported. The bill to secure to men in the Department of the West their pay, bounty and pensions was passed. A bill to provide for an Assistant Treasurer of the United States was reported from the Finance Committee. A bill relative to the compensation of Inspectors of Customs at the Port of New-York was reported from the same Committee. Mr. WILSON, of Massachusetts, introduced his bill for the reorganization of the Engineer Corps. At the expiration of the morning hour the bill to provide ways and means for the support of the Government was taken up, and debated at length. The main discussion was on the proposition to tax bank circulation, and it was finally decided that it should be taxed one per cent. for two years, and two per cent. thereafter. The bill was then passed, 32 yeas to 4 nays -- Messrs. CARLILE, of Virginia; POWELL, of Kentucky; RICHARDSON, of Illinois, and WALL, of New-Jersey.

abstract: His Reply to French Offer of Mediation
snippet: His Reply to French Offer of Mediation
lead_paragraph: The steamship Etna arrived at this port yesterday forenoon, with advices from Europe four days later. She left Liverpool on the 28th, and Queenstown on the 29th ult. The most striking news by this arrival relates to an insurrection in Poland, which assumed quite formidable proportions in some quarters, but which, at last advices, had apparently been quelled by the military. It broke out in the provinces around Warsaw, in consequence, as was supposed, of the conscription which had recently taken place. Troops were attacked at various points, and numbers of them were killed, some of them being strangled in their beds. Railroads were also torn up, and telegraphic communication interrupted, but all this had been again regulated. The rumors in regard to the new mediation scheme of the French Emperor continued to circulate. The Nord, of the 27th, says that M. DROUYNDE LHUYS had addressed a note to the French Ministers at St. Petersburgh, London, Vienna and Berlin, instructing them to sound those courts upon the fitness, not of a mediation, but of simple counsels which might be given to the belligerent parties at Washington and Richmond, advising them to name Commissioners charged to examine, with or without an armistice, upon what basis an arrangement might be made to put an end to the war. It was generally thought by the English journals that the new scheme would prove unacceptable to the United States Government. The Bank of England had advanced its minimum rate of discount from four to five per cent., which movement caused a depression in the Liverpool cotton and other markets. Consols were quoted at 92 1/8@92 1/4 for money.

lead_paragraph: The steamship Champion arrived at this port last night, from Aspinwall on the 4th inst., whence she sailed under convoy of the gunboat Connecticut. She brings nearly $360,000 in treasure. No later news had reached the Isthmus from Central or South America, though a report had been brought from Callao that there was much excitement on the coast of Peru regarding the visit of a large Spanish fleet to the contiguous waters. It was thought by many at Callao and Lima, that Peru was to be subjugated -- Spain never having recognized her independence. Affairs in the United States of Colombia remain quiet. A British brig, arrived at Aspinwall, reports that on the 27th ult., in the afternoon, she saw a ship on fire twenty miles south of San Domingo, and it was conjectured that she was a victim of one of the Southern pirates. The United States brig Bainbridge, without guns, and partly dismantled, still lies at Aspinwall -- her crew of 80 or 90 were idle.

abstract: Keokuk, Gunboat, Fatal Boiler Explosion on
snippet: Keokuk, Gunboat, Fatal Boiler Explosion on
lead_paragraph: About 1 1/2 o'clock yesterday morning, a serious explosion occurred on board the Government iron-clad gunboat Keokuk, lying in the dock at the foot of Eleventh-street, East River. The steam-pipe of the boat exploded, instantly scalding to death four of the men on board of her, and seriously injuring one other person. The names of the deceased are HENRY C. BILLS, engineer, of No. 277 Henry-street; DANIEL JORDAN, GEORGE A. SMITH and DANIEL COLLINS, firemen. ABRAHAM BOUGHTON, also a fireman, was very severely scalded. He was immediately taken to the New-York Hospital by the Police of the Eleventh Precinct, where he now lies in a critical state, but it is believed that with proper care he may recover.

abstract: We have advices from New-Orleans to the 6th of February by the arrival at this port last evening of the steamship Empire City. The news is important as showing that the work of preparation is now complete, and that we may expect soon to hear a good account of Gen. BANK'S army.
lead_paragraph: We have advices from New-Orleans to the 6th of February by the arrival at this port last evening of the steamship Empire City. The news is important as showing that the work of preparation is now complete, and that we may expect soon to hear a good account of Gen. BANKS' army. The troops, after a month's drilling, were in a condition to take the field, and it was believed that the first movement would be to clean out the Lafourche district entirely of the rebels, who are known to have returned since the withdrawal of Gen. WEITZELL's forces from the Bayou Teche to Thibodeauville. A fishing smack had been seized on Lake Pontchartrain, having on board a large quantity of medicines for the rebels, and a number of letters from persons in New-Orleans to persons prominent in the rebel Government. Gen. BANKS was taking measures to have the writers arrested. The three clergymen -- Drs. LECOCK, FULTON and GOODRICH -- sent North by Gen. BUTLER, had returned to New-Orleans, but refusing to take the oath of allegiance, had not been allowed to land. It was reported from above that the water in the cut-off of Vicksburgh had been increased in depth, so as to allow the passage of a small steamer; but this report probably grows out of the fact of the ram Queen of the West being below the batteries.

abstract: Christian Commission Meeting, the
snippet: Christian Commission Meeting, the
lead_paragraph: The great meeting at the Academy of Music on last Sunday night had some significant features worthy of remark. In numbers, enthusiasm, and blended patriotic and Christian sentiment, it stands alone among the great gatherings of the war. There have been great war meetings and great political meetings; but the element which takes hold of the strongest and holiest principles of our nature found expression in the utterances and emotions of Sunday evening. Patriotism, philanthropy and religion met together.

It appeared from the evidence that BLISS is only 15 years of age, that he has three brothers in the army, and was himself, until lately, in the naval service where he maintained a good character.
lead_paragraph: ALTERING TREASURY NOTES. -- EDWARD DALTON BLISS, the young man who was arrested on Thursday for attempting to pass a $50 United States Treasury note at Niblo's saloon, had a preliminary examination before United States Commissioner OSBORN yesterday. It appeared from the evidence that BLISS is only 15 years of age, that he has three brothers in the army, and was himself, until lately, in the naval service where he maintained a good character. No other altered money was found on his person, and there is little doubt that in attempting to pass the note he was made a tool of by older and more guilty parties. Commissioner OSBORN reserved his decision in the case until Monday, and will, meantime, make inquiries with regard to young BLISS, and release or commit him as the facts may warrant.

abstract: -- The New-Orleans Delta tells this story: "Some time ago a planter up the coast sold his sugar and cotton to a gentleman of this city, amounting in value to $4,600. The gentleman paid him in cash, and left the purchased produce on his plantation, to be called for at some future time. The guerrillas getting wind of the transaction, visited the plantation and destroyed the property. A day or two since the gentleman who had purchased and paid for the articles happened to be passing the plantation on a steamer. The boat stopped for a few moments to wood, and while detained there, the planter came aboard, and refunded the money. This was an honorable action, and worthy the loyal Creole population of Louisiana. He was not legally bound to return the money, as the property had been left on the plantation at the risk of the purchaser; but in the eyes of the honorable gentleman such a course would not have been honest, and his conscience would never have been quiet while he had the money in his pocket for the cotton and sugar destroyed by the guerrillas.

abstract: Shall We Go to Pieces
snippet: Shall We Go to Pieces
lead_paragraph: Is this really to be the cry? Shall we throw thought and care to the dogs, while things generally topple down upon our heads? Is it an earthquake that is rumbling? or is the foundation on which the fabric of Government rests turning into quicksand? No matter; some folks have got an idea that their rights are in danger unless the Government is thoroughly shaken into a sense of its weakness, or unless it feels the very ground on which it has hitherto firmly stood sinking from beneath its feet, and calls in despair for help upon the unshakable dominions and powers established at Albany and Trenton, and humbly begs to be propped up again on any conditions. Let the earth shake, then, so only this result be produced. Let us go to pieces, that we may be great and free -- each piece for itself. Hand in hand, let the sisterhood of States, in a bacchanalian frenzy, dance one final round together, till heads swim, and fingers unclasp, and the whole set tumble to the ground. It must be confessed that this is a somewhat mixed figure of speech, but it would not suit the occasion were it coherent.

abstract: BOLD LARCENY. -- A very bold robbery was committed yesterday, about 1 o'clock, at the rooms of Mr. MARCUS L. WARD, NO. 2 Custom-house Building, in Newark. An assistant, who had been engaged in the payment of money sent on by New-Jersey soldiers, having left the room for a few minutes, locking the door after him, upon returning found the door wide open, and $501 missing from a tin box he had left open in the room. Fifty dollars of the money belonged to the clerk, and the balance to the soldiers. No clue to the robber hab been obtained.

abstract: The King's Policy and the Chambers
snippet: The King's Policy and the Chambers
lead_paragraph: The King of Prussia and the Prussian Chambers are again face to face, and everything indicates that the strife of the last session will be renewed with ten-fold bitterness in this. A King who has once wielded the sceptre of despotism, can seldom brook to descend to the condition of a Constitutional Monarch. Rather than do so, the second of the STUARTS died on the scaffold, and the last of them forfeited the triple crown of the Isles, and the present representative of the House of Brandenburgh seems to be as obstinate and as determined to brave the worst, as either of those ill-fated personages. Both the letter and the spirit of the Prussian law are against him, and yet he persists in his infatuated course. During the recess, his principal employment was invoking laudatory addresses from the Reactionary and Absolutist party, or laboring to stifle the national purpose, and to silence all expression of popular sentiment. One instance of the regal contempt for every show of constitutionalism is now much talked of in Prussia. It is customary with the municipality of Berlin to present an Address of Congratulation to the King, on New-Year's day. But as the old year waned, WILLIAM became uneasy. Aware of the liberal proclivities of that body, and not wanting to hear unpleasant truths from them, he ordered Count EULENBURG, his Minister of the Interior, to intimate to the President of the Corporation that if a draft of the contemplated address was not forwarded for his perusal, the address would not be received. Instead of the required draft, however, the Count got the address itself, coupled with the request that he would transmit it to his master. Now, reluctant as the Minister felt to discharge this mission, he nevertheless did not like to assume the responsibility of declining it, and so the obnoxious address was presented to his serene Majesty, who, having failed to awe the Berliners into courtliness, found himself obliged to entertain and answer the unwelcome document. But, though the general tenor of the address was laudatory, the temper of the King was sorely tried by the admonitions of these audacious municipals. They warned him to "eschew the path which ends in revolution, and to tread in that which leads to reconciliation and peace." This was, in effect, a formal censure of the past conduct of the King. WILLIAM, however, did not throw the address into the fire after reading it, but in his reply he expressed "his determination to persist in carrying out those measures which he deemed essential to the welfare of the State, in despite of the fact that he was misunderstood by the Nation." This explicit declaration on his part, leaves no room for doubt as to his future policy, no ground for hoping that he will walk in the way of "reconciliation and peace." He has evidently made up his mind to enter into no compromise with the representatives of the people. He will augment his army and levy taxes to support it, in defiance of the Lower Chamber, and by virtue of his prerogative, at a time when even FRANCIS JOSEPH has been giving proof of his respect for constitutional government, by suffering the Reichsrath to cut down the ministerial estimates, and by reducing, at their suggestion, the military force of his empire.

abstract: Mr. ISAAC G. THORNE, who has just returned from Memphis, visited the Contraband's Relief Commission at their regular weekly meeting, last night, and gave the following interesting statement regarding the general condition of the fugitive blacks in the Department of West Tennessee: The number of contrabands at Cairo is about 1,500; at Columbus, Ky., 500; Memphis, 5,000, and constantly arriving, 2,000 more having come in, during the late heavy snow-storm, in an entirely destitute condition. At Bolivar 1,100 are congregated, where they are laboring for the Government. At Corinth there are 2,000 comfortably situated, and everything around them is orderly in appearance. At the latter place they are in command of Chaplain Alexander. At Jackson about 200 are collected, shifting about under nobody's especial charge. At Memphis the negroes are quartered in sheds, tents and old buildings. The women and children outnumbering the men, two to one. At Helena Mr. THORNE reports the fugitives much abused. Eight hundred were recently sent from the latter place to work on the Vicksburgh cut-off. Many die from neglect, and it is evident some system of ameliorating their sufferings should not fail to attend the policy which induces them to seek the protection of our arms. -- Cincinnati Commercial, Feb. 10.

abstract: -- The Commissioner of Internal Revenue, GEORGE S. BOUTWELL, Esq., has addressed a letter to G.F. SANGSTON, Esq., Clerk of the Superior Court, in answer to inquiry, giving the following information in relation to the Government stamps required to be used for certain legal instruments. The Commissioner states: 1. That releases of mortgages are exempt from stamp duty. When, however, the Clerk issues a certificate to the effect that a release has been placed on record, or makes a certified copy thereof, such certificate must be stamped as provided in schedule B of the excise law. 2. That bills of sale are exempt. 3. That actions by consent are subject to stamp duty as original process. 4. That the bonds for the conveyance of land comes within the meaning of the second clause of schedule B, pertaining to bonds, and is therefore subject to a stamp duty of 25 cents. 5. That the forms of bonds named and numbered as in letter B, replevin bonds, injunction bonds, bonds to dissolve attachments, being bonds required in legal proceedings, are exempt from stamp duty. 6. Trustees' bonds come within the meaning of the first clause of the schedule pertaining to bonds for the due performance of official duties, and are, therefore, subject to 50 cents stamp duty. 7. The probate of a Justice of the Peace or other magistrate does not require a stamp duty. -- Baltimore Sun, Feb. 7.

abstract: New-York; Crosby, Ann, beaten to death by her husband
snippet: New-York; Crosby, Ann, beaten to death by her husband
lead_paragraph: Coroner RANNEY was called to hold an inquest, yesterday, upon the body of Mrs. ANN CBOSBY, who died at Bellevue Hospital, from the effects of injuries received at the hands of her husband, WILLIAM CROSBY. The facts of the case, as detailed upon the inquest, are truly shocking, and almost too inhuman to relate. It appears that CROSBY and his wife had for several weeks past been residing together at No. 1 Monroe-street. He was much addicted to drink, and whenever intoxicated he would beat his wife in a most unmerciful manner, without provocation. On Monday night last, he came home beastly drunk, and soon after entering the house he caught his wife by her hair, and by this means dragged her several times across the floor of the room. Her hair was torn out by the roots, and large tufts of it were found on the floor twenty-four hours afterward by the Police. In addition to this, it seems that without any reasonable provocation, he at the same time beat his wife with a chair upon her head and body, until the chair was so badly broken that he could no longer use it upon her. After exhausting this means of warfare upon his helpless wife, he threw her down and stamped upon her head, neck and breast with his cowhide boots, until she could not see, speak or move from the floor.

lead_paragraph: -- Several of our City cotemporaries owe an apology to Mr. SEWARD. They have represented him as being guilty of an atrocious libel upon the Nation. This representation of theirs may have sprung out of an error of the types, but though that excuses their intention, it leaves the charge still standing against him. Mr. SEWARD, in his letter to Mr. DAYTON, of Feb. 5, after sundry remarks on the political organization of this country, proceeded to say that our people "are a pure Democracy." But the Tribune, the Evening Post, and the Herald represent him as styling our people "a peace Democracy." They could hardly have put more untrue words in Mr. SEWARD's mouth, as describing the present attitude of the Democratic Republic.

lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the Military Committee to whom was referred the petition of Dr. W.T.G. MORTON, asking for compensation for the use of ether in the army, made a report of the facts, without auy recommendation. A bill to increase the efficiency of the hospital department of the army was referred to the Military Committee. The bill to enlarge the canal, and the Fox and Wisconsin Rivers, was reported back from the Military Committee. The bill to prevent and punish frauds against the Government was considered, and after some amendment was passed. The bill authorizing letters of marque and reprisal was taken up, but it was postponed after a brief debate, and the Senate, after an executive session, adjourned.

abstract: Speech at Newark, N. J
snippet: Speech at Newark, N. J
lead_paragraph: Concert Hall, Newark, N.J., (the Newark Theatre,) was last night filled to overflowing, by an audience assembled to hear Hon. C.L. VALLANDIGHAM, of Ohio, on the "Political Issues of the Day." The stage boxes were filled with ladies, and on the stage itself were the officers and most prominent members of the Newark Democratic Union Club, under whose auspices the lecture was delivered. Shortly before the meeting was called to order a delegation arrived bearing a banner with the inscription, "Welcome, Champion of Constitutional Liberty," the entrance of which brought forth loud and prolonged applause. The stage was draped all round with the national flag, and two very large ones were suspended immediately over the speaker's head.

abstract: -- The new iron Monitor Sangamon, built at Chester, went into commission yesterday, and was expected to sail during the evening for Fortress Monroe. Her crew, consisting of 19 seamen, 10 ordinary seamen, 18 landsmen, 2 boys, 3 first-class firemen and 7 coal-heavers, making a total of 69, were taken from the Navy-yard to Chester in a tugboat. Capt. GUEST, the Commander of the Sangamon, the Commandant at the Navy-yard, and several other naval officers were on board the tug. On reaching Chester, the iron-clad moved out into the stream and anchored. Capt. GUEST then took charge of the Monitor, and, after the men had been called together, addressed them in a brief and patriotic speech. The wharves in front of the yard where the iron-clad was built, were crowded with citizens of Chester, who were anxious to see the Sangamon leave for her destination. -- Philadelphia Ledger, Feb. 10.

abstract: on the Emancipation Proclamation
snippet: on the Emancipation Proclamation
lead_paragraph: JOHN VAN BUREN, in his speech, on Tuesday evening, conceded that the Proclamation of Emancipation "does nothing but what any General commanding the army might do." This is more of a concession than most of his coadjutors in the Democratic ranks would make. It admits to the full that which the friends of the Proclamation claim, viz.: that a General commanding an army has the right to declare all the slaves within his reach free. Not of course that they will be so in fact until his military power can be brought to bear upon the slaves and their masters, but that when it is brought to bear the relation of Slavery is destroyed. It is wonderful that any one should really argue -- as so many have -- that this proceeding is unlawful. Slavery is a state of suppressed war -- and that statement alone is sufficient to show that a General who is making war has the right to deliver from that condition those who are forcibly kept in it by those upon whom he is making war. The deliverance of a conquered people has always been a powerful weapon with those who fought with their conquerors. And that the people are scattered over the land instead of being collected together into one province, cannot make the slightest difference as to the law of war in the matter.

abstract: Between 1 and 2 o'clock yesterday morning, an explosion occurred on board the new Government iron-clad steamer Keokuk, lying at the foot of Eleventh-street, East River, whereby four of the men employed on board of her were instantly killed, and another was so seriously scalded that it is believed he cannot recover. Coroner RANNEY held an inquest yesterday afternoon, at the Eleventh Precinct Station-house, upon the bodies of the four unfortunate men. The verdict of the jury decides that the occurrence was purely accidental.

abstract: Assumes Command of Vicksburgh Expedition
snippet: Assumes Command of Vicksburgh Expedition
lead_paragraph: -- The St. Louis Republican states that on the 28th ult., the Twenty-fourth Kentucky Regiment, stationed at Frankfort, received an order to proceed to Nashville and join the Army of the Cumberland, under Gen. ROSECRANS. Part of the regiment, comprising 200 men, refused to obey the order, and left town, carrying their arms and equipments with them. Instead, however, of going South to join the rebels, they dispersed to their homes, in some of the counties near the State Capital, where they were originally enlisted. A brigade of Free State troops was in Frankfort on the day of the demonstration, but made no effort to arrest the mutineers, because the brigade commander, Col. GILBERT, thought it prudent not to hazard a collision. Col. GRIGSBY, of the Twenty-fourth, was not in camp at the time of the occurrence, and is, of course, not responsible for the defection in his regiment. The President's Proclamation was alleged by the mutineers to be the cause of their desertion.

abstract: Longworth, Nicholas, of Cincinnati
snippet: Longworth, Nicholas, of Cincinnati
lead_paragraph: -- Nicholas Longworth, who died at Cincinnation Feb. 10, was born in Newark, N.J., on Jan. 16, 1782, and consequently was a few days over 80 years of age at the time of his decease. He acted for several years in the capacity of clerk in the store of an elder brother who then lived in South Carolina; but the climate did not agree with his health, and at the age of 21 years he emigrated to Cincinnati, then almost a frontier settlement, where he fitted himself for the bar under the instructions of Jacob Bennet, at that time universally acknowledged to be one of the ablest lawyers in the northwestern territory. Convinced that Cincinnati would ultimately become one of the chief commercial centres of the West, he invested all his scanty savings in land, and after 25 years, spent in the practice of his profession, retired, that he might give his entire time to the management of his property, which had by that time become quite extensive. Mr. Longworth's attention was turned to the cultivation of the vine at a very early period. As long ago as 1828 he laid the foundation of his extensive vineyards in the vicinity of Cincinnati, which now cover upward of 200 acres. The wine manufactured there has attained quite a wide celebrity. In the City of Cincinnati, also, Mr. Longworth had a wine-house where he received the raw juice from the vine-dre[???]er and converted it into wine. Mr. Longworth had an extensive reputation as a general horticulturist. His experiments on the sexual character of the strawberry were so successful as to give his name to one of the best seedlings.

abstract: ARREST OF AN ALLEGED SWINDLER. A man named GIOVANNI PACININI, was brought before Justice CONNOLLY, at the Tombs, yesterday, by Officer GOLDEN, of the Sixth Precinct, charged with swindling his brother Italians.
lead_paragraph: ARREST OF AN ALLEGED SWINDLER. -- A man named GIOVANNI PACININI, was brought before Justice CONNOLLY, at the Tombs, yesterday, by Officer GOLDEN, of the Sixth Precinct, charged with swindling his brother Italians. It is alleged that GIOVANNI's practice was to obtain money from his countrymen, promising, by written contract, to refund the same to them again within 24 hours in gold and silver, charging a premium of only 6 cents for sliver and 15 for gold. Several of the innocent victims entered into the plan and confided the money, but received no return; hence the arrest. It is stated that he obtained about $2,000 in all. There is quite a history or this man's practices, all of which will be developed on trail. Justice CONNOLY locked him up for examination.

abstract: A FEMALE ADVENTURER. -- Two or three days since, a young French girl, named PAULINE MILLER, residing at West Hoboken, was arrested, in male attire, while attempting to enlist at a recruiting-office in New-York, and was sent to Police Headquarters. At the latter place she narrated a plausible story, which was credited, and considerable sympathy was enlisted in her behalf. She stated that her father and brother had enlisted in the army, since which her mother had died, and being unable to pay the rent of her apartments she had been turned out of doors, and that she attempted to enlist that she might be near her father and brother. The girl was sent, in charge of two officers, to the Police Station in Jersey City. Upon entering the girl was at once recognized by her mother, who was then in search of her. PAULINE's desire for adventure, under an assumed character, had not been satisfied, and she departed in company with her mother with great reluctance.

lead_paragraph: A NEW APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLE OF RETALIATION. -- Gov. LETCHER, of Virginia, wrote, on the 2d day of January last, a long letter to President LINCOLN, which, as it was not answered at the close of last month, he has transmitted to the Legislature of Virginia, and it is now published in the Richmond newspapers. The object of it is to inform President LINCOLN that Gov. LETCHER has inaugurated the principle and practice of retaliation.

abstract: The debate upon the address in the Chamber of Deputies closed on the 29th ultimo. The President of the Council refuted the accusation that the Government was attempting to complicate foreign relations for the purpose of diverting attention from its difficulties at home. The draft of the address proposed by the majority hostile to the Government was voted by the overwhelming majority of 255 to 68. The minority was made up of partisans of the Federal party, of the followers of Herr VON VINCKE and of the Catholic members.

abstract: Confidence of Americans in the Future
snippet: Confidence of Americans in the Future
lead_paragraph: All accounts represent the feeling at Washington, both upon the part of the Government and among all the supporters of the war, to be buoyant and confident. It is regarded as almost certain that we are about to enter upon a path of splendid successes, which will settle the speedy fate of the rebellion. The prevalence of such feeling at the national Capital is an excellent sign. Certainly nowhere else is there so good a knowledge of our own resources and preparations, and of the present condition and means of the rebels. If we are to look for a correct forecast anywhere, it should certainly be at the national headquarters. A great deal of the depression which has existed in this City and elsewhere through the North, has rested upon no definite data whatever. Its foundation has been mere discontent with some particular policy of the Government, or with the treatment of some particular General, rather than any substantial facts bearing upon the vital elements of the war.

abstract: Between 1 and 2 o'clock Saturday morning, an explosion occurred on board the new Government iron-clad steamer Keokuk, lying at the foot of Eleventh-street, East River, whereby four of the men employed on board of her were instantly killed, and another was so seriously scalded that it is believed he cannot recover. Coroner RANNEY held an inquest on Saturday afternoon, at the Eleventh Precinct Station-house, upon the bodies of the four unfortunate men. The verdict of the jury decides that the occurrence was purely accidental.

abstract: MILITARY OPERATIONS. -- A letter, which we published yesterday on military prospects in the far West, suggested that a certain dashing frontier officer, now doing nothing, "have an independent command, and be turned loose. If so, you will hear from him." Likely enough we would. And if we were conducting war after the rebel fashion, it would be a good thing to "let loose" in the South a number of independent chieftains that might be named. Assuredly, they could do plenty of damage to rebel property, rebel towns, and the residents of rebeldom generally. But what would such independent work effect in crushing the military power of JEFF. DAVIS? It would effect very little, and would be very far, in the long run, from paying what it would cost.

abstract: Bonner, Mr., Photograph of His Trotting Horses
snippet: Bonner, Mr., Photograph of His Trotting Horses
lead_paragraph: A PHOTOGRAPH OF MR. BONNER's HORSES. -- We have to thank Mr. BONNER, of the New-York Ledger, for a very fine photograph, from an oil painting, of his famous horses, Lady Palmer and the Flatbush Mare, that trotted last Summer two miles in double harness in five minutes, one second and a quarter, -- the fastest time ever made by any team. The horses are represented as moving at speed, and Lady Palmer -- a beautiful, thoroughbred animal -- being placed on the offside, gives the picture a very attractive appearance. To use a horseman's phrase, she looks as if she could trot all day. Mr. BONNER, it is well known, keeps these splendid horses for his own use, and never, under any circumstances, allows them to be used for racing purposes. He has succeeded in establishing the fact that a private gentleman can own the best horses, without being induced to bet on them. This undertaking was a new thing; but the accomplishment of new things is characteristic of the editor of the Ledger, as the whole history of that paper demonstrates.

abstract: One branch of Congress has rejected a bill authorizing the enlistment of negro soldiers. Mr. SUMNER declares his intention to persist in forcing the passage of such a law, by offering it as an amendment to some other bill. Meantime the President, by laws already enacted, has full authority over the subject; and we can see no good object to be attained by forcing it into the discussions of Congress and adding it to the causes of dissension already existing in the country at large. One would suppose that, in such a time as this, when the salvation of the country may depend on the harmonious and energetic cooperation of all parties and all classes of our people, even the most ultra and confirmed hobby-riders of the day could be induced to forego their experiments on the passions and patience of the people, especially when no good can possibly result from their prosecution of them.

abstract: The regular performances at the German Opera this week have been interrupted by the occurrence of the Arion Ball on Wednesday evening, and HERR LOTTI's benefit on Thursday. The last named event was, we are glad to say, eminently successful. Mr. LOTTI has improved rapidly during the past three months, and is now an acceptable tenor, equal in resources to more vaunted artists, and thoroughly reliable. The patronage bestowed on Mr. ANSCHUTZ has been sufficient to render any new revivals unnecessary, especially as the Philadelphians insist on having a new season of German Opera immediately, and to this end have raised a handsome subscription for ten nights. Mr. ANSCHUTZ will remain with us only a fortnight longer, opening in Philadelphia on Monday, the 2d of March. To-night will be given for the first time MEHUL's Opera, "Moses in Egypt."

abstract: The schooner E.A. De Hart, of Georgetown, Maine, CUMMINGS, from Jacmel, Jan. 29, reports as follows: -- Jan. 30, off Cape Tiburon, was chased by the rebel privateer schooner Retribution, which fired several shot and shell at us during the chase, but fortunately doing us no damage. The weather at the time was calm, but a breeze coining up we soon ran away from her, but had it continued calm, she would no doubt have taken us with her boat; on the same day saw her board another small schooner of about eighty or one hundred tons burthen, was an Eastern built vessel, top painted black and green bottom. On the morning of the same day, previous to seeing the privateer, saw a large steamer which we took to be a Federal cruiser, come from almost the same direction, in which we made the privateer out.

abstract: We have advices from Europe to the 1st inst., one week later, by the arrival at this port, yesterday, of the steamship Asia, from Liverpool. The news is important. The new scheme of the French Emperor, for bringing the North and the South together in conference on neutral ground, had been promulgated, and the general impression was that it would prove unacceptable both to the North and South. The Paris correspondent of the London Times conjectures that the proposal is meant as merely preliminary to a more important step on the part of the Emperor. A great emancipation meeting had been held at Exeter Hall, London, which overflowed into another hall, and finally into an open air meeting. Resolutions were adopted approving President LINCOLN's Emancipation Proclamation, and in their general spirit entirely in favor of the North. There was a small and ineffectual element of opposition, at the head of which was an individual believed by our correspondent to be the Rebel Commissioner MASON, though a different name appeared in the papers next morning. The accounts regarding the insurrection in Poland are contradictory. The telegrams received in Liverpool on the day the Asia sailed state that the insurgents had been overcome at all points, and that order had been reestablished, but the very latest news received at Queenstown conveys an opposite impression. The better classes of the Poles were said to be joining the insurgents. The Liverpool Cotton market had been very dull under the influence of the advance of the rate of discount by the Bank of England, but had rallied slightly at last accounts. Breadstuffs and Provisions were inactive. Consols were quoted at 92 1/2.

abstract: A letter from Warsaw of the 22d inst. states that the Cossacks are everywhere hunting the young men who are escaping from Warsaw to join the insurgents. The Government in the meantime are taking all imaginable precautions against the spread of the insurrection. The Abbe GOHAN preached a sermon in the Cathedral on the previous Sunday, in which he blamed the National movement. A woman exclaimed in a loud voice, "Oh Lord God! I call you to witness that the enemy attacks us without cause. Here are apostates who explain your laws falsely by attacking our love of country and by endeavoring to destroy the courage of the nation. Lord have pity on our sufferings!" The preacher, amazed at this interruption, grew quite pale, and was unable for some time to continue his discourse. He then thanked the congregation for not having joined in that revolt against the word of God. Similar scenes occurred in other churches, which fully prove the enthusiasm, or rather fanaticism, which prevails among the population of Poland. The conscripts were crowded into the citadel, and it is asserted that they had no food for twenty-four hours; that strong liquor was then distributed among them, which rendered some of them nearly frantic, and which the official journal represented to the public as a proof of the happiness thus experienced at being enrolled in the Russian army. The crowds of young men who assembled round the Serok have dispersed in consequence of not being able to provide themselves with arms. Another gathering took place in the forest of Kampinosy. Though surrounded by Russian troops, they succeeded in crossing the Vistula, but great anxiety is felt for their future safety. The writer of the letter adds that the parties who had constantly urged the population to desperate measures have lost their confidence, and that they are to be replaced by a Committee of men of more moderate principles, who will act according to more matured plans. It is further said that the existing Committee, wishing to maintain its influence, had determined on adopting the desperate resolution of calling the people to arms throughout the entire kingdom. The letter concludes in these words: "We are passing through an alarming crisis. God grant that it may not lead us to a catastrophe."

abstract: In the Senate, on Saturday, the Military Committee to whom was referred the petition of Dr. W.T.G. MORTON, asking for compensation for the use of ether in the army, made a report of the facts, without any recommendation. A bill to increase the efficiency of the hospital department of the army was referred to the Military Committee. The bill to enlarge the canal, and the Fox and Wisconsin Rivers, was reported back from the Military Committee. The bill to prevent and punish frauds against the Government was considered, and after some amendment was passed. The bill authorizing letters of marque and reprisal was taken up, but it was postponed after a brief debate, and the Senate, after an executive session, adjourned.

abstract: Yesterday afternoon, Detective KEEFE, of the Central Police Office, arrested HENRY D. GILBERT and H.J. MUMFORD, both of whom are members of the Seymour Light Infantry, upon the charge of having cooperated with a man named L.J. COOPER, formerly a Lieutenant in the same regiment, in swindling recruits out of the sum of $3,000 in the aggregate. COOPER, it appears, has not yet been arrested. But a few weeks since, he, with the accomplices named above, went to Erie County, in the Western part of this State, to raise men for the Seymour Light Infantry. They there collected about thirty-five men, who joined the regiment, and for which the pretended officers received the sum of $3,000, the recruits being induced to sign false receipts for their bounty money. abstract: Foh Kein; Trial Trip of the
snippet: Foh Kein; Trial Trip of the
lead_paragraph: A new steamer, of this name, built for Mr. PAUL S. FORBES, of this City, for the China trade, went on her Engineer's trial trip on Wednesday last. The ship was built by HENRY STEERS, on one of those exquisite models which have made his family famous; and the engine was reconstructed from one of the large Lake Erie engines by Messrs. DICKERSON & SICKELS, of this City, at the Morgan Iron Works. The ship is 285 feet long, 38 feet wide, and 22 feet deep; and with a load of 700 tons when she left, drew between twelve and thirteen feet of water. The engine is an 81-inch, 12 feet stroke beam engine, of the ordinary construction, except so far as the engineers have altered it in reconstruction; which alterations consisted in substituting a new cylinder with a steam-jacket for the old one without it, in replacing the fixed Stevens cut-off and ordinary exhaust valve gear, with the Sickel's cut-off and exhaust gear as recently improved by Mr. DICKERSON, and in giving a new sort of waterwheel, instead of the old-fashioned one. The decalarator of Mr. LIGHTHALL was also added to the condensing apparatus of the ship, whereof fresh water is given to the boilers; and the boilers are known as Smith's boilers, but are very small for the size of the engine -- made so upon the expectation that the economy of fuel which would result from the improvements on the engine, would compensate for the loss of boiler power and the want of coal consumption.
