abstract: The rapid march of improvement, which forms so distinguishing a characteristic of the Manhattanese, is daily removing or transforming the old landmarks that have been to this generation silent reminders of olden days and a Knickerbocker ancestry.
lead_paragraph: The rapid march of improvement, which forms so distinguishing a characteristic of the Manhattanese, is daily removing or transforming the old landmarks that have been to this generation silent reminders of olden days and a Knickerbocker ancestry. The resting places wherein were interred (as was thought for all time) the remains of those of our progenitors who have passed from earth, are no longer yielded up to the silent dead; the increase of business and population rendering the sites of their "narrow houses" more valuable to the mercantile and manufacturing community than when the practice of intramural interments was universal in Gotham. The kindly wish, "Requiescat in pace," as applied to them, seems a mockery, so far as their corporeal natures are concerned; and Mammon, with a covetous eye, lays his plans for invading and turning to business purposes those hallowed spots heretofore sanctified to the memory of our deceased friends.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, after the presentation of petitions, a statement of the facts regarding the case of ZARVONA, the "French Lady," was reported from the Military Committee. The bill regulating the appointment of Midshipmen was debated until the expiration of the morning hour, when Senator WILSON's bill for enrolling and calling out the Militia was considered. Mr. WILSON explained that the bill professed to enroll the whole people of the country, and not merely the militia. An amendment proposing to exempt members of Congress from its provisions was rejected. An amendment was adopted limiting exemptions to the Governors and Judiciary of the States, but to those were subsequently added the only sons of widows dependent upon them for support. The amendment allowing persons drafted to be exempted by paying $250, etc., was debated, but temporarily withdrawn. The debate on the bill was continued during an evening session.

abstract: On Saturday last two young man of refined demeanor, though poorly clad, called at the headquarters of Provost-Marshal DRAPER, and presented letters of introduction and explanation from the ProvostMarshal at Pensacola. They reported themselves as escaped Southern conscripts, and gave their names as J. MUNY and THOMAS PRATT.
lead_paragraph: On Saturday last two young man of refined demeanor, though poorly clad, called at the headquarters of Provost-Marshal DRAPER, and presented letters of introduction and explanation from the Provost-Marshal at Pensacola. They reported themselves as escaped Southern conscripts, and gave their names as J. MUNY and THOMAS PRATT. They stated that they formerly lived near Dunkirk in this State, and went South a short time before the rebellion. About two months ago they took up their abode at Montgomery, Ala., and soon after were enrolled in the Southern militia. They were too discreet to exhibit any symptoms of dissatisfaction, but entered the service apparently with the purpose of doing what they could to advance the interests of the cause. Having thus warded off all suspicion, their next step was to procure leaves of absence for twelve hours, which they succeeded in obtaining. The brief time which they had to make preparations for escape was not idly squandered. They immediately went to a friend in the neighborhood who supplied them with two horses and equipments. One of the horses they subsequently bartered for a buggy and harness, which with the remaining horse constituted their means of traveling. They struck off in the direction of Pensacola, and being familiar with the road, were able to make rapid progress. After driving sixty miles without rest, they fortunately discovered a Union family in Florida, who received them kindly, and furnished food for themselves and horse. The acceptance of this hospitality, however, came very near losing them the liberty which they were so earnest to obtain, for no sooner had the time for their return to camp expired and it had become known they had left town, than a squad of cavalry was instantly dispatched in pursuit. The cavalry came up to the house of the Union family just as the young men were about to continue their journey. The Sergeant in command inquired of the owner concerning the whereabouts of the refugees, and was told that they had but a minute previous gone to the barn to harness their horses. While this conversation was going on, the young men were secreted in an adjoining apartment, and as soon as the pursuing party had adjourned to the barn to make a search, they sprang upon horses furnished them by their protector, and sped toward our lines. The cavalry followed in hot haste, but upon coming to a river, the water was too deep for them to ford, and the young men, having seized the only available boats, were half way across the stream. The cavalry fired several shots, but none of them took effect. They were, of course, compelled to retrace their steps without making the anticipated addition to their number. Arriving at Pensacola, having traveled a distance of 112 miles, the refugees made themselves known to the Provost-Marshal at that post, and were kindly furnished by him with the papers above mentioned and a passage to this City. They left town yesterday morning for Dunkirk, where their parents reside.

abstract: the Uprising in
snippet: the Uprising in
lead_paragraph: The facts of the insurrectionary movement in Poland, as far as they can be extracted from the confused accounts which have reached western Europe, hardly support the conclusion that it was preconcerted. The stories which have been circulated of the attempt of the Poles, under the direction of the National Committee at Warsaw, to reenact St. Bartholomew's Day, by a general and sudden massacre of the Russian troops, have such strong marks of having been invented by their enemies for the purpose of depriving them of the sympathy of foreign nations, that we have no hesitation in discrediting them; and we are led to do so all the more readily, from the fact that this charge of treachery and assassination is coupled with the allegation that one of the objects of the revolution thus foully inaugurated, was an equal division of the lands, if not of the entire property of the nation amongst the inhabitants. In spreading abroad this version of the acts and motives of the alleged conspirators, the agents of the Russian Government no doubt confidently expected to deprive the Poles of their traditional hold on English and French sympathy by rousing against them that horror of socialism by which the middle classes all over Europe are still haunted, and which constitutes, at the present day, a still stronger support for arbitrary government, and a still stronger obstacle to the spread of free institutions, than either standing armies or the enslavement of the Press.

abstract: The iron-clad Ericsson battery Catskill, having been finished by the contractors, will proceed to the Brooklyn Navy-yard to-day or to-morrow to be formally delivered to the representatives of the Government. Her turrets, armament, and all other appendages are on board completed, so that she will be able to leave here to reinforce the iron-clads in the South Atlantic before this week expires. The Catskill is an exact copy of the Passaic and Montauk, except that her sections have been materially stengthened within the past few weeks. Her battery consists of one 11 and one 15-inch gun, both mounted on the new Ericsson carriage, in the turret. The compass is arranged in the manner recently adopted on vessels of her class. The vessel steamed from Greenpoint to the Delamater Iron Works last week to receive her muzzle-box, which is now finished. Annexed is a list of her officers as far as reported.

abstract: The Board of Aldermen met at the usual hour, yesterday, and referred to the Committee on Ferries several communications from the Comptroller, giving information about certain ferries and slips, and also referred an ordinance, submitted by the City Inspector, to regulate the removal of human remains from old burial grounds.
lead_paragraph: The Board of Aldermen met at the usual hour, yesterday, and referred to the Committee on Ferries several communications from the Comptroller, giving information about certain ferries and slips, and also referred an ordinance, submitted by the City Inspector, to regulate the removal of human remains from old burial grounds. The Street Commissioner reported that earth had been removed from Hamilton-square by permission from the late Comptroller, which had been revoked. The $500,000 Family Aid Ordinance, No. 5, was taken up, and passed. The resolution to appropriate $5,000 to celebrate WASHINGTON's Birthday was lost for want of a two-thirds vote: then reconsidered and laid over. The Mayor's veto (already overruled by the Councilmen) on a batch of resolutions -- passed during the closing week of last year's session of the Common Council -- correcting errors in names of persons already appointed, and appointing some additional Commissioners of Deeds, was called up by Mr. HARDY who wished to divide the subject, being opposed to the additional appointments. President WALSH ruled that no division was admissible. Mr. BOOLE said the veto was void, because it embodied several resolutions, the Charter requiring a separate communication on each legislative act vetoed. Mr. HALL added that it was void, because the Charter required the return of a paper vetoed to the Board in which it originated, and both Boards of 1862 were out of existence. The subject was laid over for action to-day, the Board adjourning till 1 o'clock this afternoon.

abstract: The chirruping and twittering of a thousand canaries; the mellifluous strains of a half a hundred Of DODWORTH'S best musicians, led by the immortal HARVEY B.; the Academy of Music, resplendent with illumination and gorgeous with manifold decorations,...
lead_paragraph: The chirruping and twittering of a thousand canaries; the mellifluous strains of a half a hundred of DODWORTH's best musicians, led by the immortal HARVEY B.; the Academy of Music, resplendent with illumination and gorgeous with manifold decorations, and the 5,000 attentive representatives of the youth, beauty, wealth and fashion of the metropolis, made the promenade concert of the Seventy-first Regiment, on Saturday evening, a memorable success. The ornaments or the edifice were much the same as those which graced the Light Guard Ball, for, be it rememdered, the "Tigers" are a company of the Seventy-first, and the perpetuation of their tasteful arrangements bore a double significance. They, too, have marched, encamped, bivouacked and served the country under the leadership of the gallant VOSBURGH, and it was fitting that the emblems of their festivities should be intertwined with the funereal drapery of their late commander.

abstract: We suppose  the statement made by the commanders of our blockading vessels oft Charleston, and published this morning, will settle finally and decisively the falsity of the assertions of BEAUREGARD and INGRAHAM, that the entire...
lead_paragraph: -- We suppose the statement made by the commanders of our blockading vessels oft Charleston, and published this morning, will settle finally and decisively the falsity of the assertions of BEAUREGARD and INGRAHAM, that the entire blockading fleet was "sunk, dispersed, and drove off and out of sight," on the 31st ult., and that the blockade of Charleston was consequently raised. There were nine blockading steamers off Charleston on the morning in question, and the commanders of all of these -- excepting three who were absent -- show, by a recital of the positions and doings of their vessels, that neither in the morning nor during the day of the engagement, did they ever leave the blockading line usually occupied by them. The statement is so circumstantial and specific in all its details, that there is no possibility of mistake. In regard to all the rebel official and unofficial reports, these officers pronounce them "false in every particular." The statement that any foreign Consuls in a rebel steamer, or the British man-of-war Petrel, came anywhere near the usual anchorage of any of the blockaders, after the retreat of the rebel rams, is pronounced to be "deliberately and knowingly false."

abstract: Loyalty; Letter of a Kentuckian
snippet: Loyalty; Letter of a Kentuckian
lead_paragraph: The remarkable workings of Northern traitors and of their colleagues in the Middle States must be looked upon by all true men with mingled emotions of loathing and contempt. This new batch of traitors is more wicked than the mass of rebels in the South. In the case of the former, thousands were overtaken by the avalanche let loose upon them by a slave aristocracy, and overwhelmed by it; in that of the latter the treason stalks before the eyes of men with the utmost possible deliberation, and in the perfection of prestidigitation. As compared with each other, the first are in the category of manslaughter, the latter are murderers with malice prepense. One is stupendous folly, the other stupendous meanness. I earnestly wish that some of your Northern traitors could have a few weeks intercourse with this rebellion, to which they are now anxious to extend their hospitalities. These traitors are attempting to delude the people into the notion that they are preparing a bed of roses for the loyal States, but if it were possible that their wild dream of partisan politics could take form and substance, this bed of roses would be such a bed as that on which the antetypes of JEFF. DAVIS and his crew of piratical de nons stretched MONTEZUMA in the City of Mexico.

abstract: The important experiments on the steamer Foh Kien., during her ocean trial trip last week, reported in another column, add to the best practice of the world for half a century their direct and special evidence in favor of a high rate of expansion in steam...
lead_paragraph: -- The important experiments on the steamer Foh Kien, during her ocean trial trip last week, reported in another column, add to the best practice of the world for half a century their direct and special evidence in favor of a high rate of expansion in steam engines, and against the blunders of the Navy Department. After the value of this principle had been demonstrated by WATT and practiced in every one of the ten thousands of steam-engines since his time, where economical results were of moment -- after high expansion had attained to such importance that nearly every improvement and patent in steam engineering was an attempt to better the means of obtaining or exaggerating it -- after its value to the public had become sufficiently important to warrant the most costly and prolonged patent suits about cut-offs -- (the means of obtaining expansion) -- while CORLISS, SICKLES and their imitators, were achieving constantly improved results by this means in this country, and RANDOLPH & ELDER, ROWAN and others in England, not content with what expansion they could get in one cylinder, expanded the same steam through two, in ocean vessels, with high economy, -- at this very time Mr. ISHERWOOD invented the uselessness of such expansion, and pronounced the whole engineering world in error. So captivated were the authorities by his presumption that they not only raised him to be Chief of the Bureau, but actually allowed him to repudiate and neutralize the professional success and talent of the whole country, and to specify, under its protest, to the uttermost detail, the machinery for a whole navy -- machinery which in the gunboats has proved a comparative blunder in every particular, which in the sloops has miserably failed before it ever went to sea, and which can only be remedied by being broken up into scrap iron and remodeled according to those laws of nature which it was vainly called upon to violate. The abandonment of even comparatively moderate expansion, is but one of the mistakes of Mr. ISHERWOOD.

abstract: GERMAN OPERA. The approach of Lent has probably induced Mr. ANSOHUTZ to produce MEHUL'S opera of "Joseph in Egypt" a serious but beautiful work, in three acts. As an oratorio, it is already well known here, but in its complete form, it was, we fancy, given last night for the first time.
lead_paragraph: GERMAN OPERA. -- The approach of Lent has probably induced Mr. ANSCHUTZ to produce MEHUL'S opera of "Joseph in Egypt" -- a serious but beautiful work, in three acts. As an oratorio, it is already well known here, but in its complete form, it was, we fancy, given last night for the first time. The music is written in a style of simple grandeur, which can hardly be excelled, and although a little old-fashioned, is full of melody and broad, open choral effects. Its production last night was hailed with frequent applause by a very full and attentive audience. The principal parts were sustained by Mad. ROTTER, Herr LOTTI, Herr QUINT, Herr WEINLICH and Herr GRAFF, most of whom will be heard to greater advantage on Wednesday next, when the opera will be repeated.

lead_paragraph: A SECOND DOSE OF LILLIPUTIANIA. -- Gen. T. Thumb and wife are the lions of our National Capital. They have been graciously received by the President and his counselors in the great East Room, have danced at the semi-annual hop, at Willard's, with Foreign Ministers and their better halves, have eaten the bread of the titled and drank the wine of the prosperous, and may now be fairly considered as on their way to the Court of Her Gracious and Brittanic Majesty. In their absence Mr. BARNUM advertises another tit-bit of creation, in the person of Miss MINNIE WARREN, who is littler, prettier, and altogether a greater curiosity than her sister. She, with Commodore NUTT, make the smallest couple in the world, of corresponding years. We trust there is no truth in the absurd rumor of their matrimonial engagement; there is time enough for that sort of thing years hence. The exhibition of these little ones begins to-day, and we expect for another month to have Broadway blockaded in front of the Museum, to hear of extravagancies on the part of frantic millionaires, and eventually a Barnumistic coup d'etat, which will eclipse in magnificence and audacity anything which the unparalleled showman ever before suggested.

abstract: Reply to Ohio Legislature Vote of Thanks
snippet: Reply to Ohio Legislature Vote of Thanks
lead_paragraph: The letter of Gen. ROSECRANS to the Ohio Legislature, in response to its vote of thanks, has a ring there's no mistaking. It comes like one of the missives of the old barons, stamped with the hilt of the sword. It has an emphasis of thought and of word that needs no Corinth or Murfreesboro to confirm that there's a staunch hand behind it. Of personal profession there is not a syllable; and yet the veriest stranger would say on the instant: "Here is a man whose heart is in the cause." The whole deliverance is in refreshing contrast with the halting, mincing, words which have become the established style of a certain set of Major-Generals, in all their communications with the public ROSECRANS has no political aspirations, and you see at once that he cares not the snap of his finger for party sensibilities. He has but one feeling, and that is intensest hatred of the rebellion, and of all who would yield to it. He knows but one duty, and that is the duty of fighting.

abstract: Vallandigham's Speech
snippet: Vallandigham's Speech
lead_paragraph: Some of our neighbors are making themselves unhappy over the prospective movements of the Democratic party. They fear the country is to be "sold out." They take alarm at the language held by VALLANDIGHAM and the resolutions offered in the New-Jersey and Illinois Legislatures. We do not share their apprehensions. The leaders of the Democratic party will go just as far as they can, toward peace and disunion, with even the tacit approval and support of the American people; but that will not be very far. And when they come to the limit of popular patience they will stop. They are just as powerless as any other faction, except as they are backed up by public sentiment. And if they suppose that the sentiment of the people of this country is in favor of peace at the price of Disunion, they will very speedily be aroused from their delusion.

abstract: -Mr. JOSEPH ENEAS, of this City, sends to us to say that a report in our law columns of the prize case of the schooner Levi Rowe, is calculated to injure him by giving the impression that he was the owner of the vessel which, was captured in suspicious proximity to the Southern coast. We do not see how such a construction could be put upon the report of the case. It is true that it stated that the vessel had on board of her a certificate of her registry to Mr. ENEAS as owner, but it stated also that that registry was dated in September, 1861, and in the same sentence said that she had on board a charter from other persons as owners, dated in November, 1862, just before she was captured. But to avoid all possibility of harm, we will add that Mr. ENEAS has shown to us the proof of his having sold the vessel, and having had no interest in her whatever on the voyage in question.

lead_paragraph: The Eighth Ward Pioneer Clay Club celebrated, for the twenty-fourth time, last evening, at the Apollo Rooms, the anniversary of the ratification of the Treaty of Ghent. A brilliant assemblage was present, among which DE PEYSTER OGDEN, Esq., Prof. MAPES, and others of note, were prominent. The room was tastefully decorated, and everything that could be done for the entertainment of the guests was done. Seldom has the Club given a more delightful entertainment. Letters of regret for non-attendance were received from President Lincoln, Millard Fillmore, Geo. Opdyke, W.A. Darling, Francis Granger, R.B. Van Valkenberg, Hon. Mr. Maynard, Daniel Ullman, and others. Among the ornaments of the room were two portraits of HENRY CLAY, painted by Mrs. FOLSOM, of the Eighth Ward. During the evening, the Club entertained its distinguished guests with a social glass, and complimentary toasts were given and responded to by James M. Murray, S.J. Wilken, Jos. M. Price, De Peyster Ogden, Prof. Mapes, Supervisor Sheridan Shook, Capt. B. Price, and others. The following are the officers of the Club:

abstract: Southwest Territory Clear of Rebels
snippet: Southwest Territory Clear of Rebels
lead_paragraph: All the Territories of the United States now seem to be clear of belligerent rebels. Last year at this time they were rampant in New-Mexico, and held its capital; they roamed and ravaged at their will through the unorganized regions of Arizona; and they held undisputed possession of the Indian country west of Arkansas. Now, New-Mexico is entirely free from rebels, and a loyal Legislature is at this moment sitting in Santa Fe, legislating loyally; and the acting Governor of the Territory (Mr. ARNY) has just sent in to that body one of the very best Gubernatorial messages we have ever read. From this document we learn that our gallant little army from California and Colorado, aided by the native volunteers, have not only driven the invaders permanently from New-Mexico but have taken possession of El Paso and Fort Bliss, and detachments of troops have beer sent to Camp Quitman and Fort Davis, in Texas the latter fort being 200 miles east of El Paso. All the forts down to some distance in the Northwestern part of Texas have been evacuated and abandoned by the rebels; and Fort Clark, 120 miles from San Antonio, is the nearest fort to El Paso held by the Texans.

abstract: Upon the returns of the Thirteenth Precinct Police there appeared yesterday morning an account of a case of grand larceny alleged to have been committed by a man named CHARLES PEARSON. The circumstances attending the commission of the crime...
lead_paragraph: Upon the returns of the Thirteenth Precinct Police there appeared yesterday morning an account of a case of grand larceny alleged to have been committed by a man named CHARLES PEARSON. The circumstances attending the commission of the crime are of some interest. It appears that the accused has been a resident of Bridgeport, Connecticut, for some time past, and that while there, he succeeded in winning the affections of a good-looking, well-educated and respectable young lady. The marriage of the couple was agreed upon, and for the purpose of carrying it into effect, he induced her to accompany him to New-York, where they arrived three days ago, and put up at a private boarding-house in Clinton-street. Finding that his funds were running low, but at the same time determined to carry out the plan of the marriage tour, PEARSON entered the room of a fellow-boarder, named EDWARD S. PERCIVAL, while the latter was asleep, and stole from his pockets the sum of $300, with which he succeeded in making his escape from the hotel. The money was soon missed, and the Police put upon the track of the offender, and yesterday afternoon Officer OSBORNE took him into custody, just as he and his bride were in the midst of their preparations for departure from the house. The most of the stolen money was recovered. PEARSON was taken before Justice OSBORNE held for trial.

abstract: "Historicus" (Mr. Vernon Harcourt) on the Question of Recognition
snippet: "Historicus" (Mr. Vernon Harcourt) on the Question of Recognition
lead_paragraph: We copy from the London Times another of those very able articles which have from time to time appeared in that journal under the signature of "Historicus," upon the question of recognizing the independence of the Southern Confederacy. They comprise the most thorough and exhaustive treatment of the subject, both on the ground of historical precedent and on that of international law, which has come to our notice. The writer takes the ground that neutral States cannot recognize the independence of any revolted province or portion of any country, so long as the Government maintains a serious contest for the suppression of the revolt. While there are any armies in the field -- while the war is actually continued, neutral nations may not rightfully interpose. They are bound, in justice and in law, to await the issue of the contest, and that cannot be known until the contest itself is abandoned.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, a joint resolution was reported from the Post-office Committee, authorizing the collection of foreign postage in coin. The bill reorganizing the Engineer Corps was reported back from the Military Committee. The bill to authorize contracts to be made with those...
lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, a joint resolution was reported from the Post-office Committee, authorizing the collection of foreign postage in coin. The bill reorganizing the Engineer Corps was reported back from the Military Committee. The bill to authorize contracts to be made with those States which have advanced pay to the soldiers, was reported adversely. The bill to prevent agents of the Government, members of Congress, etc., from taking any consideration for procuring place, office, or contracts, was passed. The bill authorizing letters-of-marque and reprisal was considered. An amendment in the shape of a substitute, authorizing the President in all domestic and foreign wars to issue letters-of-marque, was adopted, and the bill as amended was passed, 27 to 9. The Secretary of the Treasury was called upon for information relative to the New-York Custom-house frauds. The Senate adjourned, after holding an executive session.

abstract: Historicus on the Doctrine of Secession
snippet: Historicus on the Doctrine of Secession
lead_paragraph: SIR: I observe that a writer in the current number of the Edinburgh Review has criticised the doctrines which I ventured to lay down on the subject of "Recognition," in a letter which I addressed to you on the 4th of November last. The reviewer contends that the question is one of policy entirely, and not of right. Upon this point, though I entertain the most sincere respect for his opinion, I cannot by any means concur in his reasoning, or admit the facts on which it is founded. I am in a condition to support the propositions for which I have contended from the mouth of an authority which I am sure the Edinburgh reviewer will admit to be entitled to the very highest consideration. I referred in my former letter to the speech of Lord LANSDOWNE, in the House of Lords, on the subject of the recognition of the South American Republics -- a speech evidently most carefully considered, and replete with that wisdom, knowledge, accuracy and moderation which are characteristic of an English statesman who still represents to an age which he adorns the "mitis sapientia Lali." The following passage from this remarkable performance is so important and so pertinent that I make no apology for quoting it in extenso:

She will be completed next week, and the authorities regard her as one of the most valuable vessels of our iron-clad fleet. The statement that she had not sufficient means of egress from the engine-room is erroneous. Capt. RHIND will command her. The builder of this vessel has asked permission to accompany her South, so great is his faith in her efficiency.

abstract: Courrier des Etats Unis on French Mediation and Secretary Seward
snippet: Courrier des Etats Unis on French Mediation and Secretary Seward
lead_paragraph: -- The Courrier des Etats Unis is not at all satisfied with Secretary SEWARD's reply to the French proposal for the appointment of Commissioners to adjust the differences between our Government and the rebels. It concedes the "incontestable right" of the Government of the United States to reject the proposition of the French Emperor; but, unless the French make all possible allowance for the inspirations of patriotism in the American Secretary, it is quite confident they will find it very difficult to regard Mr. SEWARD's reply as anything but "deliberately discourteous."

abstract: Semi-Annual of
snippet: Semi-Annual of
lead_paragraph: The third "Semi-Annual" of the Students of Columbia College was celebrated yesterday morning, at WALLACK's Theatre -- which, notwithstanding the storm, was comfortably filled long before 11 o'clock, the hour at which the exercises were announced to begin. A brighter, or more cheerful, or more intelligent audience is rarely seen in New-York. Composed in good part of the friends and relatives of the students, of course it was prepared to be pleased, and not even the fifteen or twenty minutes' delay at the commencement was potent enough to destroy its good humor, -- which was further aided by some excellent music by the orchestra, under the direction of HELMSMULLER. At length the curtain rose, and disclosed a semicircle of gowned students, among whom was seated the Chaplain, Rev. Dr. JOHN MURRAY FORBES, an Alumnus of Columbia, who opened the order of exercises with a brief prayer. The presiding officer, Mr. H.A. NAZRO, of the Senior Class, a manly-looking and well-mannered youth, now stepped forward and delivered, in clear and measured tones, a neat and tasteful address, in which he said that when, two years ago, the Faculty and Trustees of the College came to the conclusion to dispense with further Semi-Annuals, on account of the expense attending them, and the state of the country, the students resolved to continue them on their own responsibility and at their own expense, -- a resolution to which the aforesaid Faculty and Trustees had made no decided objection, though they deemed it inconsistent with the course they had decided upon to lend their presence at future celebrations. With a brief and pertinent allusion to the war, the speaker drew his address (which was rewarded with a bouquet) to a graceful conclusion, and announced the first orator, Mr. ALFRED E. CLARK. Before proceeding to notice the successive efforts of the young gentleman, we will copy, for the benefit of the reader, the list of speakers and titles of their orations:

lead_paragraph: We learn from headquarters of the Army of the Potomac that two expeditions have recently been sent to break up the contraband traffic between the rebels in Maryland and Virginia, with the most satisfactory results. Near the extremity of the peninsula, between the Potomac and the Rappahannock, a large quantity of provisions and a number of horses, mules, &c., were seized, together with two large mail bags. Several vessels used in carrying supplies were destroyed, and several smugglers, some rebel soldiers and a rebel signal officer were captured.

abstract: Speech at Peace; Secesh Meeting in New-York
snippet: Speech at Peace; Secesh Meeting in New-York
lead_paragraph: Last evening about five hundred citizens assembled at the Hall, corner of Twenty-second-street and Broadway, with the anticipation of hearing an address from Hon. Mr. CARLILE, of Western Virginia, on the subject of the present state of the country. The meeting was held under the auspices of the Young Men's Democratic Association, and was presided over by Hon. LUKE F. COZZENS. The hour appointed -- 8 o'clock -- for the opening of the meeting, having arrived, the chairman of the meeting announced to the audience that he should be necessarily obliged to disappoint them in not presenting Mr. CARLILE. He concluded his remarks by saying that, in future, efforts would be made to secure the services of distinguished gentlemen to address the public once or twice a week.

abstract: Prophecies of Revolt in 1860
snippet: Prophecies of Revolt in 1860
lead_paragraph: The philosophers who have taken the political education of the North into their hands, have begun once more to inculcate upon the Northern people the necessity of maintaining a rigid silence regarding Slavery, and all questions arising out of Slavery, as an essential condition either of the restoration of the Union, or its preservation. One of them, Mr. S.J. TILDEN, has disinterred during the past week a letter which he wrote in 1860, prophesying the revolt of the South in case LINCOLN were elected; and with that amusing confidence in the national baseness by which men of his school have always been characterized, points to the fulfillment of his prophesy as a crowning proof of the folly and imbecility of his opponents. That civil war should have followed the exercise by the larger portion of the people of their constitutional right of discussing the most momentous question of modern times, and of voting for a President whose convictions accorded with their own, is to him so complete a demonstration of the stupidity and wickedness of either speaking their minds or coming to the polls, that he evidently imagines that he has only to call attention to it, in order to make the Republicans both ashamed and repentant.

abstract: CURIOSITIES OF CRIME. -- In the Court of General Sessions, yesterday, Wm. MONTAGUE, a native of London, 32 years of age, painter by trade, pleaded guilty to forgery in the fourth degree, and was remanded for sentence on Saturday. The circumstances connected with this forgery are somewhat peculiar. It appears that the District-Attorney, A. OAKEY HALL, acting as the attorney of JOHN DE LA MONTAGNE, who is now in Europe, drew a check on the Broadway Bank for $183 75. payable to the order of WM. DE LA MONTAGNE, father of JOHN, who lives at No. 149 Madison-street. The check was deposited in the Post-office and directed to No. 139 Madison, that being the old number of JOHN DE LA MONTAGNE's residence before the recent renumbering of the street. The letter-carrier delivered the letter as directed, and the similarity of the names MONTAGUE and MONTAGNE, naturally led Mrs. MONTAGUE, to whom the letter was delivered, to suppose that it was intended for her husband. When he came home it was opened by him, and although he discovered that it was intended for another person, yet he was tempted by the coincidence in the names, to indorse the check, (merely adding "[???]e la" before his own name,) and dispose of it to one JOSEPH CONNOLLY, who, in depositing it in a bank for collection, discovered that the indorsement was a forgery. It is rather curious that the renumbering of a street should be followed by such a coincidence in the names of an old and a new manner, and that this very coincidence should tempt a man to the commission of a felony.

abstract: DESTUCTIVE FIRE IN NEWARK. Yesterday morning, about 2 o'clock, a fire broke out in the buildings of the Morris and Essex Railroad Company, near the depot of that Company at Newark, which consumed a large brick building 100x30 feet, used for storing wood, also a large building containing four locomotives the Passaic, Hudson, Orange and Pequest. The latter was undergoing repairs. Three of the engines were first-class and cost $10,000 each.
lead_paragraph: DESTUCTIVE FIRE IN NEWARK. -- Yesterday morning, about 2 o'clock, a fire broke out in the buildings of the Morris and Essex Railroad Company, near the depot of that Company at Newark, which consumed a large brick building 100x30 feet, used for storing wood, also a large building containing four locomotives -- the Passaic, Hudson, Orange and Pequest. The latter was undergoing repairs. Three of the engines were first-class and cost $10,000 each. They were all destroyed, together with the machinery and tools of the machine-shop. A small building, and some lumber sheds belonging to Messrs. EAGLES & Co., wagon-makers, were also consumed, and also a frame tenement occupied by an Irish family, and owned by a Mr. SWEENEY. The fire raged for nearly four hours. The loss of the Morris and Essex Company is estimated at about $25,000; fully insured in the Mechanics' and New-Jersey Insurance Companies of Newark. The loss of Messrs. EAGLES & Co. was about $1,000 -- insured in New-York. Mr. SWEENEY's loss is about $300 -- fully insured. The fire will not in any way impede the travel on the road, which continued yesterday as usual. The fire was undoubtedly the work of an incendiary as no fire was ever used in the building where it originated.

A joint resolution to compensate the crew of the steamer Monitor, for the loss of clothing, &c., was passed. A communication was received, through the Secretary of War, from CHARLES H. HASWELL, regarding the Banks transports. The Fortification bill was passed. The bill to establish the gauge of the Pacific Railroad and its branches at four feet 8 1/2 inches, was passed. The bill donating lands to Michigan and Wisconsin for a military road was passed. The bill organizing the Courts of the District of Columbia was called up, but was not disposed of. The Senate adjourned after an Executive session.

abstract: Texas, Our Flag in; Mississippi; Our Navy in the
snippet: Texas, Our Flag in; Mississippi; Our Navy in the
lead_paragraph: Operations on the Mississippi, below Vicksburgh, bid fair to be aided henceforth in a very effective manner by our gunboats. The most gallant ram of our Western flock, the Queen of the West, is still lying below Vicksburgh, taking a brief respite after her wonderful dash down the river; and we have news this morning that the new Monitor Indianola has run the batteries at Vicksburgh, and now keeps company with the Queen. Whether these boats are to take any direct part in the attack upon Vicksburgh, we do not know; but there is an important and immediate work in which they could profitably be employed. The two gunboats are amply sufficient to clear the whole Mississippi River and all its tributaries of every sort of rebel craft -- of all the steamboats bearing supplies to the rebels at Vicksburgh and Port Hudson, whether they come down from Texas by way of the Red River, or up from Lower Louisiana by the Atchafalaya. The Queen of the West, herself, burnt three of these steamers and destroyed great quantities of supplies, beside capturing the town of Vandalia with a force of seven tars. But the Indianola is a far superior boat to the Queen. She belongs to the class of Monitors which have been building for service on the Western waters, and is much like our seagoing Monitors in her main features. The rebels have nothing that could stand for a moment against her. Even the boasted rebel iron-faced City of Vicksburgh could not stand the assaults of the Queen, and has had to take refuge from her iron nose behind a lot of scows. It has been reported that the rebels have three iron-clads building up the Red River; but we think it more likely that they have three hundred building in the Great Sahara. The Red River is said also to be barred on its lower waters by a raft, which the rebels can open a passage through at their pleasure. This is a likelier yarn, though unlikely enough. But no supply-boat would ever come this side of the raft or the river, if one or two of our gunboats were scouring the Lower Mississippi. We do not see that these two craft could be put to more important service than that thus indicated; and we presume Gen. GRANT intends to use them for that purpose.

abstract: Pacific Railroad in Congress
snippet: Pacific Railroad in Congress
lead_paragraph: We are shocked to observe that Congress has not specified the diameter of the Pacific Railway axles -- a subject not only of vastly greater importance to the safety of passengers than the guage of the track which Congressmen do attempt to dictate, but which legislation is equally competent to prescribe. It is true that physical laws have settled the principles upon which these and other engineering problems are successfully solved; but shall this great National highway dare to be unsafe and expensive when its mechanical details have formed the subject of Congressional orations? It is true that the steamship Foh Kim, on her trial trip, last week, did not cease to work economically when "cutting off" short, even after they had opened Chief Engineer ISHERWOOD's book against "cutting off" short, and solemnly laid it right on the cylinder head; but however regardless nature may turn out to be of official opinions, shall any Senator dare to face a constituency whom he has outraged by neglecting to ingraft some original notion of his own -- good or bad, just as freaky Nature is in the humor to consider it -- upon the people's own railroad? What is the use of having any Congress, if engineers, plodding in a slough of traditions and formulas -- and, we may add, soldiers, clambering over the same rusty treadmill, as old as gunpowder -- cannot for once be compelled to turn a short corner and conform to the supreme power of the land?

abstract: the Observance of; Emigration Commissioners; Sixteenth Annual Report; Commissioner's 16th annual report
snippet: the Observance of; Emigration Commissioners; Sixteenth Annual Report; Commissioner's 16th annual report
lead_paragraph: The Commissioners of Emigration have just completed the sixteenth annual report of their proceedings, and of the condition of the peculiar interests under their charge. 1862, like 1860 and 1861, shows a great diminution of the number of emigrants arriving at this port, in comparison with others, since 1847. Like the previous three years, 1862 was marked by a much improved state of health and general condition of emigrants, and the greatly diminished number of those requiring hospital treatment or other immediate relief on their first landing. The whole number of emigrants arrived at this port during the year was 12,660 more than during the preceding year. The number in the hospitals and of those otherwise receiving support or pecuniary assistance from the Board is less than in any former year; and although the decreased number of persons paying commutation reduced the income of the Commission much below that of most former years, yet the improved system and economy of their establishments, together with diminished county claims, enabled them to meet the current expenditures of the year, and to extinguish all debts, with the exception of those secured by mortgage on their real estate, and contracted principally in the purchase or improvement of their lands. There are no outstanding debts or claims, except such as are in dispute or to litigation. The labors of the Commissioners have been greatly diminished by improvements in the system, and their duties and responsibilities have been lessened by the operation of the law in relation to the removal of the Quarantine. The whole number of passengers landed at this port during the year 1862 was 105,383. Of these, 29,079 were citizens, or persons not subject to bonds or commutation was paid, or bonds executed, showing an increase in alien emigrants to 10,777 over 1861, and 28,836 less than in 1860; 3,016 less than in 1859; 2,283 less than in 1858, and 107,467 less than in 1857; whilst the proportion to the average of former years, since 1847, is much less than half. Of these emigrants, 32,217 were from Ireland, 27,740 from Germany, 7,975 from England, and 8,374 from other countries. The number cared for and treated in the State Emigrant Refuge and Hospital, Ward's Island, was 3,247; the number in the Lunatic Asylum was 151 -- number remaining, 66; and in the City Asylum, 9. The total number of cases of small-pox treated was 86. The number of sick sent to the New-York and to the St. Vincent Hospitals was 37; number returned to Europe at their own request, 100; forwarded to various places inland and to Canada, 178; number supplied with board and lodging, 3,649; number buried, 273; provided with situations, 6,636; number relieved and forwarded in the several counties of the State, and chargeable to the Commission, 2,343. Grand total of destitute alien emigrants landed at the port of New-York during the past five years, who were relieved, forwarded and provided with employment by the Commission, in the State and City of New-York during 1862, 16,558. The whole number of days spent in the State Emigrant Hospital and Refuge, on Ward's Island, was 207,380.

abstract: It were certainly unpatriotic, and impolitic, to draw any comparison between the French and American stage, which did not turn wholly to the advantage of the latter. But it is possible perhaps, to indirectly hint that to certain dramatic walks light com- ...
lead_paragraph: It were certainly unpatriotic, and impolitic, to draw any comparison between the French and American stage, which did not turn wholly to the advantage of the latter. But it is possible perhaps, to indirectly hint that to certain dramatic walks -- light comedy and the vaudeville business, for instance -- the French character is somewhat better adapted than either the English or American, excellent in other domains of dramatic art as these latter may be. As a heavy father, the Frenchman, in all human probability, would make a signal failure, and furnish another warning to the many on record against attempting what clearly and constitutionally lies beyond one's strength; nor do we think he would achieve eminent success in the character of a roaring lover, who shoots caresses and endearments at his mistress, as though she were an iron-plated target, and they rifled projectiles wherewith he was trying experiments. But as an imponderous parent, or a light lover, who speaks in natural tones, and carries the manners of modern society upon the stage in a play which attempts to deal with the present period, we think the Frenchman generally manages to distance, not only our glorious country, but also that distant one which we sometimes affectionately address as mother. He usually contrives to enter a hypothetical room on the stage as he would a real one off from it, he is generally thoughtful enough to remove his hat while in the presence of ladies, and talk with his eyes turned toward those whom he is supposed to address, and not toward the audience outside the footlights. It is also worthy of remark that very few cases are on record in hospitals of the French actor having broken any of his own limbs, or seriously injured the furniture by tumbling over it in entering or leaving the stage drawing-room. And by no possible torture of the lips nor convulsion of the epiglottis can he pronounce ciel in a way at all analagous to "sk-e-ei," nor convert enfant into "ch-e-ild."

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, the Assembly's amendments to the General Bounty bill were agreed to. The bill to confirm the acts of Supervisors regarding bounties was passed; also the bill to extend the time for the completion of the Albany and Susquehanna Railroad. A bill to promote enlistments was reported. It provides that volunteers now in the service shall receive $50 bounty on reenlistment for one year, or $75 for three years or the war. The bill to enforce the responsibility of stockholders in banking associations was ordered to a third reading. The bill to appoint a Receiver-General for the Trust Funds was sent to the Judiciary Committee. The Senate then adjourned until the evening of the 25th inst.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, a communication was received from the Secretary of the Treasury, making a statement of the amount of Government Cotton sold at New-York. It appears from this statement that 3,325 bales and 1,779 bags have been sold, realizing $96,562. The credentials of Ex-Gov. MORGAN, as Senator from New-York, were presented. The President was called upon for a copy of a letter from Lieut.-Gen. SCOTT to the Secretary of War, dated Oct. 4, 1861. A bill to provide for the collection and sale of abandoned property, and for the prevention of fraud in insurrectionary districts, was introduced. The bills concerning the rank of Medical officers in the Navy, and to amend the act equalizing the grade of line officers in the navy, were reported back from the Naval Committee. A bill to further promote the efficiency of the navy was reported from the same Committee. The bill organizing a Signal Corps during the present rebellion was passed. The bill for the discharge of State prisoners was called up, and Mr. TRUMBULL, of Illinois, offered a substitute, giving the President power, when Congress is not in session, to suspend the writ of habeas corpus, etc. The Senate refused to strike out the third section of the original bill, providing for the suspension of the habeas corpus, 27 to 13. The subject was debated at considerable length, but the bill was finally postponed without action. The report of the Conference Committee on the Legislative Appropriation bill was not agreed to -- the disagreement being in reference to the mileage of members from the Pacific States. Another Committee was asked for. The Naval Appropriation bill was then considered, and several important amendments were made.

abstract: Provost-Marshal-General DRAPER is actively engaged in the duties of his office, and is preparing to move into more commodious quarters. The work of arresting deserters is proceeding satisfactorily. An instance occurred a day or two ago showing how thoroughly the system of following up desertons is perfected. It appears that a man named BURTON HOOD deserted from the Third Delaware Regiment, and took refuge on board the schooner John Porder, at Georgetown, Del. An effort was made to arrest him there, but through the connivance of the Captain of the vessel he escaped. Information was sent to Provost-Marshal DRAPER that the vessel would probably arrive at New-York, and accordingly Officers MARSH and EDWARDS were put upon the alert. The vessel did arrive at New-York, was boarded by the officers, and the man arrested and safely lodged on Governor's Island. This is a fair sample of the vigilance and success with which deserters are pursued.

abstract: The National; a Pledge of Success
snippet: The National; a Pledge of Success
lead_paragraph: The Conscription Act, which has just passed the Senate, is the grandest pledge yet given that our Government means to prevail, and will prevail. It is really the nation's first assertion of a purpose to command the means for its own preservation. Hitherto these means have all been contingent and precarious. Our military strength was all dependent on individual good will in volunteering, and upon the good will of State officials in heeding, and adequately carrying out the calls of the Government for their just proportions of soldiers. The results have astonished the world. They will go into history as the most extraordinary manifestation of public spirit in all time. But, in their very nature, they were unsuited to a long war. There never was such a war, however just or necessary, that did not beget faction and opposition in its progress; and there never will be, so long as there is any wickedness or weakness in human nature. To throw the burdens of the war upon those only who shall remain true to it, would be rewarding unfaithfulness. To trust in any degree to its opponents for the means to carry it on, would be to make calculation impossible, and to hazard everything. If it be the supreme duty of the Government to save itself, it follows that it should have a supreme control over the means. It now prepares to assume that control; and therein, we say, is the best of all guarantees of its final success.

abstract: The New Hartford Convention
snippet: The New Hartford Convention
lead_paragraph: We hope no one will fail to read the series of resolutions adopted by the Connecticut Democratic Convention, which on Wednesday nominated Mr. T.H. SEYMOUR for Governor of that State. The issue with the Administration is clearly put. The policy of a cessation of hostilities with the rebels is boldly proclaimed. The doctrine of State sovereignty and independence is asserted in the first resolution, while the "heresy of Secession" is oddly enough repudiated in the third. The Conscription bill is declared to be subversive of the sovereignty of the States, and the State authorities are called upon to "sternly resist" its operation. The "banking system" adopted by the Senate is pronounced unconstitutional and dangerous to the principles on which our Government is founded. The Emancipation Proclamation is assailed. A categorical statement of the recent "usurpations" of the National Administration is made, and it is declared that if sanctioned they will destroy the Union, and "establish upon the common ruins of the liberties of the people and the sovereignty of the States a consolidated military despotism." A great many other things are protested against and denounced; and about the only thing in our recent history that is not denounced is the rebellion of the Southern traitors, and the atrocious usurpations of the Richmond despotism.

abstract: America, Designs of, on France
snippet: America, Designs of, on France
lead_paragraph: We referred yesterday to the long-cherished purposes of France in regard to America. It is no secret to persons at all familiar with his views, that LOUIS NAPOLEON has always regarded, as essential to France, the possession of colonies in America, the arrest of the United States in their progress southward, and the control of a cotton-growing region to offset that of England in India. It is equally well known that this is not only the personal policy of the present Emperor, but the settled and traditional policy of France.

abstract: THE NEW-YORK SEMI-WEEKLY TIMES is published THIS MORNING, and may be had at the counter of the publication office in wrappers ready for mailing. In addition to the latest intelligence by telegraph up to the moment of going to press, there will be found in the current number full details of all military movements in the different departments from the pens of our special correspondents. Also, all official orders, reports and documents, and the latest and fullest Washington news. European news, with graphic letters from our correspondents in London and Paris, giving the tone of public feeling abroad, is made a special and permanent feature. In addition to Editorials on all the current topics of the day, the SEMI-WEEKLY TIMES has a page of carefully prepared commercial matter, giving the latest financial news and market reports: items of agricultural and domestic interest, compiled from sources many of which are otherwise inaccessible to the American reader; and marriages and deaths of the week.

abstract: THE DUMMY ENGINE. -- The Committee of the Brooklyn Board of Aldermen, consisting of Messrs. TERNAN, BELKNAP and M. MURPHY, appointed at the last meeting to inspect the dummy engine, now in operation on the Bergen Point Railroad, and to report thereon, visited Jersey City yesterday in company with Dr. THOMPSON, President of the Brooklyn Central, Hon. JOHN A. CROSS, of the Broadway; Mr. S.L. HUSTED, of the Brooklyn City; Dr. COGOSWELL, of the Boston and Maine Railroad, and others. They rode along the route, a distance of several miles, and received all necessary information in regard to the working of the engine, and were enabled to judge from observation whether or not it was adaptable to the crowded streets of a city. The experiments proved highly satisfactory to all -- those connected with the management of railroads especially -- who expressed themselves convinced of its utility for the purposes for which it is designed, and Mr. HUSTED, of the City Railroad, gave it as his opinion that within three years the dummy would drive out the horse cars as effectually as the horse cars had driven out the stages. The Committee will probably submit their report next Monday evening.

abstract: Colorado Enabling Act; Nebraska, Enabling Act for; Enabling Acts for Nebraska, Nevada and Colorado; Enabling Act for
snippet: Colorado Enabling Act; Nebraska, Enabling Act for; Enabling Acts for Nebraska, Nevada and Colorado; Enabling Act for
lead_paragraph: We notice that three bills were before the Senate yesterday to enable three of the Territories of the far West, (Nebraska, Nevada and Colorado,) to take steps preparatory to their admission into the Union as States. The population of the two first named Territories is very small. Nebraska, by last census, had a population of 28,000, and has grown but very little since then. Nevada and then less than 7,000 inhabitants, but now [???] to have thrice that number. Colorado was then reported at 34,000, and has now probably between forty and fifty thousand. We do not believe in the propriety of creating States out of Territories which have so few inhabitants. The bills should provide that they shall attain a respectable population before they are entitled to take rank in the Senate with New-York. One hundred thousand souls would certainly be small enough for a minimum limit.

abstract: Paper Duty, Memorial of Manufacturers
snippet: Paper Duty, Memorial of Manufacturers
lead_paragraph: -- FRANK W. BIRD, of Walpole, Mass., paper manufacturer, testified before the Legislative Committee, which is considering the paper duty question, that he was a member of the "combination," and that he had no doubt its action in regard to prices had increased the advance in paper. He favored a reduction of the duty, believing it would prove a benefit to the manufacturers themselves. He said the action of the manufacturers in combining had been disastrous to their own interests. He would have a medium duty, that would bring paper makers and publishers on a common medium ground. With the present duty there is no revenue from imported paper whatever, and the finances of the country would be benefited by a reduction. He did not fear foreign manufacturers in a fair field in any branch of New-England industry, other things being equal.

abstract: In Gulf Department, Difficulties About
snippet: In Gulf Department, Difficulties About
lead_paragraph: Our New-Orleans correspondent confirms the rumors which have been current as to difficulties between the white and black regiments at Ship Island and Baton Rouge, in the Department of the Gulf. We see no reason why this state of things should be allowed to spring up. White and black troops should not be brigaded together or stationed together. The Emancipation Proclamation specified the use to which black troops should be primarily put, when raised, as "garrisoning forts and positions;" and there are forts enough now in our hands in the Gulf Department to furnish duty for ten times the number of black troops we have there. As we advance up the river, too, there will be a continual demand for post garrisons. When the sickly weather comes on, in the Gulf and on the river, our while soldiers will be glad enough to have this work taken off their hands by the acclimated negroes; and there will be no quarreling for precedence in the duty.

abstract: THE GERMAN OPERA IN BROOKLYN. A new era has dawned, operatically, upon the people of Brooklyn, and for the first time since the opening of their superb Academy of Music they are permitted to attend a series of operas pure and undefiled, uncut, unshorn and in their original entirety.
lead_paragraph: THE GERMAN OPERA IN BROOKLYN. -- A new era has dawned, operatically, upon the people of Brooklyn, and for the first time since the opening of their superb Academy of Music they are permitted to attend a series of operas pure and undefiled, uncut, unshorn and in their original entirety. Under the conscientious conduct of CARL ANSCHUTZ, the German Opera Troupe have given "Fidelio," and the "Magic Flute," with emident success; and on Tuesday last achieved a triumph worthy of record, in FLOTOW's charming opera of "Martha," which was rendered with a fidelity unknown to the Italian stage, and with an effect rarely produced by our most celebrated prima donnas. Mad. ROTTER, whose action is not inferior to her acknowledged vocal power, carried the audience by storm, and created an enthusiasm unprecedented in the lyric annals of the Academy.

lead_paragraph: THE BELT RAILROAD. -- The Aldermanic Railroad Committee gave a hearing, yesterday morning, on the resolution to permit the Belt Railroad to run through Fifty-seventh-street, between Eighth and Tenth avenues, instead of passing through Fifty-ninth-street. A petition in favor of taking this change, and a remonstrance against it, were presented. Neither document had many signatures attached to it. Two or three gentlemen spoke favorably. Their only argument was, that Fifty-seventh-street, being seventy feet wide between the curbstones, and Fifty-ninth-street only thirty feet, a double track would interfere with the ordinary travel in the latter, and as the Railroad would certainly be built, it was desirable that a wider street should be used -- a plan that would be entirely satisfactory to the Railroad Company. Only one gentleman appeared in opposition. He feared the Railroad would lessen the value of his property in Fifty-seventh-street. The Committee will give a further hearing at an early day.

abstract: There appears to be no reason to question the vigor and completeness of the reaction which is taking place in English opinion upon the subject of the American war. The late meeting at Exeter Hall surpassed in numbers and enthusiasm anything that has been witnessed since the days of the AntiCorn-Law League. A subsequent one at
lead_paragraph: There appears to be no reason to question the vigor and completeness of the reaction which is taking place in English opinion upon the subject of the American war. The late meeting at Exeter Hall surpassed in numbers and enthusiasm anything that has been witnessed since the days of the AntiCorn-Law League. A subsequent one at Bradford, the heart of the great West Riding of Yorkshire, was almost as large and fully as excited, and was crowded in imposing force by the brawny and hard-headed race, who marched into Wakefield in a gigantic column to vote for "MORPETH and Free Frade," at the famous election of 1845. Even in Liverpool, the Confederate prophet, SPENCE, has been shouted down when he attempted once more to make the Apostle Paul and Onesimus do duty for the slaveholders. And, by all accounts, the flame is spreading. The Spectator, which is by no means disposed to take a sanguine view of our affairs, predicts that in three months more the friends of the North will have made a clean sweep of the island, and elicited from the middle and lower classes a shout of encouragement for what it calls "the narrow-minded but indomitable race," which is struggling through many failures and many blunders "toward the ultimate magnificent result."

abstract: In the Senate yesterday, a communication was received from the Secretary of the Treasury regarding the frauds in the New-York Customhouse. The joint resolution to facilitate the payment of sick and wounded soldiers in the hospitals, etc., was passed. A bill to enable the people of Nebraska to take steps preparatory to an admission into the Union was reported from the Committee on Territories; also, a similar bill regarding Colorado. The Post Route bill, providing for a bridge across the Ohio River, was reported from the Post-office Committee. The bill to appoint an Assistant Treasurer, and to increase the compensation of the Treasurer, was passed. The bill to provide a temporary Government for the Territory of Arizona was passed. The bill reorganizing the Courts of the District of Columbia was then debated until 4 1/2 o'clock, when the Senate took a recess. During the evening session a bill was introduced by Mr. WILSON, of Massachusetts, authorizing the organization of a Pioneer brigade. The matter of the arrest and discharge of certain State and political prisoners was then considered.
lead_paragraph: In the Senate yesterday, a communication was received from the Secretary of the Treasury regarding the frauds in the New-York Customhouse. The joint resolution to facilitate the payment of sick and wounded soldiers in the hospitals, etc., was passed. A bill to enable the people of Nebraska to take steps preparatory to an admission into the Union was reported from the Committee on Territories; also, a similar bill regarding Colorado. The Post Route bill, providing for a bridge across the Ohio River, was reported from the Post-office Committee. The bill to appoint an Assistant Treasurer, and to increase the compensation of the Treasurer, was passed. The bill to provide a temporary Government for the Territory of Arizona was passed. The bill reorganizing the Courts of the District of Columbia was then debated until 4 1/2 o'clock, when the Senate took a recess. During the evening session a bill was introduced by Mr. WILSON, of Massachusetts, authorizing the organization of a Pioneer brigade. The matter of the arrest and discharge of certain State and political prisoners was then considered.

abstract: ALLEGED BURGLARY AND GRAND LARCENY.  A man named ISADORR ROACH, was arrested yesterday upon the complaint of a wealth Germ in lady of the namde of O'LEA GRUMPEL, who alleges that she arrived in this City about three weeks ago, direct from California, with about $5,000, consisting mainly of gold and silver coin, diamond jewelry,  Upon her arrival in this City she deposited all her money and older valuables with a German Consul.
lead_paragraph: ALLEGED BURGLARY AND GRAND LARCENY. -- A man named ISADORE ROACH, was arrested yesterday upon the complaint of a wealth German lady of the namde of O'LEA GRUMPEL, who alleges that she arrived in this City about three weeks ago, direct from California, with about $5,000, consisting mainly of gold and silver coin, diamond jewelry, &c. Upon her arrival in this City she deposited all her money and other valuables with a German Consul. Soon afterward she went to the house of the accused, who is an uncle of hers, residing in Liberty-street, for the purpose of making a short visit. While she was there, the prisoner persuaded her to take her jewelry and money from the possession of the German Consul, and to bring the same to his house, which she accordingly did. On the following evening, the room in ROACH's house, where the valuables had been deposited, was entered by some person, who cut the glass of the window with a diamond, entered the apartment, and stole all the money and jewelry, and also a shawl valued at $1,000, belonging to the complainant. ROACH was arrested soon afterward, but upon a thorough search of his person and premises being made by the Police, none of the property was found. The suspicions are strong against him, from the fact that the accused is a glazier by trade, and was the only person besides the complainant who knew where the property was deposited. Justice DOWLING held him for examination.

The Produce Exchange yesterday resolved, by a unanimous vote, to close doors and stop operations on that day, and a like action will probably be taken by other commercial bodies to-day.

abstract: The Hartford Convention; The Issue Stated
snippet: The Hartford Convention; The Issue Stated
lead_paragraph: The Connecticut Democracy have entitled themselves to the thanks of all loyal men for making so clean an issue in their late Convention. In their resolution that "the time has arrived when all the true lovers of the Constitution are ready to abandon the monstrous fallacy that the Union can be restored by the armed hand," and in their nomination of THOMAS H. SEYMOUR for Governor, who has unqualifiedly opposed the war from the start, the essential party distinction is fairly recognized. The line is drawn just where alone it consistently can be so as to make but two sides, one for unconditional peace men, and the other for unconditional war men. We like this. It is veracious; it is earnest; it is what these momentous days demand.

abstract: The news from Mexico this morning, received, by way of Havana, gives rather a bad exhibit of the condition of the French invading forces. They have met with several reverses recently, and sickness is very prevalent among them. The French evacuated Tampico out the 13th ult., after having committed various excesses, but halted in their transports on the bar. The Mexican forces, under Gen. GARZA, soon afterward entered the city, and on the 21st and 22d attacked the French and drove them away. The French war steamer Lance got aground and was fired, and they were forced to abandon a schooner loaded with munitions of war, a bark full of provisions, and another vessel half full of coal. They had also been driven out of the town of T[???]cotalpan, fifty miles southeast of Vera Cruz, and forced take refuge on board a war steamer, leaving several killed and wounded, besides arms, horses and provisions. On the 27th a mule train, loaded with provisions for the French army, was attacked and captured, seven leagues from Orizaba. Another train of three hundred mules had also been captured, and still another of five hundred. On the 30th 1,200 French, escorting a train of wagons, were attacked and defeated at a place called El Organo, with twenty-six killed and thirty or forty wounded. The Mexicans captured several of the wagons, twelve mules, and arms and knapsacks. Several other Mexican successes are mentioned in our advices. The French had established three hospitals -- one at Perote and two at Quecholac -- 2,000 sick soldiers being already in the latter. Several atrocities on the part of the French are mentioned, one of which is the shooting of a Mexican named BERNARDI, taken prisoner while bearing a flag of truce, and escorting the American Consul and Secretary of Legation from the Capital to the French lines at Perote.

abstract: The newsboys in the army are in a state of insubordination. They are evidently "demoralized." The telegraph advises us that they have refused to do duty, unless Gen. HOOKER rescinds the order restricting their numbers to one to each division. This is quite in keeping with the general course of things in the army, so far as a portion of its officers and men are concerned. We are not at all surprised that the newsboys should have come to the conclusion that they had as good a right to command the army as Gen. HOOKER. He ought to get in the habit of submitting his orders for their approval, before issuing them. We shall probably have a strike of the sutlers next, then of the persons employed in the Quartermaster's Department, and we should not be at all surprised to find the example finally infect the Generals of Divisions.

abstract: HUDSON COUNTY COURT. -- The trial of ANTOINE SCHAFFER, on a charge of placing obstructions on the New-Jersey Railroad track, near East Newark, in July last, by which a train of cars was thrown down an embankment, was concluded in the Hudson County Court, at 11 o'clock, Friday forenoon. The jury had not agreed upon a verdict at 5 o'clock P.M. SCHAFFER was tried on the same charge at the last term, but the jury failed to agree. General, alias ABRAHAM GREENTHAL, was placed on trial on an indictment for perjury against a man named RUTTENBERGH. The trial was not concluded at the time of adjourning.

abstract: Three days claim the privilege, this year, of the holiday celebration in honor of WASHINGTON'S Birthday. Yesterday, as will be seen by the reports in today's TIMES, dinners were eaten, addresses were delivered, and parades were made, in token of Gotham's pious regard for the man who was first in the affections of the nation.
lead_paragraph: Three days claim the privilege, this year, of the holiday celebration in honor of WASHINGTON's Birthday. Yesterday, as will be seen by the reports in today's TIMES, dinners were eaten, addresses were delivered, and parades were made, in token of Gotham's pious regard for the man who was first in the affections of the nation. To-day, various religious societies and moral organizations will hold appropriate services. The Order of United Americans will observe the day with religious exercises at the Cooper Institute, at 2 1/2 o'clock, when addresses will also be made by Rev. Messrs. COREY, SKINNER, and CARPENTER. In the evening, at Rev. Dr. OSGOOD's Church, the music at the vesper service will be commemorative of the Father of his Country; and in many of the leading churches, sermons appropriate to the crisis of the nation will be delivered.

abstract: Nicnames Among Political Parties
snippet: Nicnames Among Political Parties
lead_paragraph: Men betake themselves so naturally to the use of epithets, as a weapon, in any contest, that the study of the epithets in use during any given period is often a very necessary preparation for the history of it. This is likely to be a more or less important part of history in proportion to the intensity of public feeling at the time. The fluctuations of feeling, and the different directions which it has taken, may be pretty accurately traced in the epithets applied at the different stages of the progress of events. The past two years have formed no exception to this rule. Let us look a little at their history from this point of view.

abstract: By the arrival of the steamship Canada at Halifax, we have advices from Europe one week later. She left Liverpool on the 7th, and Queenstown on the 8th inst. The insurrection in Poland in said to be spreading.
lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the steamship Canada at Halifax, we have advices from Europe one week later. She left Liverpool on the 7th, and Queenstown on the 8th inst. The insurrection in Poland in said to be spreading. A sanguinary battle had been fought at Wengrow, in which the insurgents had been defeated and the town captured by the Russians. The British Parliament was in session, and the Queen's speech had been delivered. With regard to American affairs, Her Majesty said she had abstained from taking any steps with a view to inducing a cessation of hostilities, because it had not seemed that any such overtures could be attempted with a probability of success. She, however, viewed with the deepest concern the conflict which still raged, and witnessed with grief the distrees which the war inflicted upon a portion of her subjects. It was reported by the London Times that certain parties in Paris had offered a loan to the rebel Government of five millions sterling, on the basis of cotton at 5d. per pound, with the option of exchanging for Confederate bonds at 70, bearing 8 per cent. interest, and that the offer had been partly accepted. An insurrection had broken out in Cochin China, and desperate attacks had been made on the French forces. Severe fighting had taken place, but the insurgents had been repulsed with heavy loss. The French Emperor had asked the Spanish Government to send back the troops to Cochin China, but they had declined on the ground that they could not violate treaties. The Liverpool cotton market was dull and prices were weak. Breadstuffs were dull but steady, and provisions flat. Consols were quoted at 92 3/8 for money.

lead_paragraph: It is very difficult to argue with men who deny the truth of axioms. A man who denies the existence of the force of gravity, who declares that the sun does not emit light but darkness, or that two and two make five, is always a hard man to reason against. But there are some men of this sort who discuss the war and the means of putting a stop to the rebellion, and who, strange to say, are accepted as oracles by not a few. We point to Mr. VALLANDIGHAM as a distinguished specimen of this style of reasoner.
