abstract: At the opening of the present political campaign in Prussia, Herr VON BISMARK and his master have committed a serious blunder. They asked the Lower Chamber to sanction with its "retrospective approbation" the past conduct of the Government. They demand ...
lead_paragraph: At the opening of the present political campaign in Prussia, Herr VON BISMARK and his master have committed a serious blunder. They asked the Lower Chamber to sanction with its "retrospective approbation" the past conduct of the Government. They demand in fact, a Bill of Indemnity to legalize the arbitrary acts of Ministers in the recess. This faltering of the King, in the presence of the foe, is a virtual admission that, even in his own opinion, the course of his Government has not been in harmony with law. It is an admission that he and his Ministers are offenders against the Constitution, and need white-washing at the hands of the popular chamber. But that body has not the slightest intention of undertaking the work of purification, as may be inferred from the tenor of their response to the royal speech, which has been voted by an overwhelming majority of its members. Preposterous, indeed, would it be, were the King and his servile tools suffered to escape thus easily from the consequences of their acts, in raising taxes without legislative authority, in attempting to intimidate public opinion, and in trampling on the rights of the Nation's representatives -- especially as they mean to repeat all these outrages in the future, if they secure immunity from punishment by this act of indemnity. How utterly unworthy of such immunity both monarch and ministers are, has been shown by the fact that, when VON BISMARK became aware of the nature of the address which the Second Chamber had prepared for presentation to the King, he tried to force them to modify it by warning them that "there was a limit to which the King could listen to." The only ground of objection to the address was, that it described in inappropriate terms those very offences for which he had been soliciting the "retrospective approbation" of the Deputies. It did not even accuse the crown of complicity with the misdeeds of Ministers! In exonerating the King, however, from all responsibility for the acts of his Ministers, the authors of the address have dealt too tenderly with him. As long as a king maintains the neutral position of a constitutional monarch, it would be unjust to hold him accountable for the conduct of a Government over whose proceedings he exercises no control, and which can at any moment be hurled from power by the Legislature. But when a sovereign descends from this position, and assumes the leadership of a political party who are enemies of public liberty, he forfeits all claim to that consideration, and can no more use as a shield the maxim that "the King can do no wrong." WILLIAM has divested himself of the neutrality of a constitutional monarch, to become the Corypheus of an anti-national faction, and though courtesy prompted his Parliament to draw a distinction between him and his Ministers, be is not the less a party to the acts which have all but ruined them, and must share their odium. WILLIAM is, in fact, a martinet who loathes constitutionalism, and would fain dispense with its fetters, and govern his kingdom as he would a camp. In attempting to realize this crochet, he has done incalculable mischief to Prussia and his dynasty -- has outraged the rights of the people and the people's representatives -- has threatened the peace and destroyed the political prestige of the monarchy, and has inflicted deadly wounds on the common interests of all Germany.

abstract: Speech in New-York on Washington's Birthday; Republican Central Committee's Supper; Speech on N. Y. Washington's Birthday Supper; Republican Central Committee Supper on Washington's Birthday; Speech on Washington's Birthday
snippet: Speech in New-York on Washington's Birthday; Republican Central Committee's Supper; Speech on N. Y. Washington's Birthday Supper; Republican Central Committee Supper on Washington's Birthday; Speech on Washington's Birthday
lead_paragraph: Under the auspices of the Republican Central Committee, WASHINGTON's Birthday was celebrated at the City Assembly Rooms last evening, by a grand supper, accompanied by music and speeches; and the most interesting feature of the occasion was the fact that many ladies graced the supper with their presence. The room was tastefully decorated -- the American colors appearing in flags, banners and streamers. There were no less than six long tables, with about fifty guests to each. It is true, the proportion of ladies was small; but, the precedent of their presence will, it is to be hoped, assist in the much needed reform of our public dinners, or suppers -- which, by the way, are much the same thing. Of the supper itself, it is only necessary to say that it was furnished by that excellent caterer and popular gentleman, L.F. HARRISON, of Irving Hall, whose efforts on this occasion were duly appreciated by all. The confectionery ornamental pieces were appropriately decorated with miniature flags, and the whole affair was well managed. WM.A. DARLING presided, and at the table with him were, among other distinguished guests, Mayor Opdyke, Collector Barney, Edgar Ketchum, Col. Mix. Daniel S. Dickinson, Rev. Dr. Hitchcock, Sheridan Shook, Hon. E.D. Morgan, E.C. Cowdin, Alderman Smith, O.W. Brennan, C.S. Spencer, Alderman Hall, Dr. Lieber, Sinclair Tousey, and others of like note.

abstract: McDowell, Rev. John, of Philadelphia
snippet: McDowell, Rev. John, of Philadelphia
lead_paragraph: -- Rev. Dr. John McDowell died in Philadelphia on Feb. 13. He was born in Somerset County, N.J., on Sept. 10, 1780; entered the junior class of Princeton College in 1799, graduating in 1801; pursued his theological studies under Rev. Dr. John Woodhull, of Freehold; was licensed to preach in 1804; received his first call to preach from a Presbyterian Church at Elizabeth, N.J., where he remained until 1833, when he removed to Philadelphia. There he was successively pastor of the Central and Spring Garden Church, laboring with much acceptance. Dr. McDowell was intimately connected with many of the religious movements of the present century. He was one of the founders of the Princeton Theological Seminary, of which he continued a Director up to the time of his death, and for 46 years Secretary of the Board; a member of the Convention which formed the American Bible Society, in 1816; Moderator of the General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church, in 1820; a member of the Board of Domestic Missions, and Chairman of its Executive Committee from its organization, 30 years since; besides holding other important and honorable positions, which our limits will not allow us to mention. Dr. McDowell was the author of several works; among which may be mentioned, A System of Theology, Bible Class Manual, and a System of Bible Questions, for the use of Bible Classes and Sabbath Schools, the first, it is believed, ever published, and now published by the American Sunday School Union. He was a man of persevering and systematic industry, and great energy of character.

abstract: MACHADO ONCE MORE. -- Mr. JOHN A. MACHADO, who has been two or three times arrested within the last two years, on a charge of fitting out slavers from this port, yesterday surrendered himself to the United States District-Attorney, on learning that a Bench warrant had been issued for his arrest. The preliminary examination, on the first arrest of Mr. MACHADO, failed to sustain the charge, and he was released. On the second arrest a preliminary examination was had, pending which MACHADO was committed to Fort Lafayette on a charge of fitting out vessels to run the blockade. He was afterwards released from Fort Lafayette, and visited Cuba, from which place he has recently returned. Meantime the Grand Jury have found an indictment against him on the slave-trading charge, and a Bench warrant was issued for his arrest, as stated above. Judge SHIPMAN held him to bail in the sum of $4,000 to appear at the trial.

abstract: Currency in England During Napoleon's Wars and now in America
snippet: Currency in England During Napoleon's Wars and now in America
lead_paragraph: The question which most exercises the public mind at the present moment is the financial one. The price of Gold, which remained during the first year of the war so small as to excite little attention, began soon after the battles before Richmond slowly to rise. For eight months it has been almost constantly advancing, driven up by a factitious scarcity, and the unremitted efforts of speculators, till yesterday it stood at 162 1/2. Two widely different opinions rule the public mind in reference to the significancy of this rise. One class look upon the advance of gold as purely speculative, and as a merely accidental and unimportant effect of the excited state of public feeling. Others, still regarding gold as the standard of value, have seen in its rise the measure of a constant depreciation of the currency. Filled with prophetic forebodings, these men see for the country nothing but the continuance of this depreciation, and in its continuance nothing but financial ruin.

abstract: on Our National Finances--House
snippet: on Our National Finances--House
lead_paragraph: I have already stated, in the debate on the Finance bill, that I had no doubt of the constitutionality of the National Bank bill, proposed by the Secretary of the Treasury, nor had I any doubt that State banks were also constitutional; that both systems of banking might be useful within their sphere of action, and that I was willing the country should have both kinds of banking. That inasmuch as the National Government had hitherto failed to establish a permanent system of national banking, State banks had, as a necessary means of commerce and the operations of State Governments, become firmly established, and that the Supreme Court of the United States had, by repeated decisions, decided that they were constitutional.

abstract: With a Horrible Fracture in his Skull About 6 o'clock, yesterday morning, a man  named JOHN A. BOYLE, a native of South Carolina, aged 33 years, residing at No. 138 West Sixteenth street, was found dead at the front basement door
lead_paragraph: About 6 o'clock, yesterday morning, a man named JOHN A. BOYLE, a native of South Carolina, aged 33 years, residing at No. 138 West Sixteenth street, was found dead at the front basement door of the house above named. An examination of the body disclosed the fact that his skull was very badly fractured on the left side of the head, the fracture being about six inches long and two inches wide. The body was discovered by a servant at that early hour in the morning, and although it was warm at the time, life was entirely extinct. A post mortem examination was made by Dr. GALEN HUNTER, of the Coroner's office, and it was his opinion that death necessarily resulted almost instantaneously from the fracture.

abstract: -- Coroner NORRIS concluded the investigation, on Saturday night, into the circumstances attending the murder of Mrs. CECELIA MCLAUGHLIN, who was found dead in her room in Park-avenue, near Canton-street, on Friday morning. A number of witnesses were examined, but nothing was elicited to fasten the guilt directly upon any one, although all the attending circumstances would seem to indicate that either the husband, THOMAS MCLAUGHLIN, or the daughter, MARY ANN, or both, had a hand in the matter. Some of the tenants in the same house testified that they heard a noise as if caused by the slamming of a door, and the falling of a heavy body; screams and a cry of murder were also heard. No one went into MCLAUGHLIN's apartments to ascertain the cause, except JAMES MCCABE, residing on the second floor, who was sent for by the daughter. The deceased was lying on the floor dead when he entered. The daughter, according to her own statement, had been on a visit to a neighbor, and on her return saw her father holding her mother's head and wiping the blood from her face. She accused him of killing her, when he cleared her out of the room. The noise then made and her screams, it is thought, were what attracted the attention of the other occupants. The father also made a statement, without oath, in which he said that he had bought two pints of brandy on Thursday, and after disposing of it pulled off his boots and went to bed. His son FRANK woke him about 5 o'clock P.M., and told him that mother was lying dead on the floor. He got up, and lifting up her head wiped the blood from her face. His daughter then came in and accused him of the killing, but he denies having driven her out of the room. He knew nothing whatever of the cause of his wife's death. The son, FRANK, was likewise examined. He stated that he returned from play on Thursday afternoon, and found his mother lying dead upon the floor. The stove was tipped over, and the edge lying on her head. The stove-pipe had fallen down. He woke his father and informed him of what had occurred. It appears that the elder members of the family were in the habit of drinking to excess. They had frequent quarrels; and MCLAUGHLIN acknowledged that he had beaten his wife previous to this time. The physician's testimony showed that the right side of her skull was fractured, her left ear torn off, and that she had more than a dozen cuts and bruises about her head, face and upper part of the body. The jury were, however, unwilling, with the testimony before them, to render a hasty verdict, and, therefore, requested the Coroner to allow them till Tuesday before making their decision, which was granted MCLAUGHLIN and his daughter are meanwhile detained to await the result. MCLAUGHLIN was formerly a policeman of the First Precinct, and had the reputation of being a good officer until he commenced drinking rum, for which offence he was dismissed.

abstract: In the Senate on Saturday, the bill to amend the act to establish and equalize the grade of line officers in the navy was passed. The bill to divide the State of Michigan into two Judicial Districts was passed. The credentials of Hon. S.M. MORRILL, reelected from Maine, were presented. A resolution offered by Mr. POWELL, of Kentucky, directing an inquiry into the imprisonment of D.A. MAHONEY and others, was laid over. Mr. POWELL also gave notice that he should call for an investigation regarding the dispersion of a Convention recently at Frankfort, Kentucky. A bill to promote the health, comfort and efficiency of the army was referred to the Military Committee. The bill to grant lands to Kansas for the construction of railroads and telegraphs was passed. The bill relating to the discharge of State prisoners was then taken up, and debated at great length -- Mr. POWELL, of Kentucky, and Mr. WILSON, of Massachusetts, making the principal speeches. The matter was not disposed of when the Senate went into Executive session, and subsequently adjourned.

lead_paragraph: Mr. AUSCHUTZ's highly successful season of German Opera will close with the present week, and at the invitation of the Philadelphians, the company will appear once more in the Quaker City on Monday next. The programme for the week is highly interesting; to-night, the "Magic Flute;" to-morrow, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, the highly entertaining and delightful comic opera of the "Poacher;" on Wednesday, the company will give its one hundredth performance, and a programme worthy of so remarkable an occurrence has been prepared; on Thursday, AUBER's opera of "Fra Diavolo" will be given for the benefit of Mr. J. GRAFF; on Friday, there will be a grand closing performance at the New-York establishment, and on Saturday, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, a Grand Farewell Matinee, the first ever given in the sister city, at which FLOTOW's charming opera of "Martha" will be performed. It will be seen that Mr. ANSCHUTE's industry is equal to his other merits.

abstract: We have been looking daily, for a month past, to Vicksburgh and Charleston as the points at which the confronting armies should first come into actual collision. But if signs do not fail, the first battle may be at neither one nor the other of these places, but in a locality from which we have heard ominously little.
lead_paragraph: We have been looking daily, for a month past, to Vicksburgh and Charleston as the points at which the confronting armies should first come into actual collision. But if signs do not fail, the first battle may be at neither one nor the other of these places, but in a locality from which we have heard ominously little, although we know that an able leader, with a splendid army, has been preparing, with military rapidity, for the inevitable struggle. The Richmond Enquirer, of Friday last, says that there are rumors in that city of an advance of the Yankee army in Middle Tennessee; and it adds that two days previously cannonading had been heard on the rebel front and in the direction of Beech Grove. By the front of the rebel army, we suppose is meant the region along the line of railroad running from Murfreesboro southward to and beyond Tullahoma; for, so far as we know, these two places are still the headquarters of the respective armies. Beech Grove is a small town some twenty miles southeast of Murfreesboro, and five miles from the railroad; and if ROSECRANS has a column of his army there, it would seem that he is proposing to execute a movement on the rebel flank as well as on their front -- as he has but to march down the turnpike to Manchester, on the head-waters of Duck River, to be in a position to operate very advantageously against Tullahoma from the east.

abstract: -THREE STABLES FIRED IN ONE NIGHT -- THREE HORSES BURNED TO DEATH. -- Between 6 and 7 o'clock on Saturday evening a fire was discovered in the brick stable owned and occupied by ANDREW J. and GEORGE ODELL, at No. 89 Seventh-street. Two horses, valued at $300, were burned to death, and the stable was damaged to the amount of $200. About 10 o'clock the same evening a fire occurred in the basement stable No. 169 East Tenth-street, occupied by Mr. SCANLON. One horse, valued at $150, was destroyed. The flames spread to the carpenter shop of DAVIS & GRAHAM, situated on the floor above. Their loss is about $200. Mr. SCANLON is fully insured in the Manhattan Insurance Company. The building is of brick, owned by a Mr. SMITH, and was very much damaged....Soon after 12 o'clock, the same night, a third fire occurred in the stable of JOHN GLASS, No. 148 East Twelfth-street. The flames were soon discovered and extinguished before much damage had been done to the building or contents. The most remarkable fact is, that these fires all occurred in the same vicinity, within a few hours of each other, all of them in stables, and the Police report them all to have been the work of incendiaries. Fire-Marshal BAKER will investigate the circumstances of their origin to-day.

abstract: There prevails in the public mind a general sentiment of a great need of an efficient and thoroughly drilled corps to be devoted exclusively to the assistance and safety of the wounded, during and immediately after every battle. The public heart has been greatly pained, after almost every serious contest, to hear of large numbers of our wounded countrymen being compelled to lie a long time, in some instances several days, on the open ground, in helpless suffering and exhaustion from loss of blood, cold, wet, and hunger, and still the wonder grows that there has not long ago been arranged a thorough system of immediate relief to them. The anxiety of the country to see in active operation an efficient organization for this humane purpose, is believed to be second only to the anxiety to see the end of the rebellion. To lift the wounded man immediately from the ground and convey him to a place of safety, is the first impulse of every heart, and though to some it may seem to savor of mawkish philanthrophy to be in such haste to extend the hand of succor to those who go into battle, expecting to suffer from wounds which they have striven to inflict upon others, yet we are not to forget that a wounded man is no longer a warrior, and having offered his blood and his life for the cause, the duty of prompt and energetic action for his safety is then ours, as it before was his for us. Nor must it be forgotten that from the moment the weapon falls from his hand, the wounded foe is no longer such, and is entitled to all the "aid and comfort" in our power, which we may now render without treason.

abstract: From all  sources from our own correspondence, from private letters of soldiers, and from the Western Press we hear the most shocking and shameful accounts of the lack of hospital accommodations, and the bad treatment of sick soldiers in the armp of Gen. GRANT, opposite Vicksburgh.
lead_paragraph: From all sources -- from our own correspondence, from private letters of soldiers, and from the Western Press -- we hear the most shocking and shameful accounts of the lack of hospital accommodations, and the bad treatment of sick soldiers in the armp of Gen. GRANT, opposite Vicksburgh. The region itself is about as unhealthy all the year round as it well could be, and the sick and mortality lists of GRANT's army are excessive -- being three or four times as great as in the army of Gen. ROSECRANS, in Middle Tennessee. No proper hospital buildings have been raised, for the reason that it was hoped the army would not remain there any length of time, but would speedily move over to the high and wholesome region on the opposite side of the river. But instead of doing the best that was possible under bad circumstances -- instead of removing the sick away, or placing them on hospital steamboats, or using the best houses in the vicinity for their accommodation, they have been crowded into filthy negro shanties, dank hovels located in the swamp, and pens that are not fit for swine; while the few dry and roomy houses thereabouts are assigned to the officers for their use. The surgeons, apparently hopeless of contending successfully with adverse circumstances, seem to almost completely neglect their patients, and invite malaria and death to do their worst. On this latter point complaints are unfortunately too well founded to admit a doubt of their truth.

lead_paragraph: -- DISCLOSURES FROM WASHINTON. -- It is very pleasant to have been the means of bringing who such journals as the World and Tribune into harmony of sentiment. We have that delightful satisfaction. Both these organs are suitably and harmoniously shocked at our intimation that the country was probably on the eve of a rupture with France, and that it would be wise to make preparation for that contingency. The World was especially fearful that the expression of such an opinion might startle the weak nerves of "Wall-street," though its principal concern, (as was quite natural under the circumstances,) was for the "dignity of journalism." It made haste to announce that sundry Senators and other distinguished gentlemen, with Mr. SUMNER at their head, had called on the French Minister to assure him by their presence that they did not approve of the course of our Government in treating him and his Imperial Master with so little respect as was shown in declining his "suggestions" concerning the management of our domestic affairs. As this statement, however, was immediately denied, the World fell back to its original base.

abstract: In accordance with previous announcements, an "oration" was spoken in the large Hall of Cooper Institute, on Saturday evening, on the "State of the Union," by Mr. G.H. SNYDER, of the U.S. Circuit Court, for the Northern District of Illinois. Admittance 25 cents. Mr. SNYDER, however, did not meet with all the encouragement anticipated by his syllabus and he condensed accordingly. The hall was illuminated as promised, which rendered the counting of the audience an easier task for the reporters than it might otherwise have been. At the commencement of the "oration," the hall contained the following: Audience, 20; reporters, 4; ticket takers, 4; attendants on hall, 2; Captains of Police, 1; Sergeants of Police, 1; roundsmen, 1; patrolmen, 24. Mr. SNYDER thanked his audience for attending, and then proceeded to deliver his oration. He considered the nation in a troublous orate, and going rapidly to ruin. We had already sacrificed many valuable lives and a vast sum of money, and all we had obtained were promises to put down the rebellion. It was true we had gained some points, but it required more men to hold them than they were worth. We required a change or we must go down. The Constitution must be preserved at all hazards, and Mr. LINCOLN should resign and Gen. BUTLER be put in his place.

abstract: Free Labor in Louisiana
snippet: Free Labor in Louisiana
lead_paragraph: The important question, whether liberated slaves can be made to work as hired laborers, is being tested pretty extensively in Lower Louisiana. It has been discovered that the slaves within the parishes exempted from the operation of the Emancipation Proclamation are virtually emancipated by the fact that they are within our military lines; and as they amount to many thousands, and their former masters have very generally remained on their plantations, the latter, under the advice and with the cooperation of Gen. BANKS, have held consultations among themselves, and come to terms with their ex-slaves, as to their future relations with each other. No general plan has been adopted, each planter making such terms with the negroes as he finds convenient or possible. Our New-Orleans correspondent gives, this morning, a copy of the rules which have been drawn up by an old citizen of Louisiana for the management of his plantation, the labor on which is performed by his freed slaves; and their practicability is confirmed by an efficient negro overseer, who says that under these rules he can work any gang of negroes successfully. The rules provide that the negroes shall labor the usual number of hours, and receive about their usual supplies of food; but besides this, they are to get wages, averaging from $3 to $10 a month -- one-half of it at the end of each month, the balance at the end of the year. Various punishments are prescribed for bad conduct, and rewards for good conduct -- such as will appeal to the sensibilities, instincts and interests of the negro. The rules are in the main excellent, and if equally good ones have been adopted and are rigidly enforced on the other plantations, we do not see that anything better could be desired for the Louisiana or any other negroes. The plan is the best that has been adopted in any of those parts of the South occupied by our army -- as no military supervision or interference is called for. The working of these free-negro-labor schemes will be watched with great interest.

abstract: -- The Chamber of Commerce has remonstrated very warmly against the rejection by the Senate of the proposal to construct a submarine telegraph from Fortress Monroe to Galveston. Such a line would prove of immense importance in facilitating the operations of our navy, especially as the Spanish Government proposes to construct a line to be connected with it from Key West to Havana. It would be much easier than it is now, to direct the course of our vessels in pursuit of the rebel privateers, and would greatly increase the chances of their capture.

abstract: I have read once and again, at first eagerly, then with deliberation, your three articles on the designs of France, and appended the one of your excellent correspondent, "A Veteran Observer," whose communications I always welcome with peculiar pleasure.
lead_paragraph: I have read once and again, at first eagerly, then with deliberation, your three articles on the designs of France, and appended the one of your excellent correspondent, "A Veteran Observer," whose communications I always welcome with peculiar pleasure. All these, your own and his, denote that the enlargement and blackening of that "cloud," which, I think, I predicted once in the TIMES, the which one of your readers, a friend of mine, will well remember I have constantly pointed out as coming over us "from the Gulf of Mexico." The rumbling of its thunder may even now be heard by anticipative ears. What are we doing to make its bolts innocuous? How lies, for example, our own harbor, which has never yet been properly defended, not even at its southern approach?

abstract: -A large number of connoisseurs and picture lovers have within the last few days visited the Galleries of the Art Institute to view the collection of Mr. T.A. RICHARDS, which are to be sold to-night. There are 150 of the works of this well-known assist on exhibition, embracing landscapes, studies, sketches, "fruit, flower and thorn pieces." The landscapes are all American, and comprise views North and South. The fruits and flowers, too, are all native, and to the continent born. Some of the pieces are very charming -- well drawn, finely colored, and vital. If the sale be as well attended as the exhibition has been, and the attendants be as lavish in their bids as visitors have been in their praises, the Secretary of the Academy will achieve a pecuniary success equal to his artistic triumph.

lead_paragraph: SENTENCE OF PRISONERS. -- In the Hudson County Court, yesterday, Judge OGDEN pronounced the following sentences upon persons convicted during the present term: Mathias Galitzdorf, convicted of murder in the second degree, was sentenced to the State Prison for a term of fifteen years. General, alias Abraham Greenthal, convicted on three indictments for perjury and subornation of perjury, was sentenced to three years' imprisonment on each indictment, the terms to run together, and fines amounting in all to $500. Margaret Rose, (colored,) for secreting the birth of her child and burying it in a heap of ashes, thereby preventing a knowledge as to whether it was born alive or not, was sent to the State Prison one year. Thomas Madden, for stabbing an officer while in the discharge of his duty, State Prison one year. Sarah Egan, for entering a house and stealing, State Prison one year. John O'Brien, for assault and battery upon a man in the street, with some weapon, State Prison seven months. James Muldoon, grand larceny; State Prison one year. Nauman Sickle, attempting to pass a $100 bill at Lamb's Exchange; State Prison two years. Wm. Raymond, grand larceny; State Prison eighteen months. Charles Brauer, maintaining a bone boiling nuisance; fined $100. Thos. Price, petit larceny; County Jail four months. George Harris, (colored,) larceny; County Jail five months. Francis Grimes, (colored,) assault upon a colored woman with a hatchet; County Jail twenty days. Martin Lowe, stealing a watch and chain from a soldier; County Jail thirty days. Riley and McMann, assault and battery on a bartender; fined $20 each. Ann Leights, assault and battery on her mistress; County Jail thirty days. The Court then adjourned to the 20th of March.

abstract: Active operations against Vicksburgh commenced on the 18th inst., as we learn by way of Memphis and Chicago. On that day the mortarboats were towed into position, and opened a brisk fire, the effect of which is not yet known.
lead_paragraph: Active operations against Vicksburgh commenced on the 18th inst., as we learn by way of Memphis and Chicago. On that day the mortar-boats were towed into position, and opened a brisk fire, the effect of which is not yet known. Three rebel batteries responded, when the position of our boats was found to be too much exposed, and it was changed. The bombardment of Vicksburgh is known to be but a part of the general plan for its reduction. We shall hear of the rest in good time. The Indianola, which ran the blockade a short time ago, is understood to have on board coal and provisions for three months.

snippet: Speech on Washington's Birthday; Speech on Washington's Birthday; Speech on Washington's Birthday
lead_paragraph: On no previous occasion has the Anniversary of WASHINGTON's Birthday been observed so generally as the one just passed. During three entie days, in various ways, various public associatios and organizations, civic and military, have testified their respect for the memory of the departed patriot, and a very general participation in the festivities of the celebration was evinced by our citizens at large. Yesterday was the time set apart by the authorities of the City for the official ceremonies in honor of the holiday, and, as will be observed, the programme was not only carried out, but well carried out, in a manner creditable to New-York and worthy of the great name it was intended to honor.

abstract: Notwithstanding our little townsman Mr. CHAS. S. STRATTON, or, as we are wont to call him, Gen. Tom Thumb, issued twenty-five hundred invitations to the Bridal Reception held at his mother's house on Thursday last, the desire to see him and his...
lead_paragraph: Notwithstanding our little townsman Mr. CHAS. S. STRATTON, or, as we are wont to call him, Gen. Tom Thumb, issued twenty-five hundred invitations to the Bridal Reception held at his mother's house on Thursday last, the desire to see him and his tiny bride seems greater than ever. Whenever these thimblesful of humanity appear, they are instantly surrounded by a crowd of old and young. Their every movement is watched, and if they venture out of the house, they are pounced upon by the crowd which is always in waiting. If they ride out, their carriage is pursued by pedestrians and equestrians, who form a train more numerous (as well as more motley) than that of any monarch in the universe. If they come into our city on a "shopping" excursion, the store which they happen to patronize is filled with new customers who cram every corner, mount chairs and counters, and place the windows, show-cases and goods of the unhappy merchant in extreme peril. The little General complains that he is obliged to encounter similar troubles in whatever town or city he and his petite wife chance to visit. If they venture out of their room when in a hotel, they are instantly surrounded by the Brobdignagean multitude, and in several instances they have been nearly suffocated within the living wall which suddenly surrounded them! Their parlor and dining-room are frequently invaded by an army of curiosity mongers, and nothing short of a double lock and a pair of patent bolls has proved sufficiently powerful to preserve the sanctity of their bed-chamber! This infinitesimal man and wife propose to visit Europe soon, but their fame has, of course, already preceded them, and the momentous question arises, what can they do to arrest this terrible result of too much notoriety? We beg leave to suggest that the General should revise and reverse his decision that his wife shall not be exhibited. We understand that the little lady herself is not adverse to public exhibitions, but on the contrary that she "rather likes it." This being the case, let them hold public levees in our large cities and towns and charge fifty cents or a dollar per ticket of admission. If the General feels that he is already rich enough he will find plenty of worthy charitable objects that will make good use of his money. At all events it is very evident that with all their wealth, Mr. CHARLES S. STRATTON and his beautiful little wife, Mrs. LAVINIA WARREN STRATTON, can find no peace at home or abroad until in some way public curiosity is satisfied. -- Bridgeport Evening Standard.

abstract: The flags were displayed from the City Hall and other public buildings, and the various liberty poles throughout the city, in honor of the occasion. The Seventieth Regiment of Cavalry met at the State Arsenal, in Portland-avenue, in the morning, and marched through the principal streets of the city, preceded by a mounted band. The Twenty-eighth Regiment also turned out, and marched through some of the principal thoroughfares. They attracted considerable attention. At sundown Capt. DEGEZ fired a national salute from Fort Greene, in compliance with a resolution of the Common Council. In the evening the annual distribution of premiems took place at the Brooklyn Institute, in Washington-street. OLIVER HULL, Esq., presided, and made an address appropriate to the occasion -- previous to which C.P. SMITH, Esq., presented the institution with a portrait of ROBERT NICHOLS, Esq., the late acting President. The premiums were then distributed to the most deserving pupils, when the meeting adjourned. The Cadets of Temperance (Mercantile Section) gave an entertainment at the Athenaeum, last evening, in honor of the occasion. There was a large attendance. The exercises consisted of recitations, dialogues, &c. The Navy-yard Band was in attendance.

abstract: -The Secretary of the Navy has transmitted to Congress a report, giving details concerning of the vessels captured by our navy in running the blockade. Three hundred and sixty-seven prizes are reported, thirty-five of which are steamers; but the number is far greater than this, though the Secretary is not at present able to report them. The information is full concerning all the cases in the Courts at New-York, Boston and Philadelphia. The Secretary mentions the evils and dangers arising to the Government from the delay in the disposal of many of these cases; and he might also have mentioned the dissatisfaction in the navy arising from the same cause. We know that, under the circumstances of some of the cases, delay was unavoidable; but we trust that the proper parties will now, for the benefit of all concerned, hasten forward all adjudications in prize cases.

abstract: One of the most brilliant, and the best-appointed, ball of the season, came off last evening at the City Assembly Rooms, in Broadway. It was given by the members of Company B. Twelfth Regiment, NewYork State Militia, known as the "Washington Light Guard," in commemoration of the birthday of that...
lead_paragraph: One of the most brilliant, and the best-appointed, ball of the season, came off last evening at the City Assembly Rooms, in Broadway. It was given by the members of Company B, Twelfth Regiment, New-York State Militia, known as the "Washington Light Guard," in commemoration of the birthday of that great patriot from whom the company takes its name. There were present the members of the regiment, besides a large number of invited guests, including many distinguished military gentlemen, among whom we noticed several members of the veteran Gen. WOOL's Staff. The ladies comprised more than one-half of the assemblage, and added to the elegance of the affair by the magnificence of their attire. The ball-room, which is an extremely commodious one, was brilliantly illuminated, and handsomely decorated with the Stars and Stripes and the colors of the Regiment. The programme comprised twenty-five dances, the music for which was performed by ROBERTSON's Band. The gentlemen who constituted the Committee were untiring in their efforts to render the occasion an agreeable one to all, and as far as we are able to judge, they succeeded admirably. The dancing commenced with a quadrille, at about ten o'clock, and with the exception of the time devoted to supper, lasted until the "wee hours of morning." It was estimated that the number of tickets sold for this ball could not have been less than eight hundred. The following named gentlemen were among the Committee: Messrs. WALLS, BAIRD, DAMERS, HOEY, BENNETT, BRODERICK, SIBLEY, QUINN, GODWIN, and Mr. JOHN R. DILLON, Floor Manager.

abstract: NIBLO'S GARDEN. In the absence of English opera, It is well to be content with the suggestion at it given by Mr. and Miss RICHINGS in their curious musical and dramatic entertainment. The lady is blessed by nature with a fine voice, and practice has...
lead_paragraph: NIBLO's GARDEN. -- In the absence of English opera, it is well to be content with the suggestion at it given by Mr. and Miss RICHINGS in their curious musical and dramatic entertainment. The lady is blessed by nature with a fine voice, and practice has taught her how to use it in the best way for pleasing the public; the gentleman is experienced in stage affairs, and is, we presume, responsible for the vehicle of his daughter's talent. In the case of "Satanella," he has seized upon a popular work by a pleasing composer, and retaining the most salient of the melodies, has reconstructed the plot to suit it for dialogue, pantomime and ballet. The task is not an easy one, nor has it been discharged with facility. A large amount of after-thought with have to be exercised before the piece presented last night can claim any merit on the score of construction, and extensive excision must be practiced before it can be acceptable, even as regards length. The interest of the performance centred almost exclusively upon Miss RICHING, who sang several morceaux with good effect, and was encored in "The Glorious Vintage of Champagne." Aided by a chorus, (strong in the male department,) and an increased orchestra, under Mr. HARVEY B. DODWORTH, these musical suggestions of the parent work were always acceptable. The scenery and dresses were good, the latter especially so; but the working of the machinery was intolerably bad, and by delaying the performance until near midnight seriously jeopardized its success. A defect of this kind will, of course, be immediately remedied. At an establishment so admirably and lavishly conducted as Niblo's, it should never be noticeable. There is an excellent corps de ballet, and several fine dancers have been expressly engaged to give importance to this department, so that when the work has been repuced to proper limits, it will present many claims to public consideration. Its success, last evening, was not of a very hearty character.

abstract: A train of fifteen wagons, loaded with nay and drawn by about eighty horses, was going from New Creek to Moorefield. When within about six miles of Romney the train was surprised by a squad of rebel cavalry. The train was accompanied by a squad of fifty men, who were completely surprised and captured. The rebels burned the wagons and contents and succeeded in getting away with the horses and prisoners. -- Wheeling Intelligencer.

abstract: Unemployed Generals should be Employed
snippet: Unemployed Generals should be Employed
lead_paragraph: We hope the Government will lose no time in complying with the requests understood to have been made by Gens. FREMONT and MCCLELLAN for active employment. Both have been out of service long enough. Both have military ability of a certain kind, without doubt, and the country certainly needs all the ability of this sort which it can command. The military capacity of both is unquestionably very much exaggerated by their special political admirers, but this affords no excuse for leaving them idle. There is a class of politicians who believe that if Gen. MCCLELLAN were at the head of the army, the war would somehow or other come to an end: -- and another portion of the public believe that Gen. FREMONT would also end it, if he were only in command. Upon what these respective opinions rest it would not be easy to say. Nothing that either of these distinguished Generals has actually done, gives, so far as we can see, any warrant for such a judgment. Nevertheless, both of them have ability, and the Government is in duty bound to give the country the benefit of it. It can certainly assign to each some command which will furnish full scope for his peculiar capacity. It need not send them where their presence will be especially distasteful, or where the special faculty of each will not be required. Gen. MCCLELLAN would not be particularly useful in any Department where dash and vigorous fighting were needed, nor would Gen. FREMONT be able to render valuable service in any quarter especially sensitive on the question of Slavery. But the Government can certainly find some suitable position in which each may make himself useful. There is no good reason for leaving them in absolute idleness, at so heavy an expense to the country, while new Generals, without knowledge or experience of military affairs, are appointed by the hundred.

abstract: The association of Employer-Printers gave their first annual celebration at the St. Nicholas Hotel last evening. JOHN F. TROW, Esq., president, occupied the chair, supported on the right by Rev. Dr. Cox, and on the left by Prof. OWENS, of Yale College.

TROW, Esq., president, occupied the chair, supported on the right by Rev. Dr. COX, and on the left by Prof. OWENS, of Yale College. Among the other invited guests present were GEORGE BRUCE, (the elder) type-founder: Mr. MCKELLAM, of Philadelphia; BENSON J. LOSSING, A.K.P. WELCH, of the University Press, (Cambridge, Mass.:) Mr. HOUGHTON, of the Riverside (Mass.) Press, and Mr. HENRY O'REILLY, of New-York. The tables were appropriately decorated with statues of FRANKLIN and GUTTENBERG, monument to WASHINGTON, La Belle Hollandaise, Nougat Pyramids, and a petit representation of Amour and Hymen.

abstract: Hostility to the War of the Northern Disunionists
snippet: Hostility to the War of the Northern Disunionists
lead_paragraph: The Northern Disunionists who are now laboring to demoralize the army, paralyze the Administration, and bring the war to a conclusion by some means or other, be they fair or be they foul, are very indignant over the hard names which their opponents apply to them, and over the doubts thrown upon their honesty and patriotism. They insist also upon being treated as ordinary political adversaries, whose opinions happen to differ from those of the rest of the community upon a mere question of expediency. They demand, in short, all the rights, privileges, and immunities of an ordinary political party, which has, in common with the rest of us, the good of the nation in view, but does not agree with us as to the best means of attaining it.

abstract: Sentiment in England on the American War
snippet: Sentiment in England on the American War
lead_paragraph: -- When the Senate passed a bill, a few days ago, authorizing the issue of letters-of-marque and reprisal, it was opposed by a number of Senators on the ground that the rebels had no commerce on which our privateers could prey, and that the measure would only be significant as a menace to French and English commerce, in case foreign intervention in the American war was attempted. The friends of the bill did not hesitate to accept and justify this alternative construction of the act, if any European Government were minded to so understand it. Why should not France and England count the cost of hostilities with the United States, while considering the grave diplomatic questions that the war is giving rise to? And why should not the issue of letters-of-marque and reprisal be classed among the risks they must run, seeing how much the rebel endeavors in this line against American commerce have been fostered in foreign harbors and shipyards?

abstract: The proceedings of the Senate on Monday night did not terminate until 12 o'clock, at which time Mr. TRUMBULL'S substitute for the bill relating to arbitrary arrests was passed 24 to 13. The operation of the act is limited to the 1st of March, 1864.
lead_paragraph: The proceedings of the Senate on Monday night did not terminate until 12 3/4 o'clock, at which time Mr. TRUMBULL's substitute for the bill relating to arbitrary arrests was passed -- 24 to 13. The operation of the act is limited to the 1st of March, 1864. In the Senate yesterday, a number of bills relating to the District of Columbia were reported. The Military Committee made an adverse report on the bill relating to hospitals, and an ambulance corps -- regarding it as impracticable. A bill for the removal of the Sioux Indians from Minnesota was passed. A bill to carry into effect the treaty with Peru was reported from the Committee on Foreign Affairs. A Committee of Conference was appointed on the Naval Appropriation bill. The bill to amend the Pacific Railroad act was debated, and a number of amendments were acted upon, but the bill was not finally disposed of. A bill, authorizing the President in certain cases to take possession of steamboats and other vessels, was referred to the Military Committee. The Senate then adjourned.

abstract: The Whitney iron-clad battery Keokuk got steam up at an early hour yesterday morning for the purpose of making a trail trip down the Bay, touching on the way at the Navy-yard. Admiral GREGORY and other officers, and Mr. WHITNEY, besides several ladies,
lead_paragraph: The Whitney iron-clad battery Keokuk got steam up at an early hour yesterday morning for the purpose of making a trail trip down the Bay, touching on the way at the Navy-yard. Admiral GREGORY and other officers, and Mr. WHITNEY, besides several ladies, were on board about 9 1/2 o'clock, at which time crowds of people began assembling on the adjoining wharves to see the first movements of the strangest looking vessel afloat. The interest attaching to her initiatory evolutions was heightened by the ominous hints as to "topheavinese" which had circulated for some days among persons of a semi-nautical turn. So much iron over water-mark, and so little ship work below it, did, indeed, seem liable to oscillation of a disagreeable character.

abstract: If the consolidation scheme of the Lake Shore roads is carried out on the basis laid down in your article of this morning, it will be a gross outrage upon a portion of the Buffalo and State Line stockholders. It is possible that Mr. DEAN RICHMOND, holdings the
lead_paragraph: If the consolidation scheme of the Lake Shore roads is carried out on the basis laid down in your article of this morning, it will be a gross outrage upon a portion of the Buffalo and State Line stockholders. It is possible that Mr. DEAN RICHMOND, holdings the New-York Central proxy, may, by combination with a majority of his Board, succeed in perpetrating this wrong; but with your permission, he shall not do it without the full merits of the transaction being made known to the other stockholders and the public. It is by no means the first time that the minority owners of this valuable property have had their rights trampled upon, nor is it the first time they have complained. But what can widows, orphans, soldiers in the field, and such like people, do against an unscrupulous. and utterly selfish management, headed by DEAN RICHMOND? They may protest, as they have done over and over again, but it is all in vain. Worse than a deaf ear is turned to their complaints; the complainers are turned off with scoffs and insult.

abstract: "Sirrah, what humor is the Prince of?" Well, he is in a war humor now, most consumedly. We want no better war speech than his at the Corporation Banquet. It was as different from his talk before the election as ...
lead_paragraph: "Sirrah, what humor is the Prince of?" Well, he is in a war humor now, most consumedly. We want no better war speech than his at the Corporation Banquet. It was as different from his talk before the election as gunpowder from peach-down. Instead of dulcet pleas to join him in wooing back the "wayward sisters," we have the most emphatic protestations that no honorable and lasting peace can be had except by the most determined war. "This peace," he asseverates, "you will secure by conquest only, and, in my deliberate judgment, never in any other way." He still thinks ill of the Proclamation, and of the suspension of the habeas corpus; but these he now proclaims to be nothing, before the supreme necessity of fighting this war staunchly and thoroughly through. He affirms it to be every man's bounden duty to come out openly and consistently on the one side or the other -- to join heart and hand in putting down the rebellion, or to go over to the rebels; and he makes bold to prophesy that if the North will loyally and unitedly come up to the work "the rebellion will be prostrated in six months from to-night."

abstract: Evening Post on the New-York TIMES and Unemployed Generals
snippet: Evening Post on the New-York TIMES and Unemployed Generals
lead_paragraph: The Evening Post speaks of our urging that Gens. FREMONT and MCCLELLAN should be put to service, as a "dangerous suggestion;" and it scarcely stops short of imputing to us connection with some "conspiracy" which it is designed to promote. With what we cannot help styling very great impertinence, it affects to detect in our suggestion, the sentiment of a "particular member of the Cabinet," whom it proceeds to berate accordingly for an offence of which he is quite as innocent, to say the least, as the editor of the Post himself. "The TIMES," says the Post, "owes it to itself, then, a well as to others who may be innocently implicated and injured by its speech, to declare explicitly the object of its singular military suggestions, so entirely in opposition to its more recent course, so dangerous in themselves, and so likely to revive dissensions in the loyal community, now happily laid to rest."

abstract: The Sufferings of Unionists in
snippet: The Sufferings of Unionists in
lead_paragraph: -- There is no surcease to the sufferings of the Unionists of Texas. Since the beginning of the war they have been subjected to ceaseless martyrdom for their principles; and from no other part of the South have we had such well-authenticated tales of horror. They have not been stories concocted at a distance, or even by the suffering party; but the most fearful accounts have been simply the narrations given by the newspapers published in the locality in which the circumstances occurred. We received yesterday, by way of Monterey, Mexico, two Texas newspapers of not very late date -- one from San Antonio,and the other from Houston; and both of them contain tales which make the blood run cold. The San Antonio Herald coolly says that the number of Unionists in Western and Northern Texas was "small at first, and they are becoming every day less; for in the mountains near Fort Clark, and along the Rio Grande, their bones are bleaching in the sun, and in the counties of Wise and Denton their bodies are suspended by scores from black-jacks. They were warned in time to leave the country; and, choosing to remain, and rely for protection upon the enemy with whom their Government is at war, they must expect to take the consequences of their choice." To the tragical picture here given, naught of horror could be added by anything we might say.

The news is contained in the Rich  mend Examiner of the 21st, telegraphed from
lead_paragraph: The ram Queen of the West, which has won so much glory for herself by running the Vicksburgh blockade, and by other notable exploits, has been captured by the rebels up the Red River, whither she had gone in search of rebel steamers and fortifications. The news is contained in the Rich mend Examiner of the 21st, telegraphed from Port Hudson. The capture of the rebel transport Eva by the Queen of the West has already been announced. It appears that the pilot of the Eva was taken on board the Queen, and compelled, under guard, to pilot her up the river. He succeeded in deceiving the Commander of the Queen as to positions of the rebel batteries, and when she had reached Gordon's Landing, she was fired into and disabled. She drifted to the opposite side of the river, when all but thirteen of her officers and crew succeeded in escaping to the transport De Soto. The Queen and all her armament, supplies, &c., remained in the hands of the rebels. According to the rebel report, a rebel steamer subsequently pursued and recaptured the Eva, which had one of her wheels disabled, and the De Soto was burnt to prevent her capture. It is also stated that the National gunboat Indianola had gone up the Red River to attempt the recapture of the Queen. We shall probably soon get our own version of this whole affair.

lead_paragraph: -- A child named CATHARINE HENRY, aged about three years, whose parents reside at No.26 1/2 Atlantic-street, fell into a large boiler of hot water which had just been lifted from the stove, and was so dreadfully scalded that she died in a few hours thereafter. The child was playing about the boiler, and tumbled in head foremost. An inquest was held by Coroner HEGEMAN, and a verdict in accordance with the facts was rendered....Mr. HENRY STYLES was thrown from a sleigh, in Bedford-avenue, yestertday afternoon, and sustained a fracture of the leg. He was conveyed to his home in Putnam-avenue by Officer JELLY, of the Ninth Precinct Police.

abstract: Our correspondent at  Great Salt Lake City sends us a brief but vivid account of a considerable battle in Utah on the 29th ultimo. It was between a body of California volunteers and two or three hundred Indians.
lead_paragraph: -- Our correspondent at Great Salt Lake City sends us a brief but vivid account of a considerable battle in Utah on the 29th ultimo. It was between a body of California volunteers and two or three hundred Indians, and took place some distance north of the extreme northern settlements in Cache Valley. It seems to have been not merely a victory over the red men, not only a rout of them, but their extermination. Only about a dozen of the warriors are supposed to have escaped. Our own men, too, suffered pretty severely, as the list of killed and wounded will show. The Indians fought desperately, repulsing first a cavalry charge, then a foot charge, and our troops finally succeeded only by plunging determinedly into the brush and executing a general slaughter.

abstract: Free Speech in the South
snippet: Free Speech in the South
lead_paragraph: -- Earl RUSSELL, in his remarks during the debate on the Queen's speech, said that in certain contingencies he should be happy to see the Union restored; but the subjugation of the South by the North would bring with it endless calamities -- calamities to the negro race as well as to the white race, calamities to the cause of liberty and danger to the national prosperity. Among other things, he said it "must put an end to a free Press, and destroy the right of free discussion in the South." The noble Earl could not have shown a more complete ignorance of the past history of the South than be does in this sentence. There never have been such things there as a free Press and the right of free discussion. On almost every subject of public interest the Press of the South has been under the most rigid surveillance, not only by the Slaveholding class, but by the State authorities. On the question of Slavery, on the rights of the poor whites, on popular progress, on the reform of abuses, and on many cognate and collateral questions, the Press of South Carolina, for example, has for a half century had no more liberty of discussion than the Press of Paris now has regarding the prerogatives of the Emperor. The surveillance extended not merely to discussions on Slavery, but to everything bearing upon it, and everything seemed to bear upon it. There were three great regulators of the Press in the South; the revolver, the mob, and the local laws; and there always have been proofs enough how efficiently these agencies worked.

abstract: Evidences of Union Feeling in
snippet: Evidences of Union Feeling in
lead_paragraph: There are, no doubt, individuals scattered over various portions of Western and Northern Texas, who have long indulged the hope that the Yankees were just upon the point of invading the State, dispersing the rebels, and taking the poor, down-trodden Unionists under their protection. This unhappy class of our citizens may be distinguished by their lugubrious countenances, never relieved by a smile, except when news arrives of some disaster to the Confederate cause. Upon such occasions their pleasure is so intense that it is impossible to conceal it. The most extravagant reports of Federal victories are received by them as indisputable facts, while Confederate successes require to be a dozen times confirmed before they are considered worthy of the least attention. The greatest delusion under which such persons labor, is the belief that they are deceiving the community, and that their real sentiments are not known. Never was there a greater mistake. They are known and will be remembered. Their numbers were small at first, and they are becoming every day less. In the mountains near Fort Clark, and along the Rio Grande, their bones are bleaching in the sun, and in the Counties of Wise and Denton, their bodies are suspended by scores from black jacks. They were warned in time to leave the country; and, choosing to remain, and rely for protection upon the enemy with whom their Government is at war, they must expect to take the consequences of their choice. No Government, in time of war, will tolerate treason; and no man who is a traitor at heart should expect favors from the people of a Government with which he has no sympathy, and in the overthrow of which he would rejoice.

abstract: Mr. T. ADDISON RICHARDS paintings were sold at auction last evening at the Der by Gallery. There was a full attendance of buyers, and the bidding was spirited, the pictures generally bringing fair prices. The one which reached the largest figure was a landscape, entitled "The Keowee, Blue Ridge, N.C.," which was sold to Mr. HOLLY for $140. A picture of nearly the same size, called "Live Oak, Florida," was knocked down to Mr. BARLOW for $105. A group of twenty-one carefully-finished views in the Central Park, brought $102 50, and was bought by Mr. HUNT. The fruit and flower pieces brought generally their full value, and some much more. Some "Oranges" brought the ridiculously large sum of $25. Some "Raspberries" sold for $50. On the other hand, some of the landscapes were sacrificed. A charming picture, called "Showery Weather on the Delaware" -- one of the very best pieces in the collection -- was started at the ridiculously low figure of $5, and was sold to Mr. ADAMS for only $18. The most of the pictures were quite small, averaging about 10 by 12 inches. The largest ("Franconia Notch, N.H.," which sold for $100,) was about 28 by 36.

abstract: GERMAN OPERA. Mr. CARL ANSCHUTZ'S season at the German OPera reaches its one hundreth night to-night a duration which, we believe, is unparalleled in the musical history of New-York. The  An immense Union meeting was held here last night at the Opera House and Melodeon Hall. Both places were filled to overflowing.
lead_paragraph: GERMAN OPERA. -- Mr. CARL ANSCHUTZ's season at the German Opera reaches its one hundreth night to-night -- a duration which, we believe, is unparalleled in the musical history of New-York. The series of successes which has led to this result is fresh in the memory of the public. It has been obtained by unswerving fidelity to the true interests of art; by unceasing industry, and by a just perception of what the public required. With leading artists, who were conscientious; with an orchestra that was excellent, and a chorus that has never been surpassed in this City, Mr. ANSCHUTZ has succeeded in producing an ensemble of singular power and brilliancy. Operas that were hackneyed, seemed to acquire freshness under his direction; and works that were strange and distant to the American public, were reached with a graceful and winning hand by these means, and made at once familiar. In this way Mr. ANSCHUTZ has won his hundred nights, and we are glad to hear not unprofitably to himself. To-night, when the centenary event is celebrated by the performance of BEETHOVEN's "Fidelio," there will, we hope, be a hearty recognition of the impressario's services -- especially as it is the last regular performance of the season, and a fitting opportunity for enthusiasm and liberality.

abstract: The Military Value of
snippet: The Military Value of
lead_paragraph: The only value that Vicksburgh possesses for the rebels is that of a blockade point on the Mississippi. So long as the batteries of Vicksburgh command the river in front, and prevent the passage of boats above or below, the armies of the Northwest and Southwest are sundered, and military operations in the Department of the Gulf are conducted at immense disadvantage. The armies in Louisiana have to be fed from the Atlantic seaboard, and weeks of precious time are lost in returning reports and receiving orders. The true base of operations against the rebellion in the States of the Southwest was to be found in the Northwest. Columbus, Island Ten, Fort Pillow and Memphis, hindered the advance from that direction. But as each of these places fell, the demoralizing effect on the rebels was prodigious. It deprived them of the use of the channel by which they collected their army supplies; and as soon as they lost control of this channel they fell back at once as far as possible from the river's bank, to find subsistence in the more populous interior. The country bordering on the Mississippi, for twenty to fifty miles inland, and as far down almost as Vicksburgh, is wholly free from the presence of rebels in force. A predatory band of guerrillas, insignificant in numbers, and too mobile for easy capture, is the only enemy the upper portion of the Mississippi Valley is now infested by.

lead_paragraph: -- The loss of the Queen of the West is as much a subject of regret as was the loss of the Monitor. The Monitor, however, is at the bottom of the sea, but the chances are that the gay and gallant Queen will soon again be in our hands. The Indianola is said to have gone down to look after her, and we should not be surprised if her captivity to the rebels was short.

abstract: Yesterday, Dr. C. MCDOUGALL, the Medical Director of the Department of the East, accompanied by Mr. MERWIN, Chaplain of the Ladies' Home Hospital, and one or two other gentlemen, proceeded to St. Joseph's Hospital, at the upper end of Central Park, for the purpose of making an inspection. The party arrived at the Hospital at 12 M., and were kindly received by Dr. T.W.S. GEULEY, the Surgeon in charge. A careful inspection of the premises was instituted, which resulted (favorably for the manager and attendants. It will be recollected that this building was formerly used as a convent -- known as the St. Vincent Convent. Last October it was leased by the Government, to be used as a hospital, and near the close of that month a large number of patients were admitted. The building was enlarged, and all the modern improvements introduced. Upon the basement floor are the store-room, subsistence-room and wash-room. The upper floor is used for offices, ward-rooms and a dining-room. The hospital contains thirteen wards, capable of accommodating 250 patients, although at the present time they are occupied by only about 100. There is a nurse to every ten patients, besides twelve Sisters of Charity, who attend to the culinary department and the policing of the interior of the hospital. The neat appearance of the rooms, and the order in which everything is kept, were especially noticed. In close proximity to the building is a large tent, for the use of the guard. Dr. GAULEY has recently taken charge of the hospital, having been attached for a long time to the Army of the Potomac.

lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the bill authorizing the President to confer brevet rank was called up and passed. A bill to authorize the Covington and Cincinnati Bridge Company to bridge the Ohio, was referred to the Post-office Committee. The bill to promote the health, comfort and efficiency of the army was passed. The bill amendatory of the Pacific Railroad act was passed. The Indian Appropriation bill was then considered, a large number of amendments were acted upon, and the bill was passed. After an Executive Session, the Senate adjourned.

abstract: The most fearful storm the Army of the Potomac has ever experienced began on Saturday evening, and continued all day yesterday. The sun shone so brightly and the air was so balmy on Saturday morning, that we all supposed the unfavorably weather of the past six weeks ended. About 2 o'clock in the afternoon, however, the weather commenced growing colder, and by midnight the wind had blown up a furious snow-storm.

abstract: necessity for discipline
snippet: necessity for discipline
lead_paragraph: We cannot help indulging in the hope that the frequency with which officers guilty of the grossest breaches of military discipline escape without any heavier punishment than "dismissal from the service," is due rather to the desire of the authorities to get rid of worthless men, than to any notion on their part that discipline can be maintained by the infliction of such a penalty as this. We know very well that for offences purely military, it would, at the beginning of the war, have been neither just nor expedient to treat volunteers with the rigor which is usual and necessary in all regular armies. Men have to learn to estimate the importance of discipline before they can be held very rigidly accountable for breaches of it. But most of our vollunteers have by this time lost all claim to leniency and indulgence, founded on their rawness. They have been long enough in the field to be able to measure things by a military standard, and to feel the importance of having everything which occurs in camp or in action measured by it. But whether they have or not, the interest of the service, and, consequently, of the nation, require that some sharper and quicker agent than Time should be employed in teaching them their duty.

abstract: We publish elsewhere a very sharp and petulant note from CASSIUS M. CLAY, MajorGeneral in the army, and recently recommissioned to be Minister to Russia. He professes to find occasion for writing it in what he styles our "insinuation" that he "could serve the Government consistently with his private sentiments only in a foreign mission."
lead_paragraph: We publish elsewhere a very sharp and petulant note from CASSIUS M. CLAY, Major-General in the army, and recently recommissioned to be Minister to Russia. He professes to find occasion for writing it in what he styles our "insinuation" that he "could serve the Government consistently with his private sentiments only in a foreign mission." We have neither said nor insinuated anything of the kind. We simply expressed the hope that he had found a place at last where he could serve the Government consistently with his private sentiments. His note, however, satisfies us that we might have said what he imputes to us without doing him the slightest injustice. He acknowledges that he did reuse to serve the Government at home, unless President LINCOLN would adopt his policy concerning slaves; -- and not content with having secured that point, he still refuses to enter the service -- not on account of his own sentiments -- but because Gen. HALLECK's don't suit him. After such a confession, it seems to us quite clear that if he can serve the Government to advantage anywhere, it must be abroad.

abstract: Lecture on New-Orleans as It Was and Is
snippet: Lecture on New-Orleans as It Was and Is
lead_paragraph: Rev. HOWARD OSGOOD delivered, at the church corner of Bedford and Christopher streets, last evening, a lecture on "New-Orleans as It Was, and as It Is," commencing with a glowing description of the harbor of New-York, the Passes of the Mississippi and Pilot Town, Forts St. Philip and Jackson, and the historic plains of Chalmette, the speaker came to the City of New-Orleans, whose geographical position, topographical peculiarities, commercial importance, history and variety of population were duly noted. He remarked upon the fate of Dr. PALMER, of New-Orleans, who prophecied that God had meant to save, preserve, and extend Slavery in the South, and who is now in the army of Secessia, and whose church -- capable of containing three thousand persons -- is almost deserted.

abstract: Business is remarkably brisk at the headquarters of Gen. ULLMANN, No. 200 Broadway. The promotions made, in compliance with the special order directing certain officers and privates to report to him, are all based on the performance of actions combining coolness, gallantry and patriotism in a high degree. Others (not included in the special order) receive promotions in consequence of acts of heroism, which have not become generally known, but which are of a character rendering such promotion a fit and proper reward. The conferring of these higher grades is not confined to the officers or men from any particular State, but from any and all sections of the Union. In many cases (even of privates promoted) recommendations for that honor are sent by Major and Brigadier-Generals and their Staffs, Colonels, Majors, Adjutants, &c. Gen. ULLMANN hopes to close his business here within a week's time, but from present indications he will not be able to do so.

abstract: The difficulty
lead_paragraph: -- The difficulty between the British and Brazilian Governments, narrated in our letter from Rio Janeiro, published in the TIMES of yesterday, gives rise to a good deal of sharp discussion in London. The conduct of the British Minister at Rio is condemned very generally as harsh and irritating, and the Opposition papers denounce the Foreign Secretary as having disgraced the country by treating a weak Power with a haughty insolence which it would never think of assuming toward a strong one. The British claim seems clearly unjust, and the peremptory manner in which it was enforced was well calculated to offend the sensibilities of the Government and people of Brazil.

abstract: The New-York Opthalmic School and Hospital held its Eleventh Anniversary on the 24th inst., in the Medical College in Fourteenth-street, before a large and highly intelligent audience. The names of the graduating class were read by Dr. MARK STEPHENSON, lecturer on Anatomy, Pathology and Treatment of Diseases of the Eye; and the diplomas were presented by SOLOMON JENNER, A.M., President of the institution, as follows: A.E. Jenner, M.D., Ohio; J.M. Waddle, Yates County, New-York; J.P. Schenck, Jr., Dutchess County, New-York; W.J. Orton, Broome County, New-York; De Witt Webb, Dutchess County, New-York; J.W. McCann, M.D., Louisville, Ky.; Robert King, Geneva, N.Y.; H.G. Olmsted, M.D., New-York City; Jas. Hutchison, St. John, N.B.; Chas. P. Sanderson, M.D., Ohio; R.J. Mordon, M.D., Canada West; J.H. Chittenden, Binghamton, N.Y.; Thos. Thompson, Delaware County, New-York; J.H. Mills, Orange County, New-York; G.A. Hayanaga, M.D., Canada West J.H. Hunter, M.D., Concord, N.H.; M.C. Rowland, M.D., Washington County, New-York. The graduates were then addressed in a very appropriate manner by Dr. MARCUS P. STEPHENSON, one of the attending Surgeons, under whose immediate instruction they had been during the past Winter. The valedictory address was delivered by ALEXANDER E. JENNER, M.D., one of the graduating class, and the exercises of the evening closed with an address by J.F. GARRISH, M.D.

lead_paragraph: SOCIAL CHURCH GATHERING. -- Tuesday evening there was a large congregation at the John-street M.E. Church -- Rev. Dr. PORTER in the Chair. Very interesting speeches were delivered by the Chairman and by Messrs. FAIR, LOUDER, GILLETTE and others. There is a debt of $13,000 upon the church, and the annual current expenses are about $3,000. The Trustees having recently been at some extra expenses, this meeting was got up for the purpose of defraying the same. It proved a perfect success. While the singing and other exercises were going on in the church, tables were set and refreshments served in the basement. The meeting was a very social one.

abstract: This ordinance, passed by the Common Council, has been approved by the Mayor. It appropriates $1,000,000, to be raised on seven per cent. bonds, and is to be expended by a Commission, to consist of the Mayor and Comptroller and five members of each branch of the Common Council, to be chosen by ballot by the respective Boards, within five days. The balloting probably will take place at the meeting of the two Boards to-day. The money is to be expended in any manner the Commission may deem best to protect the harbor and defend the City. The clerkship, likely, will be offered to DAVID T. VALENTINE, Esq., the venerable Clerk of the Common Council.

abstract: On Tuesday the specifications and plans for the last batch of iron-clad vessels were withdrawn from inspection by Admiral GREGORY, in pursuance of an advertised notification of the Navy Department; several contractors have examined them, and some are now in Washington looking for orders to commence building. No one can attain a contract unless he is himself engaged in the construction of vessels. The new ships have one turret, (which will carry two 11 or 15-inch guns,) but will not draw so much water as the last nine Monitors. There are a few peculiarities of their construction which it would not be advisable to print at present.

lead_paragraph: Delaware is a small State, has little interest in slave property, the true cause of the war, and has felt next to none of war's ravages. Missouri is a great State, had at the beginning of the war at least Forty Millions of dollars worth of slave property, as the price of such property went, and has experienced more of the horrors and desolations of the war than any State in the Union, not even excepting Virginia. It would occur to any one that if either Missouri or Delaware understood the character of the conflict and had a profound interest in its early conclusion, and knew how best it could be concluded, that State would be Missouri.

lead_paragraph: The steamship Jura arrived at Portland yesterday, with advices from Europe five days later than were received by the Canada at Boston. She left Liverpool on the 12th, and Londonderry on the 13th inst. She also brings a summary of the news by the City of Washington, now due at this port, from Liverpool on the 11th. The ship George Griswoold had arrived at Liverpool, with food for the Lancashire operatives. Mr. MASON, the rebel Commissioner, was at the banquet of the Lord Mayor of London on the 12th, and made a speech, in which he predicted speedy friendly relations between the British and rebel Governments. The London Times, however, repudiates his predictions, and intimates that he is much too fast -- that the proceedings mean nothing. Parliament had done nothing of importance. A number of emancipation meetings had been held in England. At one held at Everton the Liverpool friends of the Secessionists mustered in force; but resolutions sympathizing with the North were passed by a vote of two to one. Collisions continued frequent in Poland -- said in most cases to result in favor of the Russians. The latter, however, had been deleated at Balmow. The rising of the Poles is now thought to be a national affair, headed, the London Times says, by the Catholic priests. The question of the occupancy of the Greek throne is still undecided. The sales of cotton at Liverpool for the week were only 25,000 bales, the market closing at a decline of 1/2d. The market for breadstuffs was dull, and flour easier. The provision market was flat. Consols closed on Saturday at 92@92 3/4 for money.
