abstract: A UNION LEAGUE IN NEW-JERSEY The loyal citizens of Newark are taking measures for the formation of a Union League, to comprise all loyal men without distinction of party. The object is to organize and compact the loyal sentiment of the city, and the development and dissemination of sound patriotic sentiments among the people.
lead_paragraph: A UNION LEAGUE IN NEW-JERSEY. -- The loyal citizens of Newark are taking measures for the formation of a Union League, to comprise all loyal men without distinction of party. The object is to organize and compact the loyal sentiment of the city, and the development and dissemination of sound patriotic sentiments among the people. It is contemplated to extend the organization into every part of the State so that each township shall have its UNION LEAGUE pledged to the support of the Government against traitors, whether without or within the lines of the loyal States. The project meets with enthusiastic favor, and already commands the hearty cooperation of a large number of the most influential citizens of Newark.

abstract: CHARLES H. GORDON, alias GRANT, was arraigned before Justice PERRY yesterday on charges of burglary, preferred by the following parties: CHAS. CHRISTMAS, Second place, corner of Henry-street; ISRAEL W. LEVISON, No. 254 Henry-street; ABEL DENNISON and Mrs. ADELA VAN BRUNT, No. 256 Henrystreet. The prisoner waived examination on all the charges, and was committed to jail to await the action of the Grand Jury.
lead_paragraph: CHARLES H. GORDON, alias GRANT, was arraigned before Justice PERRY yesterday on charges of burglary, preferred by the following parties: CHAS. CHRISTMAS, Second place, corner of Henry-street; ISRAEL W. LEVISON, No. 254 Henry-street; ABEL DENNISON and Mrs. ADELA VAN BRUNT, No. 256 Henrystreet. The prisoner waived examination on all the charges, and was committed to jail to await the action of the Grand Jury. In answer to the usual questions, he stated that he was 23 years of age, born in the United States, residence in Brooklyn, by profession a civil engineer, and had nothing to say relative to the charges against him. He declined at first to give his name, but on consultation with counsel, appended his signature to the statement as CHARLES H. GRANT.

abstract: Yesterday afternoon the Harbor Police of this City were called upon by Capt. CHAS. G. CROCKER, of the ship Lucy Thompson, to quell a mutiny on board of that vessel. As soon as the Policemen were notified, they boarded the ship, then lying in the North River, opposite Pier No. 1, and took into custody sixteen of the mutineers, (all colored,) and forthwith took them before Justice CONNOLLY at the Tombs. From the evidence there adduced, it appears that the Lucy Thompson was ready for sea, bound for Liverpool. Her crew were all shipped, and the Captain had given orders to weigh anchor, when one of the crew named WM. WILLIAMS made an attempt to leave the vessel. Capt. CROCKER ordered him back. WILLIAMS refused to obey the order, whereupon the Captain directed that he should be put in irons. When the attempt was made to put the irons upon him, fifteen of the crew made a general attack upon the Captain on the quarter-deck, with drawn knives, handspikes, &c. The Captain and his officers, however, succeeded in driving them all forward, and ordered HORATIO WEAVER, another of the crew to be put in irons. The crew then rushed aft again, and this time they were armed with belaying pins and pistols, in addition to knives and handspikes. The Captain and first Mate, John T. Blackstock, tried to keep them back. The latter was armed with a cutlass, but the Captain testifies the mate did not strike any one with it, although he was knocked down with a belaying pin in the hands of one of the mutineers, while another struck him with a handspike.. At this stage of the proceedings, the Captain, drew his revolver and shot one of the crew named JOHN RICHARDSON in the leg. This act had the effect to quell the disturbance in a measure. The Harbor Police were then notified and boarded the ship, and took them into custody. Justice CONNOLLY, upon this statement of the case, committed the whole crew for examination.

abstract: The funeral ceremonies of Miss EMMA E. TAYLOR took place at St. Mark's Church yesterday, at 3 P.M. Dr. JOSEPH H. PRICE, Rector of St. Stephen's Church, officiated. The attendance was very large, and all were deeply sensitive of the solemnity of the occasion. The service was intoned by Dr. PRICE, in a clear and impressive manner, and an appropriate hymn was chanted by the choir. The coffin was borne into the church by the following gentlemen, who acted as pall-bearers: G.H. Smith, Jarvis Weed. E.F. Lasack, F.H. Pinkney, L.D. Debost, S.J. Pollock, E.M. Vought and G.H. Williams. Upon the lid were placed wreaths of delicate white flowers; also clusters of the same material were carefully arranged round the head and face of the corpse. Before separating, those present were permitted to take a farewell look at the remains of the lamented deceased. The body was placed in a vault beneath the church.

abstract: THE NEW-YORK SEMI-WEEKLY TIMES is published THIS MORNING, and may be had at the counter of the publication office in wrappers ready for mailing. In addition to the latest intelligence by telegraph up to the moment of going to press, there will be found in the current number full details of all military movements in the different departments from the pens of our special correspondents. Also, all official orders, reports and documents, and the latest and fullest Washington news. European news, with graphic letters from our correspondents in London and Paris, giving the tone of public feeling abroad, is made a special and permanent feature. In addition to Editorials on all the current topics of the day, the SEMI-WEEKLY TIMES has a page of carefully prepared commercial matter, giving the latest financial news and market reports: items of agricultural and domestic interest, compiled from sources many of which are otherwise inaccessible to the American reader; and marriages and deaths of the week.

abstract: Dispatch to Mr. Raymond, Stating that All Dispatches were Submitted to the President; Mr. Seward's Rejection of the French Proposals to Mediate
snippet: Dispatch to Mr. Raymond, Stating that All Dispatches were Submitted to the President; Mr. Seward's Rejection of the French Proposals to Mediate
lead_paragraph: When the Tribune, a few days ago, in the course of its censure of Mr. SEWARD's rejection of the French proposal for a joint Commission, alleged that the President was not to be held accountable for the language in which that rejection was couched, inasmuch as Mr. SEWARD frequently sent abroad dispatches without submitting them beforehand for the President's approval, we took it for granted that the statement was made in entire good faith, and with no other than laudable public motives. Feeling its full importance, we took pains to investigate its truth by direct inquiry in the only quarter where its truth or its falsehood could be known -- namely, from the President and the Secretary of State themselves: -- and, on their authority and by their permission, we gave the statement an explicit contradiction in the following terms:

abstract: Offer of to the Government
snippet: Offer of to the Government
lead_paragraph: appears this morning in a new and noteworthy light. Mr. E.A. STEVENS, as will be seen by his letter to the Secretary of the Navy, offers to complete the Stevens Battery within nine months, at his own cost, and agrees to make her proof against any ordnance in the world, faster and more manageable than any war vessel, and equal to any in weight of broadside -- to do this at his own risk and cost, provided the Government will then agree to take her at a smaller price than they are now paying for less formidable vessels. Not a cent is to be paid or risked until these conditions are actually fulfilled.

abstract: The congregation of St. Francis Xavier's Catholic Church, West Sixteenth-street, gave a grand promenade concert and festival, for the benefit of the poor of that parish, during the day and evening of yesterday. Notwithstanding the severity of the storm, the affair proved an immense success. The splendid hall of St. Francis Xavier's College (connected with the Church) was used for the festival purposes, and, in the evening especially, was crowded with ladies and gentlemen. Dodworth's Band, sixteen pieces, furnished the music on the occasion. The prominent features of the festival were a prize lottery -- in which there were no blanks -- and a polyrama of the war, for chances in the one and a sight at the other, twenty-five cents extra being charged. The articles going to make up the lottery were prints, needlework, fancy articles, trinkets, &c. The amount realized from the festival was between $1,100 and $1,200, which is to be divided equally between the St. Vincent dc Paul's Society and the Ladies' Benevolent Society attached to the Church, under whose auspices the entire festival was conducted. Numbers of Catholic clergymen and many prominent citizens were present with their families.

abstract: Magazines for March
snippet: Magazines for March
lead_paragraph: -- The publishers and editors of the Atlantic furnish an excellent number for March. Attached to the leading paper, "Christopher North," we find the name of JOSEPH DANA HOWARD. It is kind in the publishers to tell us thus much; but they will further have to explain to us who Mr. HOWARD is, as the blood of all the Howards, now-a-days, courses through a great labyrinth of democratic veins, and we cannot individualize the gentleman. There were no difficulty, however, in identifying the author of the poem, "Choose ye this day whom ye will serve," even were the name of the author not whispered to us. Give OLIVER WENDELL HOLMES a biblical text or some patriotic theme, and the result may be calculated with arithmetical certainty -- a number of truisms dressed up in very pretty verse. JOHN WEISS furnishes chapter 5th of his "Horrors of San Domingo." "A London Suburb" is another of HAWTHORNE's charming sketches of the world beyond the Atlantic, or, at least, of that portion of it comprised by that fast anchored round of beef and sirloin of prejudice -- the Island of Great Britain. J.T. TROWBRIDGE's poem of "The Vagabonds" is clever in its way, though scarcely equal to BURNS' "Jolly Beggars." Mrs. CHILD's story of "Willie Wharton" tells of a boy who was taken from his parents by the Indians very early in life, and subsequently reclaimed with the Indian bride, whom he had acquired, to the pains and penalties of civilization. GAIL HAMILTON -- the pen name will be recognized as that of a lady essayist, one of the most charming in the world, setting America wholly aside -- issues a stirring appeal to her country-women. In reading the trumpet-call, "O, women, stand here in the breach!" we trust that neither matrons nor maidens will be tempted to pluralize the concluding substantive of the sentence. THEODORE TILTON's poem, "The True Church," has an excellent point, which had been better had it been sooner reached. In a notice of Mrs. HOPKINSON's story, "Under the Pear-Tree," commenced in the Atlantic for February, we prepared the readers to expect an excellent story -- they will not be disappointed. "The Pear-Tree" certainly grows in grace. Mr. GRENVILLE WEEKS, Surgeon of the Monitor, contributes a graphic story of the loss of the brave little iron-clad. In Mrs. JULIA WARD HOWE's fifth "Lyric of the Street" -- "The Darkened House" -- one would scarcely recognize the author of several stirring, nervous poems that have appeared in the same magazine over the same signature. AGASSIZ writes, "America the Old World." We do not pretend to criticise the Professor. He goes further down in the bowels of the lanp than any critic less erudite than BACON, or less persevering than moles, can safely follow. "Pericles and President Lincoln" is the title of a paper by HENRY M. ALDEN. It must be confessed that misery has made our republican ruler acquainted with strange bedfellows, and perhaps with ancient ones. In addition to the many capital articles enumerated, the Atlantic has an excellent review of Russell's Diary. Why could not some of the good things of the March number before us have been crowded into the one for February. Almost any one of them would have sparkled there in strong contrast to an almost eaden dullness.

abstract: The Board of Aldermen met yesterday, and referred a resolution in favor of continuing to lay down the present style of Belgian pavement, instead of a new and more expensive style chosen by the Croton Board. The Committee on Ferries reported that Pier No. 43, North River, is held by a party who is considerably in arrears for rent, and that it is used for a ferry and other illegal purposes, and, therefore, submitted a resolution to have the Comptroller and Corporation Counsel recover the back rent, and re-lease the pier. Adopted, and also a resolution from the same Committee, inquiring of the Corporation Counsel what progress has been made in the suit to recover the large amount of rent due from the lessees of the Grand-street and East Brooklyn Ferry. Another resolution, to amend their franchise, and sell it anew, was laid over. The City Appropriation bill for 1863 was reported by the Finance Committee, and laid over, and made the special order for next Monday. An important report of the Committee on Wharves, on the subject of the water rights of the Corporation, is printed entire in the official proceedings. The Board balloted for five of the members to become Harbor Defence Commissioners, under the ordinance approved by the Mayor on Tuesday, and elected Messrs. Henry, Mitchell, Hardy, Boole and Ottiwell, and also requested the Corporation Counsel to memorialize the Legislature to legalize the ordinance. Concurrence was had to revoke the permission given in 1853 to Commodore VANDERBILT to widen Pier No. 1, North River, notwithstanding that some of the members had been served with legal papers enjoining them from voting on the subject. Mr. BOOLE said the serving of papers was a farce, no authority existing by which the Common Council could be enjoined from voting on any subject. The Board declined to concur in the amendments made by the Councilmen to the Family Aid ordinance, desired to make other amendments, but appointed a Conference Committee and took a recess. Afterward, the ordinance came back in its original form, was amended in respect to salaries of visitors, and janitors, and the manner of their appointment, and was then adopted. Adjourned till 1 o'clock P.M., next Monday.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, a statement of the condition of the Savings Banks of the State was received from the Superintendent of the Bank Department. A concurrent resolution was introduced instructing our Representatives in Congress to induce the General Government to make specie payment to the Counties in the State of money due them, and also to pay the money due the families of deceased soldiers. The resolution before prescribed, providing for the payment of volunteers by the State -- the money to be refunded by the General Government, -- was referred to the Judiciary Committee, with instructions to report a bill. No other business of importance was transacted before the recess.

abstract: Congress has passed the law for putting the entire available military force of the United States at the command of the President, for the suppression of the rebellion. The call for 75,000 volunteers, when Sumter fell, astounded the country by its magnitude. So great a call to arms had never before been made in America. But few months passed, however,...
lead_paragraph: Congress has passed the law for putting the entire available military force of the United States at the command of the President, for the suppression of the rebellion. The call for 75,000 volunteers, when Sumter fell, astounded the country by its magnitude. So great a call to arms had never before been made in America. But few months passed, however, before this force appeared altogether insignificant and incapable of coping with the extent and energies of the rebellion. Another levy was authorized, and a half-million men rushed to the field, to battle for the Union. This vast army was in time found inadequate. Another call for 300,000 volunteers went forth, and, in a few days, 300,000 more, to be gathered by conscription, were called for. In all, 1,175,000 soldiers have been formally summoned to the field by the United States Government since the war began, and the greater part of them have gone. Volunteer companies and independent corps have tendered their services and been accepted, outside of the regular calls, sufficient, perhaps, to fill up the number to the above great limit.

abstract: In the Senate, yesterday, the correspondence between President LINCOLN and the workingmen of England was called for. A joint resolution to facilitate representation at the Hamburgh Exhibition was reported from the Committee on Foreign Affairs. A resolution offered by Mr. POWELL, of...
lead_paragraph: In the Senate, yesterday, the correspondence between President LINCOLN and the workingmen of England was called for. A joint resolution to facilitate representation at the Hamburgh Exhibition was reported from the Committee on Foreign Affairs. A resolution offered by Mr. POWELL, of Kentucky, directing an inquiry into the conduct of Col. GILBERT, who recently dispersed a Copperhead Conventinn at Frankfort, Ky., was laid over. The bill to provide Circuit Courts for the Districts of California and Oregon was passed. The Military Committee was instructed to inquire how many Paymasters, Quartermasters and Commissioners are required, and whether the number cannot be limited. The bill to carry into effect the treaty with Peru was passed. The resolution appointing a Committee to investigate the facts concerning the arrest and release of D. A. MAHONEY was called up, but was indefinitely postponed -- 21 to 19. The bill for the survey and sale of certain Indian reservations in California was passed. The bill to reorganize the Corps of Engineers was called up, but after some debate, was recommitted to the Military Committee. The Senate voted to take up the Bankrupt bill, 20 to 16, but the Conscription bill was reported from the House, and the amendments were ordered to be printed, when the Senate went into Executive Session, and afterward adjourned.

abstract: London Newspapers--Our Foreign Slanderers
snippet: London Newspapers--Our Foreign Slanderers
lead_paragraph: There could be no better proof of the extent to which party spirit has outrun its lawful limits, than the delight with which opposition orators and journalists quote and adopt foreign abuse and depreciation of the government and institutions of their country. Foreign criticism, as long as it comes from friendly pens, or lips, is always instructive, and ought always to be welcome. But there is not a line written or a word spoken by the English or French enemies of our administration at this moment, which is not inspired by sincere and hearty detestation, not simply of the policy of our Government, but of its nature. The tirades of the London Times and Saturday Review, and the lectures of Mr. BERESFORD HOPE, against Mr. LINCOLN and his Cabinet, are not inspired, and do not pretend to be inspired by zeal for humanity, or for the honor or welfare of this country or people. They care nothing about either slavery or slaveholders. They are not interested either in the security of the one or the preservation of the other. They are not interested in the restoration of the Union, or in the unity of the American people. They are not interested in the triumph of any principles, either moral or constitutional, to which any sect or party at the North avows its adherence. But they are interested, and they do not conceal it, in our failure, and the triumph of the rebels -- not because it would put an end to the waste of money and waste of blood which attends the war; not because they care a straw either for the negro or for his owner, either for Freedom or Slavery -- but because they hope to see, in our confusion, humiliation and defeat, the overthrow of those political doctrines which we have now, for eighty years, represented in the eyes of the world.

abstract: Proposals to Change to English Steamers; Prompt Dealing with Insubordinate Officers
snippet: Proposals to Change to English Steamers; Prompt Dealing with Insubordinate Officers
lead_paragraph: Major-Gen. HUNTER deserves the thanks of the country for his prompt dealing with the malcontent officers of the corps from North Carolina, which was recently sent to his department. These officers, because, in their opinion, Maj.-Gen. FOSTER ought to lead the forces in South Carolina, systematically disregarded Gen. HUNTER's orders, and studiously embarrassed his plans. Because they found negro soldiers in South Carolina, they openly declared that if the Union had got to be saved by such means, it should not be saved at all, and put themselves actively to the work of stirring up insubordination and mutiny among the white soldiers. Gen. HUNTER, in promptly putting some of these men under arrest and expelling others from his Department, has discharged his part of the duty in the premises. We trust they will be followed up, and that the service will be permanently rid of the officers who have proved so unworthy of it.

abstract: No one who has not visited Washington recently can appreciate the change that has taken place there. The concourse of people on the streets, in the public buildings, and houses devoted to public entertainment, is incredible. Whence do they come? Why are they there? No visible employment occu
lead_paragraph: No one who has not visited Washington recently can appreciate the change that has taken place there. The concourse of people on the streets, in the public buildings, and houses devoted to public entertainment, is incredible. Whence do they come? Why are they there? No visible employment occupies them. No hand seems to feed them. But the great throng remains -- the thousands that leave in the departing trains are more than compensated for by the increased thousands that the arriving trains bring in. Complaints are made that the railroads are inadequate to the accommodation of the travel seeking Washington. Heaven knows what would become of the hapless myriads that fail to reach Washington on this account, if an evil day should bring them double-track railways to the Tiber Creek and the Potomac.

abstract: Coroner WILDEY yesterday impanneled a jury at the Eleventh Precinct Station-house, and proceeded to Investigate the facts and circumstances attending the death of young FOSTER, who died at his residence, No. 251 Stanton-street, (rear,) on Thursday morning. In the TIMES of yesterday we published all the facts which were then known regarding his death.
lead_paragraph: Coroner WILDEY yesterday impanneled a jury at the Eleventh Precinct Station-house, and proceeded to Investigate the facts and circumstances attending the death of young FOSTER, who died at his residence, No. 251 Stanton-street, (rear,) on Thursday morning. In the TIMES of yesterday we published all the facts which were then known regarding his death. The testimony given upon the inquest throws very little light upon the mysterious affair. Dr. BOUTON, of the Coroner's office, made a post-mortem examination of the body. He found two balls -- evidently shot from a revolver or a Derringer pistol -- lodged in the abdomen of deceased; either of which, in the judgment of the Doctor, would have produced death. One ball, it will be remembered, was extracted by the attending physicians, shortly previous to his death.

abstract: Major-Gen. HUNTER deserves the thanks of the country for his prompt dealing with the malcontent officers of the corps from North Carolina, which was recently sent to his department. These officers, because, in their opinion, Maj.-Gen. FOSTER ought...
lead_paragraph: Major-Gen. HUNTER deserves the thanks of the country for his prompt dealing with the malcontent officers of the corps from North Carolina, which was recently sent to his department. These officers, because, in their opinion, Maj.-Gen. FOSTER ought to lead the forces in South Carolina, systematically disregarded Gen. HUNTER's orders, and studiously embarrassed his plans. Because they found negro soldiers in South Carolina, they openly declared that if the Union had got to be saved by such means, it should not be saved at all, and put themselves actively to the work of stirring up insubordination and mutiny among the white soldiers. Gen. HUNTER, in promptly putting some of these men under arrest and expelling others from his Department, has discharged his part of the duty in the premises. We trust they will be followed up, and that the service will be permanently rid of the officers who have proved so unworthy of it.

abstract: The steamship Ariel, from Aspinwall on the 18th inst., arrived at this port yesterday, bringing about $280,000 in treasure. She brings later news from the Isthmus of Panama, and from Central and South America, but it presents no features of special importance. Affairs in the United States of Colombia, appear to have settled down into quietude under the administration of MOSQUERA, who was busily at work putting governmental matters to rights. From Central America the word, is, that a war between Salvador and Guatemala is inevitable. The cause of the difference will be found stated in our special correspondence. The owl-train from New-York ran into the 11 1/4 o'clock P.M. train from Philadelphia at 2 o'clock yesterday morning, at the Princeton, N.J., station, just as the Philadelphia train was turning off on the switch to avoid it. The third car of the Philadelphia train was struck, and shattered to pieces. Nobody was killed, though several persons were injured. The locomotive of the owl-train was thrown into the canal, and two cars broken up. The obstructions on the track have been removed, and the trains are running regularly.

abstract: War between these two States appears to be inevitable. Many charge the bad feeling between Presidents CARRERA and BARRIOS, of Guatemala and Salvador, to the ambitious views of the latter, and to his unquiet disposition. But, as near as I can judge from
lead_paragraph: War between these two States appears to be inevitable. Many charge the bad feeling between Presidents CARRERA and BARRIOS, of Guatemala and Salvador, to the ambitious views of the latter, and to his unquiet disposition. But, as near as I can judge from the discussions that have appeared between the two in the public prints, and from private letters from, and conversations with, intelligent persons, I should say that the faults in the quarrel lie principally with Guatemala. CARRERA and his priests do not like the liberal religious views of BARRIOS, and feel especially angry at his determination to make the clergy swear to obey the civil in preference to the ecclesiastical law. Guatemala has harbored all the self-expatriated priests and other discontents. She seems as little inclined to make war directly as does Salvador; and the latter will not be the first to shed blood. CARRERA, by lending aid in arms and money to BARRIOS' discontented countrymen, hopes to accomplish his purpose, which is purely personal, of overthrowing his enemy by a domestic revolution, but in which it is generally believed he will be disappointed. It is hardly to be expected that, failing in this, the bad feeling engendered between the two will eventuate in any other way than in war. And it is altogether unlikely that the war will be confined to these two parties. Honduras will, undoubtedly, take the side of Salvador, and Nicaragua cannot well be kept out of the quarrel. Costa Rica, although she should be glad to see BARRIOS overthrown, is determined to take no part, but may be forced into it.

abstract: Neutrality--Rebel Navy Building in English Ship-yards
snippet: Neutrality--Rebel Navy Building in English Ship-yards
lead_paragraph: -- We ask attention to an article which we copy elsewhere from the London Daily News, giving some startling facts as to the number and character of vessels now building in English ship-yards for the rebel navy. The statements embodied in that article ought to command the attention of our Government. If they are true, they can scarcely fail to make the British Government directly responsible for the enormous aid thus afforded to the rebellion. The writer specifies a dozen steam vessels, mostly iron-clad, now in process of construction, intended for the rebel service; and he states that over fifty steam vessels, of various descriptions, in different stages of completeness, might be enumerated in this catalogue. He gives also valuable information as to efforts made to raise money for the use of the rebel States, and the degree of success by which they have been attended.

abstract: Although the Signal Corps connected with the army has not as yet been recognized by the War Department as a separate and distinct organization, still there are various urgent reasons favoring the adoption of the system which it is proposed to inaugurate. From the very commencement of the present rebel
lead_paragraph: Although the Signal Corps connected with the army has not as yet been recognized by the War Department as a separate and distinct organization, still there are various urgent reasons favoring the adoption of the system which it is proposed to inaugurate. From the very commencement of the present rebellion, the active cooperation of the Signal Corps with the different divisions of the army has been conspicuous, and that its service has been attended with the most satisfactory results has been proven and acknowledged upon numerous occasions. The operations of the corps have been referred to in a desultory manner from time to time by army correspondents, but the simplicity and facility with which it performs its labors have not been dwelt upon to any great extent. It is presumed that most people are aware of the nature of the duties required from this department of the service. The chief object is to furnish means of rapid communication between different portions or sections of the army, and to transmit the intelligence so received to the General and other headquarters. As it now stands, the corps is composed of officers of the rank of Captain and Lieutenant, under the immediate control of Maj. MYER, of the regular army, and the inventor of the code of signals at present used. Private soldiers are also detailed from their respective regiments to perform the manual labor required. In the event of an action, or one anticipated, it is the usual practice for one officer, attended by two or three assistants, to ride to the front and select an eligible position upon which the movements of the enemy can be observed. The position selected may be within our picket lines, or, as it often occurs, between the lines of the contending forces. If a wide distance intervenes between the outer station and the station at the general headquarters, or the point to which it is designed to transmit messages; or, if the view is intercepted by mountains, forest, or any other other obstacle, one or more stations, as the necessity of the case demands, are formed between the extreme stations. By this means instant advice of the enemy's movements is communicated to the commanding officer, who, acting upon the information received, disposes his troops to the best advantage. Another important benefit is derived from the operations of the signal corps, inasmuch as the firing of artillery may be directed to points most susceptible of damage. Such was eminently the case during the Peninsula campaign and the campaign through Eastern Virginia, where the enemy was successfully repulsed in consequence of his strength and precise locality having been made known to our Generals through the signal corps. The cam pains in other parts of the country also bear witness equally prominent of the efficiency of the corps. It is surprising to observe with what rapidity and accuracy messages are conveyed. When our army was at Harrison's Landing, one hundred and sixty-five messages were sent from the southern bank of the James River to Gen. PORTER's headquarters, on the northern bank, in the space of a few hours. The adaptability of the service to naval purposes is unquestioned, and has been and continues to be fully appreciated.

lead_paragraph: SINGULAR DEATH OF A COACHMAN. -- Coroner NAUMANN yesterday held an inquest upon the body of THOMAS JEFFERSON SHELLY, a man who, for many years past, has been well known, and in some respects a remarkable coachman, diligently plying his vocation in the vicinity of the United States Hotel, in this City. All who have been in the habit of frequently passing this hotel, in Fulton-street, must have noticed a man of huge dimensions, sometimes complacently sitting upon the seat of his coach, at other times good-naturedly chatting with an acquaintance, on the steps of the hotel. It appeared, from the testimony on the inquest, that he was a man of strictly temperate habits, and, until about eight years ago, he was a man of ordinary size. About that time he rapidly grew large and weighty, until he finally reached the remarkable figure of 509 pounds. Within the last few years, so great was his size and weight, that he was employed to exhibit at BARNUM's, and for several months one season he traveled with the Van Amburgh troupe all over this country. He was always good-natured, temperate and industrious in his habits, ate no more than a common man, and until within a short time past, always enjoyed good health. The verdict was that he died from suffocation from excessive fatty substances throughout the system. He was about forty years of age, and a native of Connecticut.

lead_paragraph: Mr. CARL ANSCHUTZ brings his Brooklyn opera season to a close to-day, when, for the first time in the sister city, there will be a grand Operatic Matinee. Entertainments of this kind are sure to flourish where there are plenty of pretty girls. Owing to this cause they are always peculiarly successful in New-York, and we can certainly see no reason why they should not be so in Brooklyn -- a city famous for its blooming damsels and lovely matrons. FLOTOW's charming opera of "Martha," has been selected for the occasion. It will be interpreted by the same artists who rendered it so acceptably last week. The price of admission is fifty cents to all parts of the house, and there are, of course, no reserved seats. If the day is fine we shall expect to see a brilliant sight in Montague-street; the first Matinee and the last appearance of Mr. ANSCHUTZ's troupe are twin events that should surely interest the public. The impressario opens in Philadelphia on Monday next.

abstract: REBELS. -- We ask attention to an article which we copy elsewhere from the London Daily News, giving some startling facts as to the number and character of vessels now building in English ship-yards for the rebel navy. The statements embodied in that article ought to command the attention of our Government. If they are true, they can scarcely fail to make the British Government directly responsible for the enormous aid thus afforded to the rebellion. The writer specifies a dozen steam vessels, mostly iron-clad, now in process of construction, intended for the rebel service; and he states that over fifty steam vessels, of various descriptions, in different stages of completeness, might be enumerated in this catalogue. He gives also valuable information as to efforts made to raise money for the use of the rebel States, and the degree of success by which they have been attended.

abstract: No one who has not visited Washington recently can appreciate the change that has taken place there. The concourse of people on the streets, in the public buildings, and houses devoted to public entertainment, is incredible. Whence do they come? Why are they there? No visible employment occu
lead_paragraph: No one who has not visited Washington recently can appreciate the change that has taken place there. The concourse of people on the streets, in the public buildings, and houses devoted to public entertainment, is incredible. Whence do they come? Why are they there? No visible employment occupies them. No hand seems to feed them. But the great throng remains -- the thousands that leave in the departing trains are more than compensated for by the increased thousands that the arriving trains bring in. Complaints are made that the railroads are inadequate to the accommodation of the travel seeking Washington. Heaven knows what would become of the hapless myriads that fail to reach Washington on this account, if an evil day should bring them double-track railways to the Tiber Creek and the Potomac.

abstract: The steamship Ariel, from Aspinwall on the 18th inst., arrived at this port yesterday, bringing about $280,000 in treasure. She brings later news from the Isthmus of Panama, and from Central and South America, but it presents no features of special importance. Affairs in the United States of Colombia, appear to have settled down into quietude under the administration of MOSQUERA, who was busily at work putting governmental matters to rights. From Central America the word is, that a war between Salvador and Guatemala is inevitable. The cause of the difference will be found stated in our special correspondence.

This is less than paid in the corresponding time last year, and in the previous six months less by $279,194.

abstract: Second Lecture on Brazil
snippet: Second Lecture on Brazil
lead_paragraph: The second lecture of Rev. J.C. FLETCHER before the Mercantile Library Association, upon Northern Brazil and the River Amazon, was delivered before a large and intelligent audience at the Cooper Institute on Wednesday evening. He commenced by speaking of the immense area of the Brazilian Empire -- larger by 100,000 square miles than the entire domain of the United States. The physical geography of this entire region was especially adapted to make it one of the greatest, richest and most prosperous nations of the earth, while its climate was more temperate and salubrious than the corresponding latitude of either Africa or Asia. The average height of the land throughout the entire Empire was 700 feet above the level of the sea. Its mountains were tillable to their summits, its rivers were navigable for hundreds and thousands of miles inland, it was free from earthquakes, volcanoes, drouths, simoons and fevers -- in fine it was a land where the wnite man could live and thrive, though in the tropics. But alas! how it had been neglected! No American could go to South America without wishing that his countrymen inhabited the country. There were, however, signs of improvement in Brazil, and a new era was about to dawn upon the Empire. The Brazilians of to-day far surpass any of the Latin races in the Western Hemisphere, and they are fast improving in all that pertains to the welfare and greatness of a nation. The liberal and constitutional Government established by DON PEDRO the First, father of the present Emperor, was gradually being improved and perfected through the beneficent reign of his accomplished son, and a great and brilliant future for the Empire was about beginning. The Old World was nearly twice as large in area as the New, yet there was more available soil in the New World than in the Old, and in no part of it was there more available soil in proportion to the whole area than in Brazil. Mr. FLETCHER here spoke of the importance to Americans of opening a more extensive trade than has hitherto been carried on with Brazil. The English were fully alive to the advantages to be reaped from such a trade, and since the establishment of their line of steamers to Rio Janeiro, they were fast getting the better of the Americans. The speaker next reverted to the river Amazon, taking up the subject from the point were he left off in the previous lecture, and giving an interesting and vivid description of that "King of Waters," interspersed with numerous anecdotes of his personal experience while navigating its bosom. From the point where the river enters the boundaries of Brazil, to its mouth -- a distance of two thousand miles -- the river was from three to seven miles wide, and although the tide set inland upward, of five hundred miles, yet so immense was the flood, and so strong the current, that the water was fresh even down to the mouth of the river. The lecturer spoke at length of the immense resources of the Amazon and other rivers of Brazil, and in fact of the entire Empire. The cotton crop of Brazil, for the last year, had more than doubled, and it ranks in the European market next to our own Sea Island. With reference to Slavery Mr. FLETCHER said he visited numerous plantations in different parts of the Empire during his trip thither last summer, and as well as in former years, and he had yet to see the first man in Brazil who held to the doctrine of Divine right of Slavery. They all, without exception, admitted it to be an evil, and acknowledged it to be their duty to do all in their power to mitigate and eventually to exterminate the curse. Unlike the United States there was no prejudice in Brazil against any man on account of his color -- but qualities of manhood alone were regarded. Under the action of influences now at work in Brazil it was generally believed that Slavery would come to a final and peaceful end within twenty years. The speaker closed by paying a high tribute to the rare qualities of head and heart which distinguish the present Emperor of Brazil and render him the greatest and best monarch now living. He also spoke of an interview which the Emperor permitted him to hold with the two Imperial Princessess-aged 15 and 17 -- during which they acknowledged with gratitude the beautiful present of copies of the Bible and Pilgrim's Progress, sent them by some ladies of New-York. The lecture was listened to with great attention by an appreciative audience, and was well worthy of a more extended report than our limited space permits us to give. The subject will be continued in future lectures before the samo Association.

abstract: ARREST OF A NOTORIOUS COUNTERFEITER AND SEIZURE OF $26,000 in BILLS. -- Detective DENTON yesterday arrested a well-known counterfeiter, named JEREY COWSDEN, alias COLEMAN, alias SMITH, on the charge of manufacturing counterfeit $5 bills, purporting to be issues of the Westfield Bank, of Westfield, Mass. The officer had been "on the lay" for COWSDEN for the past three weeks. He ascertained that he resided at No. 4 Verandah-place, South Brooklyn, and observed a light in the attic every night, where it was supposed he carried on the business of manufacturing bills. Having obtained sufficient evidence to arrest him, the officer watched the Post-office, and took him into custody, after calling for some letters, and locked him up. Detective DENTON. accompanied by Detective FROST, then proceeded to his residence and found a complete printing office in the attic story, consisting of presses, rollers, types, plates, dyes, and all other materials necessary in the manufacture of bills, together with $26,000 in printed money, and several reams of paper wetted down and ready for working off. A young man, engaged by COWSDEN at $3 per day for doing the mechanical work, was found in the office, and also taken into custody. The materials were taken possession of by the Police. The prepared bills are all finely executed on good paper, and will readily pass for genuine. The vignette, on the upper right corner, represents the village of Westfield; near the left upper corner is the word "Five," in Roman characters; on the lower right corner is the figure "5," and on the left side of the bill is represented a black-smith with an anvil, a seaman, two females, and a child with a spinning-wheel. COWSDEN is said to be an old offender, and well known by the Police for some years as being engaged in the counterfeiting business.
